\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheaf of Continuous Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X;Y}(U):=\{f:U\to Y\mid f\text{ is continuous}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;Y}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, more is true: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;Y}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function, then by restriction to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we get continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:U_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=f_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if we are given continuous maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:U_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 that agree on the overlaps (that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=f_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) then there is a unique set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and it is continuous.
 Indeed, for any open 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)\cap U_{i}=f_{i}^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\widehat{\mathbb{N}}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X;W}^{\alpha}(U):=\{f:U\to W\mid f\text{ is }C^{\alpha}\text{ map}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;W}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 It is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheaf of Holomorphic Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X;W}(U):=\mathcal{O}_{X;W}^{\text{hol}}(U):=\{f\colon U\to W\mid f\text{ is holomorphic}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X;W}$
\end_inset

 (with the usual restriction maps) is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constant Sheaf
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 We define a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{E}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with value 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\series default
, by setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{E}(U)=\begin{cases}
E & \text{if }U\text{ non-empty}\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and letting the restriction maps be the identity map.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves are determined by their values on a basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{B}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If we know what 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 is fo of a sheaf on every element 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, then we can use the sheaf property to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(V)$
\end_inset

 on an arbitrary open set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We simply cover 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 by elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Here is a more systematic way of saying this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{F}(V) & =\left\{ (s_{U})_{U}\in\prod_{\substack{U\in\mathscr{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U)\mid\text{for }U'\subseteq U\text{ both in }\mathcal{B}\text{ we have }s_{U}|_{U'}=s_{U'}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{\substack{U\in\mathscr{B}\\
U\subseteq V
}
}\mathcal{F}(U).\label{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using this observation, we see that it suffices to define a sheaf on a basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 of open sets of the topology of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 as a full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

, then a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Every such presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafdefinedonbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the presheaf of bounded continuous functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is not a sheaf.
 Indeed, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=(i,i+2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=x|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and there is no bounded continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{\mathbb{R};\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propgluingsheaves}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that for each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 of indices we are given isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ij}\colon\mathcal{F}_{j}|_{U_{ij}}\to\mathcal{F}_{i}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 satisfying for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k\in I$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cocycle condition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ik}=\varphi_{ij}\circ\varphi_{jk}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined up to unique isomorphism by these conditions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of collections of sections which are locally compatible:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})_{i\in I}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i}\cap U)\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}\cap U}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}\cap U}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} \label{eq:gluingsheaf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction maps are defined pointwise.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{V}=(s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap V})$
\end_inset

.
 The cocycle ensures that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gluingsheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:gluingsheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has the slightly simpler description:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)=\left\{ (s_{i})\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})\mid s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i,i'})_{i\in I}\in\mathcal{F}(U{}_{i'})$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(s_{i,i'})|_{U_{ii'j'}}=(s_{i,j'})|_{U_{ii'j'}}\label{eq:sheafsectjklfsdl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that there exists a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{U_{i'}}=(s_{i,i'})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafsectjklfsdl})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 says for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,i'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}=s_{i,j'}|_{U_{ii'j'}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i',j'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{ii'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf to obtain a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ii'}}=s_{i,i'}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we obtain a unique sequence of sections 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{F}_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})|_{U_{i'}}=(s_{i,i'})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes uniqueness, so the only thing left to do is to check that
 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{iji'}\}_{i'\in I'}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{i}|_{U_{iji'}} & =s_{i,i'}|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j,i'})|_{U_{iji'}}\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j,i'}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j}|_{U_{iji'}})\\
 & =\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{iji'}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i'\in I'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by the uniqueness part in the sheaf axiom (for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}$
\end_inset

), we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{ij}(s_{j})|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{i})\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 as claimed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{i}(U)$
\end_inset

, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s)=(\varphi_{ji}(s|_{U_{j}\cap U}))_{j\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{j})_{j\in I}\in\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}(U)$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}((s_{j})_{j\in I})=s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(s|_{V})=\psi_{i}(s)|_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 We repeat this construction for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 to get an isomorpism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}:\mathcal{F}_{i}\to\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 follows from a direct calculation: for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{j}(U_{ij})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi_{i}\circ\varphi_{ij})(s) & =\psi_{i}(\varphi_{ij}(s))\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s)|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{ki}(\varphi_{ij}(s))|_{U_{ijk}}){}_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s)|_{U_{ijk}})_{k\in I}\\
 & =(\varphi_{kj}(s|_{U_{ijk}}))_{k\in I}\\
 & =\psi_{j}(s).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, there exists a smallest neighborhood containing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can determine the sheaf completely by computing the values of the
 sheaf on these open sets.
 Indeed, then if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{x\in X}U_{x}$
\end_inset

 where the union is disjoint.
 Therefore the sheaf axiom tells us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)\cong\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}(U_{x}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of course is that almost all of the topolgical spaces we are
 interested in won't have a smallest open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Another way of saying this is that the limit of the diagram which consists
 of all open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 will not exist.
 On the other hand, colimits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

 do exist, so there's nothing stopping us from looking at colimits in the
 diagram of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-images of neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(S)$
\end_inset

 to be the full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 whose objects are open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms are inclusions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we will denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(\{x\})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 By restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(S)$
\end_inset

, we obtain a contravariant functor (which we again denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

) from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(S)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}(S)^{\mathrm{op}}$
\end_inset

 is filtered since for any two neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\supseteq U$
\end_inset

 (namely 
\begin_inset Formula $U=U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

) and since there is only one morphism between any two objects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
stalk 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

, to be the filtered colimit
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}=\mathrm{colim}_{U\in\mathbf{N}(x)}\mathcal{F}(U).
\]

\end_inset

More concretely, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{x}=\left\{ (U,s)\mid U\text{ is an open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }s\in\mathcal{F}(U)\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},s_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},s_{2})$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}|_{U}=s_{2}|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{x}$
\end_inset

, or even more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is understood from context.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
germs
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 When we don't need to choose a particular representative for a germ at
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then we often use Greek letters like 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 to denote germs at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 we obtain a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mapsto[s]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we obtain a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}:=\mathrm{colim}_{U\in\mathbf{U}(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{x}([U,s]_{x})=[U,\varphi_{U}(s)]_{x}
\]

\end_inset

This map is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 commutes with restriction maps.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the category of sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf of functions, one should think of the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 as the set of functions defined in some unspecified open neighborhood of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is any category in which filtered colimits exist (for instance the category
 of groups, of rings, of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, or 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras, etc...), then the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 and we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 to the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us make this more precise for a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of groups.
 The group law of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)\sim(W,s|_{W})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,t)\sim(W,t_{W})$
\end_inset

 and the product 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 is the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,(s|_{W})(t|_{W}))$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way addition and multiplication is defined on the stalk for
 a sheaf of rings.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of real analytic functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,f]_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is a germ at
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

, we there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}$
\end_inset

 is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}\in V$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{y})=f(\boldsymbol{x})+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(\boldsymbol{x})(y_{i}-x_{i})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(\boldsymbol{x})(y_{i_{1}}-x_{i_{1}})\cdots(y_{i_{k}}-x{}_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

Two real analytic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined in open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 agree on some open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 if and only if they have the same Taylor expansion around 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a well-defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n},p}\to$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of continuous functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{ev}_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(\text{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Stalk of the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X,x}=\left\{ (U,f)\mid U\text{ is and open neighborhood of }x\text{ and }f:U\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is continuous}\right\} /\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)\sim(V,g)$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 of a continuous function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x):=f(x)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{x}:\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad s\mapsto s(x),
\]

\end_inset

which is surjective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 contains in particular the germs of all constant functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}:=\text{Ker}(e_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 We claim that this is the unique maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring with maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove this, we need to show that the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{C}_{X,x}\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,f)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By shrinking 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous (take 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash f^{-1}\{0\})\cap U$
\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 denote the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X;W}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Inded, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 By the very same argument as in the example above, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the stability of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 property under composition and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto1/x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Working With Stalks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following result will be used very often.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop3.18}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi,\psi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be two morphisms of presheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are both sheaves, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are equal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[U^{x},s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x}=[V^{x},t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 are two germs in at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi_{U^{x}}(s)]_{x}=[\varphi_{V^{x}}(t)]_{x}$
\end_inset

 which implies there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x}\subseteq U^{x}\cap V^{x}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{W^{x}}(s|_{W^{x}})=\varphi_{W^{x}}(t|_{W^{x}}).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{W^{x}}$
\end_inset

 is injective, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{W^{x}}=t|_{W^{x}}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are two sections in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\varphi_{U}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $s=t$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is injective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 .
 By 1, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x}=[U,t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, there exists a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s]_{x})=\varphi_{x}([t]_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 By 1, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be a section over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, there exists a germ 
\begin_inset Formula $[s^{x}]_{x}=[U^{x},s^{x}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}([s^{x}]_{x})=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 with a smaller open set if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in U$
\end_inset

, denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{xy}=U^{x}\cap U^{y}$
\end_inset

 and observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}) & =\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =(t|_{U^{x}})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =t|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =(t|_{U^{y}})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{y}}(s^{y})|_{U^{xy}}\\
 & =\varphi_{U^{xy}}(s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{x}|_{U^{xy}}=s^{y}|_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this implies there exists a unique section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U^{x}}=s^{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})=t|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[U,s]_{x}$
\end_inset

 be a germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\psi_{U}(s)$
\end_inset

, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{x}([s]_{x}) & =[\varphi_{U}(s)]_{x}\\
 & =[\psi_{U}(s)]_{x}\\
 & =\psi_{x}([s]_{x}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}=\psi_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be a section over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi_{U}(s)]_{x}=[\psi_{U}(s)]_{x}$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}=\psi_{U}(s)|_{U^{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U^{x}\}_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}(s)=\psi_{U}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We call a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves 
\series bold
injective 
\series default
(respectively 
\series bold
surjective
\series default
, respectively 
\series bold
bijective
\series default
) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 A sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] & 
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi "]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{H} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

of morphisms of sheaves of groups is called 
\series bold
exact 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the induced sequence of stalks 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F}_x 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi _x "] & 
\backslash
mathcal{G}_x 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
psi _x"]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{H}_x 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is an exact sequence of groups.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively bijective) for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 On ther other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 there exist an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) and sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U_{i}}(s_{i})=t|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective if locally we can find a preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 is surjective for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we needed injectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U^{xy}}$
\end_inset

 in order to patch up the various local sections.
 Here is an example from complex analysis which demonstrates this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the sheaf of holomorphic functions on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 For every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{U}(f)=f'$
\end_inset

 be the derivative.
 .
 We obtain a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}$
\end_inset

 is surjective because locally every holomorphic function has a primitive.
 On the other hand, there exists open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 which have no primitive on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, take 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{C}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=1/z$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a primitive of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 be the path defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=e^{2\pi it}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =F(1)-F(1)\\
 & =F(\gamma(1))-F(\gamma(0))\\
 & =\int_{\gamma}f(z)\mathrm{d}z\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}f(\gamma(t))\gamma'(t)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{1}{e^{2\pi it}}2\pi i\cdot e^{2\pi it}\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}2\pi i\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =2\pi i,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is obviously a contradiction.
 The issue here comes from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)\cong\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental group of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, by complex analysis we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{U}$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if every connected component of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is simply connected (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}(U)=0)$
\end_inset

.
 The sufficiency of this condition will also be an immediate application
 of cohomologial methods developed later.
 We obtain an exact sequence of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathbb{C}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota "]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
mathrm{D}"]  & 
\backslash
mathcal{O}_X 
\backslash
arrow[r]  & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{X}$
\end_inset

 denotes the sheaf of locally constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{U}$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) if and only
 if its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{U_{i}}\colon\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}\to\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 to morphisms of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is injective (respectively surjective, respectively bijective) for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this is because these notions are defined via the stalks.
 However note that the existence of the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is crucial: there exists sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are not isomorphic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheafification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a functorial way to attach to a presheaf a sheaf:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propsheafification}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\widetilde{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}\colon\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves which satisfies the following universal mapping
 property: for all sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

, in other words, the following diagram is commutative:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramsheafification}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} "] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
varphi ", swap] & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi }"]  
\backslash

\backslash
   & 
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, the map of stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}:\mathcal{F}_{x}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and every morphism of presheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\mathcal{\widetilde{F}\to\widetilde{G}}$
\end_inset

 making the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramsheafification}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathcal{F} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
varphi ", swap] & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{F}} 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi }"]  
\backslash

\backslash
  
\backslash
mathcal{G} 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
iota _{
\backslash
mathcal{G}} "]  & 
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
mathcal{G}} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a functor from the category of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the category of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 (equipped with the canonical morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

) is called the 
\series bold
sheafification 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 which we call the 
\series bold
sheafification 
\series default
functor.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let's discuss why we are justified in saying 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
the 
\emph default
sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The point is that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is unique up to unique isomorphism.
 Indeed, let us simplify notation by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F}',\iota')$
\end_inset

 is another pair which satisfies the universal mapping property, then there
 exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota'}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{F}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota'}\circ\iota=\iota'$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\colon\mathcal{F}'\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\circ\iota'=\iota$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota'}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism whose inverse is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\circ\widetilde{\iota'}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism which satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\widetilde{\iota}\circ\widetilde{\iota'})\circ\iota & =\widetilde{\iota}\circ(\widetilde{\iota'}\circ\iota)\\
 & =\widetilde{\iota}\circ\iota'\\
 & =\iota.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\circ\widetilde{\iota'}=1_{\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}}$
\end_inset

 by the uniqueness part of the universal mapping property.
 A similar argument shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota'}\circ\widetilde{\iota}=1_{\mathcal{F}'}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is already a sheaf, then we can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},1_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 (using the unique isomorphism) and say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is the sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 since the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},1_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 clearly satisfies the universal mapping property.
 A similar line of reasoning also justifies our calling the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
the 
\emph default
sheafification functor (since this functor is unique up to unique natural
 isomorphism).
 In the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 below, we will give a construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the families of elements in the stalks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, which locally give rise to sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U) & :=\left\{ (\sigma_{x})_{x\in U}\in\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}\Biggm|\begin{array}{c}
\text{for all }y\in U\text{ there exists an open neighborhood }U_{y}\subseteq U\text{ of }y\text{ \text{and an s_{y}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{y})}}\\
\text{such that for all }x\in U_{y}\text{ the germ }\sigma_{x}\text{ can be represented by }(U_{y},s_{y})
\end{array}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The restriction maps are defined pointwise.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 is a smaller open set, then we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((\sigma_{x})_{x\in U})|_{V}=(\sigma_{x})_{x\in V}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf.
 To see why it is a sheaf, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U_{i}}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((\sigma_{x})_{x\in U_{i}})|_{U_{ij}}=(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U_{ij}}=((\sigma_{x})_{x\in U_{j}})|_{U_{ij}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 is the unique element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((\sigma_{x})_{x\in U})|_{U_{i}}=(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is clearly a sheaf (note that the same proof also shows that presheaf given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $U\mapsto\prod_{x\in U}\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf).
 Next we define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\mathcal{F}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota(s)=([U,s]_{x})_{x\in U}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us check that the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the universal mapping property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}(s)=([U,s]_{x})_{x\in U}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We simplify notation by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 Now fix a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{y}\colon\mathcal{F}_{y}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{y}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 We do this in two steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{y}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
is injective
\series default
: let 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{y}=[U,s]_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{y}=[V,t]_{y}$
\end_inset

 be two germs in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{y}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[([s]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{y}=[([t]_{x})_{x\in V})]_{y}.
\]

\end_inset

Then there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $([s]_{x})_{x\in W}=([t]_{x})_{x\in W}$
\end_inset

, or in other words, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{y}=[t]_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{y}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{y}$
\end_inset

 is surjective
\series default
: let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U}]_{y}$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{y}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{y}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U^{y})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}=[U^{y},s^{y}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U^{y}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\iota_{y}([U^{y},s^{y}]_{y}) & =[U^{y},([U^{y},s^{y}]_{x})_{x\in U^{y}}]_{y}\\
 & =[U^{y},(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U^{y}}]_{y}\\
 & =[U,(\sigma_{x})_{x\in U}]_{y}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{y}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove the two properties stated in the proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}\colon\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 First we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x_{0}}=[U,s]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x_{0}}=[V,t]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be two germs in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[([s]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}=[([t]_{x})_{x\in V})]_{x_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset

Then there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $([s]_{x})_{x\in W}=([t]_{x})_{x\in W}$
\end_inset

, or in other words, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}=[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x_{0}}=[t]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 be a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, using the construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

, we can find a better representative for this germ: choose an open neighborhood
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and choose a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s^{x}]_{x}=[s_{0}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $[([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U})]_{x_{0}}=[([s_{0}]_{x})_{x\in U_{0}})]_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}([s_{0}]_{x_{0}})=[([s_{0}]_{x})_{x\in U_{0}})]_{x_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}:\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and define the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\left(([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\right)=([\varphi_{U^{x}}(s^{x})]_{x})_{x\in U}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $([s^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that this gives rise a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves.
 Furthermore, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\iota_{\mathcal{F},U}(s) & =\widetilde{\varphi}_{U}\left(([s]_{x})_{x\in U}\right)\\
 & =([\varphi_{U}(x)]_{x})_{x\in U}\\
 & =\iota_{\mathcal{G},U}(\varphi_{U}(s))\\
 & =\iota_{\mathcal{G},U}\varphi_{U}(s).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\varphi$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 makes the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagramsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism making the diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{diagramsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 commutative.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is another morphism making the diagram commute, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\varphi=\widetilde{\varphi}\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}_{x}\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}=\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{F},x}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}_{x}=\widetilde{\psi}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}=\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we assume in addition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}\colon\mathcal{G}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, which is bijective on stalks, is an isomorphism by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop3.18})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus we can define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'=\iota_{\mathcal{G}}^{-1}\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 and it is easily seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\iota_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

 is a formal consequence from the universal mapping property.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheafification is left adjoint to the forgetful functor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmahomshpsh}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\mathcal{G})\longleftrightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}(X)}(\mathcal{F},\mathcal{G})\label{eq:sheafificationforgetful}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the sheafification functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 is the left adjoint to the forgetful functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the sheafification functor preserves all colimits whereas
 the forgetful functor preserves all limits.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\colon\widetilde{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}'\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then we 
\emph on
define 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\widetilde{\varphi}'\iota_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Functoriality in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is an easy exercise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that the bijection 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:sheafificationforgetful})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 restricts to a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(\widetilde{\mathcal{F}},\mathcal{G})\longleftrightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(\mathcal{F},\mathcal{G}),
\]

\end_inset

which is again functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, viewing the sheafification/forgetful functors as functors from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to itself, we see that sheafification preserves all colimits and the forgetful
 functor preserves all limits.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is any diagram in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{lim}(D)$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sheafification of a presheaf of functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Define a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\mathcal{F}}(U)=\left\{ f\colon U\to E\mid\text{there exists an open covering }\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}\text{ of }U\text{ such that }f|_{U_{i}}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})\text{ for all }i\in I\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 with the restriction maps of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 being the usual ones.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 (equipped with the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\mathcal{F}\to\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

) is the sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the universal mapping property.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\widehat{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U_{i}}(f|_{U_{i}})\in\mathcal{G}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, furthermore we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{U_{i}}(f|_{U_{i}})|_{U_{ij}}=\varphi_{U_{ij}}(f|_{U_{ij}})=\varphi_{U_{j}}(f|_{U_{j}})|_{U_{ij}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(f)\in\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}(f)|_{U_{i}}=\varphi_{U_{i}}(f|_{U_{i}})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This construction does not depend on the choice of an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 In particular, we have a well defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto\widetilde{\varphi}(f)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morhpism which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\circ\iota=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let's construct an explicit isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $([U^{x},f^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 together with a section 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{x}\in\mathcal{F}(V^{x})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[f^{y}]_{y}=[g^{x}]_{y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{x,y}\subseteq U^{y}\cap V^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{y}|_{W^{x,y}}=g^{x}|_{W^{x,y}}$
\end_inset

.
 Define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon U\to E$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=g^{x}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is independent of our choice of the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(W^{x,y},V^{x},g^{x})$
\end_inset

 for if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{W}^{x,y},\widetilde{V}^{x},\widetilde{g}^{x})$
\end_inset

 were another such triple, then we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}^{x}(x)=f^{x}(x)=g^{x}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W^{x,y}\}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{W^{x,y}}=g^{x}|_{W^{x,y}}$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(z) & =g^{z}(z)\\
 & =f^{z}(z)\\
 & =g^{x}(z)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in W^{x,y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g|_{W^{x,y}}=f^{y}|_{W^{x,y}}\in\mathcal{F}(W^{x,y})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\widehat{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we obtain map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}(U)\to\widehat{\mathcal{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $([f^{x}]_{x})_{x\in U}\mapsto g$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that this map induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\mathcal{F}}\cong\widehat{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the constant presheaf with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 to be the sheaf of locally constant functions with value 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{X}(U)=\{f\colon U\to E\mid f\text{ is locally constant}\}.
\]

\end_inset

for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This is the sheafification of the presheaf of constant functions with values
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
constant sheaf 
\series default
with values in
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Direct and Inverse Images of Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=f(y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Direct Image 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 to be the presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 whose values on opens 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{*}\mathcal{G}(U)=\mathcal{G}(f^{-1}(U)),
\]

\end_inset

and whose restriction maps are given by the restriction maps of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
direct image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{G}'$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then we obtain a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}(\varphi):f_{*}\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{G}'$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}(\varphi)_{U}=\varphi_{f^{-1}(U)}$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that we obtain a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{*}\colon\mathbf{Psh}(Y)\to\mathbf{Psh}(X),
\]

\end_inset

called the 
\series bold
direct image functor along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this follows from the the sheaf property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 together with the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f^{-1}(U_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 .
 Thus, the direct image functor restricts to a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{*}:\mathbf{Sh}(Y)\to\mathbf{Sh}(X).
\]

\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\pi_{\mathcal{G},y}$
\end_inset

 to be the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon(f_{*}\mathcal{G})_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{y}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi([U,t]_{x})=[f^{-1}(U),t]_{y}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in f_{*}\mathcal{G}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this map is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $t'\in f_{*}\mathcal{G}(U')$
\end_inset

 was another representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{x}$
\end_inset

, then there'd exist 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq U'\cap U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t|_{f^{-1}U}=t''=t'|_{f^{-1}U'}$
\end_inset

, but this would also mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(f^{-1}(U'))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t'\in\mathcal{G}(f^{-1}(U'))$
\end_inset

 represent the same germ 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{y}=[t'']_{y}=[t']_{y}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{y}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U'')\subseteq f^{-1}(U')\cap f^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism between commutative rings 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces a morphism of scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

.
 The underlying map of topological spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathfrak{q})=\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathrm{D}(s)}^{\flat}=\varphi_{s}$
\end_inset

 for all principal opens 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(s)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, given 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A$
\end_inset

, the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{s}\colon A_{s}\to B_{s}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{s}(a/s^{m})=\varphi(a)/s^{m}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=f(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

, then the homomorphisms of local rings 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathfrak{q}}^{\#}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,\mathfrak{p}}\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathfrak{q}}^{\#}=\rho_{\mathfrak{q}}\circ\varphi_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\mathfrak{p}}\colon A_{\mathfrak{p}}\to B_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{\mathfrak{p}}(a/s)=\varphi(a)/s
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathfrak{q}}\colon B_{\mathfrak{p}}\to B_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical localization map.
 We also have the extension of residue fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathfrak{q}}\colon\kappa(\mathfrak{p})\to\kappa(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(\mathfrak{p})=A_{\mathfrak{p}}\slash\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(\mathfrak{q})=B_{\mathfrak{q}}\slash\mathfrak{q}B_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

-module.
 This gives rise to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{N}$
\end_inset

 which is defined on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(b)\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{N}(\mathrm{D}(b))=N_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 What does the direct image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{N}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 look like? Well for an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(a)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U)=\mathrm{D}(\varphi(a))$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\widetilde{N}(\mathrm{D}(a))=N_{\varphi(a)}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\widetilde{N}=\widetilde{N_{\varphi}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propdirectstalk}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an open embedding, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon(f_{*}\mathcal{G})_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{y}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}=\widetilde{\pi}_{\mathcal{G},y}\colon\mathcal{G}_{y}\to(f_{*}\mathcal{G})_{x}$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\pi}[V,t]_{y}=[f(V),t]_{x}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this map makes sense because 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(f(V))=V$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an open embedding.
 This map is clearly the inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse Image
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
pre-pullback of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\series default
 by setting
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{+}\mathcal{F}(V)=\mathrm{colim}_{U\in\mathbf{N}(f(V))}\mathcal{F}(U).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 is open, and letting the restriction maps be the ones induces from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 More concretely, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{+}\mathcal{F}(V)=\left\{ (U,s)\mid\text{ is an open neighborhood of }f(V)\text{ in }X\text{ and }s\in\mathcal{F}(U)\right\} \slash\sim,
\]

\end_inset

where two pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U',s')$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $U''\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)\subseteq U''\subseteq U\cap U'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U''}=s'|_{V''}$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

 will be denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]_{f(V)}$
\end_inset

, or even more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{f(V)}$
\end_inset

 when it is clear from context that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a section over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{f(V)}$
\end_inset

 is a section that lives over 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a section that lives over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V'\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 is open such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V'\subseteq V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[s]_{f(V)}|_{V'}=[s]_{f(V')}.
\]

\end_inset

This makes sense because 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V')\subseteq f(V)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 The sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
pullback of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
by
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and hence of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

; hence we obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\colon\mathbf{Psh}(X)\to\mathbf{Sh}(Y)$
\end_inset

 which restrict to a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\colon\mathbf{Sh}(X)\to\mathbf{Sh}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

-modules respectively, then we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}\mathcal{F}=f^{-1}\mathcal{F}\otimes_{\mathcal{O}_{X}}\mathcal{O}_{Y}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, given an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 and an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{V}=\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{U}=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{U}=\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is the sheafification of the presheaf
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\mapsto\mathrm{colim}_{U\supseteq f(V)}M_{U}\otimes_{A_{U}}B.
\]

\end_inset

In the context of rings, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathrm{D}(t)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then an open 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(s)$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathrm{D}(t))$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in f(\mathrm{D}(t))$
\end_inset

 meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\notin\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}(s)$
\end_inset

 meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $s\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\varphi(s)$
\end_inset

 say, then we can't have 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in B$
\end_inset

.
 What does it mean to say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in f(\mathrm{D}(t))$
\end_inset

? It means there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}|\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t\notin\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{2}$
\end_inset

 both lie over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathfrak{q}_{1}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $t\notin\mathfrak{q}_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in f(\mathrm{D}(t))$
\end_inset

 even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{1}\notin\mathrm{D}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an open continuous map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\mathcal{G}(U)=\mathcal{G}(f(U))$
\end_inset

 for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and letting the restrictions maps on 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be the ones induced from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have isomorphisms
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{+}\mathcal{G}\simeq f^{*}\mathcal{G}\simeq f^{-1}\mathcal{G},
\]

\end_inset

all of which are natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{f(U)}=[V,t]_{f(U)}$
\end_inset

 be a germ at 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is a section over 
\begin_inset Formula $V\supseteq f(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon f^{+}\mathcal{G}\to f^{\star}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho([t]_{f(U)})=t|_{f(U)}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a section over 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon f^{\star}\mathcal{G}\to f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota(t_{0})=[t_{0}]_{f(U)}.
\]

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 are both morphisms of presheaves and that they are inverse to each other.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathcal{G}}=\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathcal{G}}=\iota$
\end_inset

 are clearly both natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{X}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}=f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of an open subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $U=X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then for every sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 open, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}|_{U}(U')=\mathcal{G}(U')$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propinversestalk}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})_{x}\cong\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{+}\mathcal{G}_{x}\cong\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propsheafification})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}\colon(f^{+}\mathcal{G})_{x}\to\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $[[t]_{f(U)}]_{x}=[U,[V,t]_{f(U)}]_{x}$
\end_inset

 be an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(f^{+}\mathcal{G})_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}([[t]_{f(U)}]_{x})=[t]_{f(x)}.
\]

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 The inverse map is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\mathcal{G},x}^{-1}([t]_{f(x)})=[[t]_{f(f^{-1}(U))}]_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=^{\mathrm{a}}\phi$
\end_inset

 .
 Recall that the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse-Direct Image Adjointness 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a preasheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Given a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon f^{+}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 be open and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be a section in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\varphi^{\flat})t=\varphi([t]_{ff^{-1}V}),\label{eq:pushfjdlksfjlkds-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $ff^{-1}V=f(f^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{\flat})t=(\varphi_{V}^{\flat})(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi([t]_{ff^{-1}V})=\varphi_{f^{-1}V}([t]_{ff^{-1}V})$
\end_inset

 in order to suppress notation.
 This gives rise to a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-)^{\flat}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}\,X}(f^{+}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F})\to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}\,Y}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F}).
\]

\end_inset

The idea behind our notation is that one thinks of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:pushfjdlksfjlkds-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as applying the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

associative law
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by pushing the parenthesis forward (which matches up with the idea that
 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 takes the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and pushes it forward to a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

).
 Applying the associative law in this case has the effect of removing 
\begin_inset Formula $\flat$
\end_inset

 in the superscript and introducing 
\begin_inset Formula $ff^{-1}V$
\end_inset

 in the superscript.
 f We now want to define an inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 which we will denote by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-)^{\#}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}\,Y}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F})\to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}\,X}(f^{+}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}).
\]

\end_inset

Given a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, we define a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\#}\colon f^{+}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 be open such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)\subseteq V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be a section in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi^{\#}([t]_{fU})=(\psi t)|_{U}\label{eq:fsjlkdsjfksd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi t=\psi(t)$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $fU=f(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\#}=\psi_{U}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 in order to suppress notation.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi t$
\end_inset

 lives in 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\mathcal{F}(V)=\mathcal{F}(f^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

, so restricting this section to 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is meaningful, however keep in mind that we can't bring 
\begin_inset Formula $|_{U}$
\end_inset

 inside the parenthesis since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and are associative with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (not 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 Again, the idea behind here is that one thinks of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as applying the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

associative law
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by pulling the parenthesis back (which matches up with the idea that 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\#}$
\end_inset

 takes the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and pulls it back to a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\#}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

).
 The associative law in this case has the effect of removing 
\begin_inset Formula $\#$
\end_inset

 in the superscript and replacing the 
\begin_inset Formula $_{fU}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 One of the main benefits that we get with our notation is that it is very
 easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\#}$
\end_inset

 are inverse to each other.
 For instance, given 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as above, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi^{\flat})^{\#}([t]_{fU}) & =((\varphi^{\flat})t)|_{U}\\
 & =(\varphi([t]_{ff^{-1}V}))|_{U}\\
 & =\varphi([t]_{ff^{-1}V})|_{U})\\
 & =\varphi([t]_{fU}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last part follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (so we could bring the 
\begin_inset Formula $|_{U}$
\end_inset

 inside the parenthesis) and 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{ff^{-1}V}|_{U}=[t]_{fU}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}V\supseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
((\psi^{\#})^{\flat})t & =\psi^{\#}([t]_{ff^{-1}V})\\
 & =(\psi t)|_{f^{-1}V}\\
 & =\psi t,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last part follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi t$
\end_inset

 lives over 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}V$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-)^{\#}$
\end_inset

 are natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propadjunctiondirectinverse}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}(X)}(f^{+}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}) & \longleftrightarrow & \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}(Y)}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F})\\
\varphi & \to & \varphi^{\flat}\\
\psi^{\#} & \leftarrow & \psi
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, then this restricts to a bijection
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sh}(X)}(f^{-1}\mathcal{G},\mathcal{F}) & \longleftrightarrow & \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Psh}(Y)}(\mathcal{G},f_{*}\mathcal{F})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the pullback functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\colon\mathbf{Psh}\,Y\to\mathbf{Sh}\,X$
\end_inset

 is left adjoint to the pushforward functor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}\colon\mathbf{Sh}\,X\to\mathbf{Psh}\,Y$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 preserves colimits while 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}$
\end_inset

 preserves limits.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will almost never use the concrete description of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 in the sequel.
 Very often we are given 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, and a morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then usually it is sufficient to understand for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{x}^{\#}\colon\mathcal{G}_{f(x)}\to(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})_{x}\cong\mathcal{F}_{x},
\]

\end_inset

induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}\colon f^{-1}\mathcal{G}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on stalks.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sheaves and Etale Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
