\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break 
\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let's take a moment to reflect on this image, because it will serve as a
 nice visualization tool for other categories.
 For each element 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

, there is an associated set 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

, which is just the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{-1}(s)=E_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{fiber}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that for any distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $s,s'\in S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}\cap E_{s'}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{s}E_{s}=E$
\end_inset

.
 We also have functions 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

, which is just the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The commutativity condition for morphisms in the slice category tells us
 that a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(E,p)\to(E',p')$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(E_{s})\subseteq E'_{s}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 The whole structure is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{bundle}$
\end_inset

 of sets over the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{base space}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 being called the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{total space}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 being called the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{projection}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Etale Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be topological spaces.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{local homeomorphism}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to X$
\end_inset

 with the additional property that for each point 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in E$
\end_inset

 there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{e}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{e})$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 restricts to a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{U_{e}}:U_{e}\to\pi(U_{e})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Intuitively, a local homeomorphism preserves 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local structure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is locally compact if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(B)$
\end_inset

 is.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to X$
\end_inset

 be a local homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in U$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{e}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{e})$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 restricts to a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{U_{e}}:U_{e}\to p(U_{e})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{e}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{e}$
\end_inset

, and since homeomorphisms are open maps, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{U_{e}}(U\cap U_{e})$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{e})$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{e})$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U\cap U_{e})$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 too.
 Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcup\limits _{e\in U}\pi(U\cap U_{e})=\pi(U),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a discrete space, then the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\times X\to X$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism.
 On the other hand, the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times X\to X$
\end_inset

 is never a local homeomorphism, because no product neighborhood is projected
 homeomorphically into 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For much the same reason, a nontrivial vector bundle is never a locally
 homeomorphism either.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{etale space}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an object 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\pi)\in\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Etale}(X)$
\end_inset

 to be the full subcategory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

 whose objects are etale spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms being the same as in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An equivalence of categories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the main theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 there is a pair of adjoint functors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
mathbf{Top} / X 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
Gamma ", shift left = 1] & 
\backslash
mathbf{Set}^{O(X)^{op}} 
\backslash
arrow[l, " 
\backslash
varLambda ", shift left=1] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 assigns to each object in 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\pi)\in\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

, the sheaf of all sections 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, while its left adjoint 
\begin_inset Formula $\varLambda$
\end_inset

 assigns to each preasheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, the etale space 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{\mathcal{F}},\pi_{\mathcal{F}})$
\end_inset

.
 There are natural transformations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{\mathcal{F}}:\mathcal{F}\to\Gamma\varLambda\mathcal{F}\qquad\epsilon_{E}:\varLambda\Gamma E\to E
\]

\end_inset

for a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and an object 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\pi)\in\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

 , which are unit and counit making 
\begin_inset Formula $\varLambda$
\end_inset

 a left adjoint for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, while if 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\pi)$
\end_inset

 is etale, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{E}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an object 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\pi)\in\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

, we can associate a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 as follows: for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U):=\{s:U\to E\mid s\text{ is continuous and }\pi|_{U}\circ s=\text{id}_{U}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For all inclusions of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

, we use the obvious restriction maps: if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(V)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U}\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf (and not just a presheaf).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=s_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We can construct an 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{i}}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, choose some 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 that has 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{i}$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)=s_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We need to check that this is well-defined (i.e.
 independent of the choice of neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

.
 Then because 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=s_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)=s_{j}(x)=s_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, this construction is well-defined.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is continous since if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s^{-1}(V)=\bigcup_{i\in I}s_{i}^{-1}(V)
\]

\end_inset

is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is a presheaf of functions.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
sheaf of sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break 
\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} 
\backslash
draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt},xshift=-4pt,yshift=0pt]
 (2.5,4) -- (2.5,7.2) node [black,midway,xshift=-1.2cm] (B)  {
\backslash
LARGE $F_p 
\backslash
text(U) $}; 
\backslash
node (S) at (1,-.3) {
\backslash
LARGE $X$}; 
\backslash
node (S'') at (3.6,-.3) {
\backslash
LARGE $U$}; 
\backslash
node (S') at (0.2,7) {
\backslash
LARGE $B$}; 
\backslash
node (z') at (7,0) {
\backslash
LARGE $)$}; 
\backslash
node (z) at (3,0) {
\backslash
LARGE $($}; 
\backslash
node (y) at (5,1) {}; 
\backslash
node (y') at (5,3) {}; 
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(3.2,7)(4,7.1)(5,6.9)(6,7.1)(6.8,7)(6.8,7)(6,7.1
)(5,6.9)(4,7.1)(3.2,7)}; 
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(3.2,6)(4,5.8)(5.5,6.2)(6.8,6)(6.8,6)(5.5,6.2)(4,
5.8)(3.2,6)}; 
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(3.2,5)(5,4.8)(6.8,5)(6.8,5)(5,4.8)(3.2,5)};
 
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(3.2,4)(5,4.2)(6.8,4)(6.8,4)(5,4.2)(3.2,4)};
 
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(1,0)(9,0)(9,0)(1,0)};  
\backslash
draw plot [smooth cycle] coordinates  {(0,4)(10,4)(10,7.5)(0,7.5)} ;  
\backslash
draw[-{Straight Barb[length=5pt,width=5pt]}] (y') edge[] node[right] {}
 (y); 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break 
\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(E,\pi)\to(E',\pi')$
\end_inset

 be a morphism in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Top}/X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}:\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)\to\mathcal{F}_{\pi'}(U)$
\end_inset

 to be the function that maps a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}_{\pi}(U)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ s$
\end_inset

.
 The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}$
\end_inset

 are the components of a natural transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\pi}\to\mathcal{F}_{\pi'}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have constructed a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma:\mbox{\mathbf{Top}}/X\to\mathbf{Sh}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Psh}(X)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Etale}(X)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathcal{F}}:=\coprod_{x\in X}\mathcal{F}_{x}=\bigcup_{x\in X}\left\{ (x,s_{0})\mid s_{0}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}:E_{\mathcal{F}}\to X$
\end_inset

 be the obvious projection map (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s)\mapsto x$
\end_inset

).
 For each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and section 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]=\{(x,s_{x})\mid x\in U\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 be the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 with the collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]$
\end_inset

 as a subbasis.
 We claim that the collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]$
\end_inset

 is actually a basis for this topology.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s],[V,t]\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},s_{x_{0}})\in[U,s]\cap[V,t]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in U\cap V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x_{0}}=t_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U_{0}}=t|_{U_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}=t_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[U_{0},s|_{U_{0}}]\subseteq[U,s]\cap[V,t]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}:E_{\mathcal{F}}\to X$
\end_inset

 a local homeomorphism with respect to this topology.
 To see why, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 maps basis elements to basis elements (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $[U,s]\mapsto U$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, it must be an open mapping.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s_{0})\in E_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

, then after choosing a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,s)$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,s_{0})\in[U,s]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{[U,s]}:[U,s]\to U$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi|_{[U,s]}$
\end_inset

 is an open mapping and a bijection, hence its inverse must be continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
co-unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:B\to X$
\end_inset

 be any local homeomorphism, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{p}$
\end_inset

 its sheaf of sections, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{F_{p}}:B_{F_{p}}\to X$
\end_inset

 the associated sheaf of germs.
 Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $k:B\to B_{F_{p}}$
\end_inset

 as follow: If 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

, there exist a local section 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, defined on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in s(V)$
\end_inset

 (we proved this earlier).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k(b)=(f(b),[s]_{f(b)})$
\end_inset

 be the germ of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b)$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(b)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on which section through 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is chosen (we proved this earlier too).
 This gives us the following commutative diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=small] B 
\backslash
arrow[dr,"p" swap] 
\backslash
arrow[rr,"k"] && B_{F_{p}} 
\backslash
arrow[dl," p_{F_{p}} "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & X 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Etale}(X)$
\end_inset

-arrow from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{F_{p}}$
\end_inset

, in fact, it is an iso.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{U}:F(U)\to F_{p_{F}}(U)$
\end_inset

 by putting, for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in F(U)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{U}(s)=s_{U}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{U}:U\to A_{F}$
\end_inset

 is defined by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{U}(x)=(x,[s]_{x})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of a Ringed Space and a Locally Ringed Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout the rest of this article, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\widehat{\mathbb{N}}_{0}=\mathbb{N}\cup\{0,\infty,\omega\}$
\end_inset

.
 Ringed spaces formalize the idea of giving a geometric object by specifying
 its underlying topological space and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

functions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on all open subsets of this space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then we simplify our notation and write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ringed space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-ringed space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 (or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is understood from context) the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X,x}:=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\slash\mathfrak{m}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 (or simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is understood from context) its residue field.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

, then its image in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a fixed open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then it is not necessarily true that every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, it is the case that every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

 for some open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 needs to be smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Usually we will denote a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Also if we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then it will be understood that its structure sheaf is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 (unless otherwise specified of course).
 Sometimes we may write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and in this case the structure sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions: For all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(U)=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\alpha}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 The same argument as for sheaves of continuous functions yields the following
 observation: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Another example comes from Algebraic Geometry:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be an algebraically closed field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is equipped with the Zariski topology.
 Recall that a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:U\to k$
\end_inset

 from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the field 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
regular 
\series default
at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 if there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and there are polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as follows: for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{\varphi:U\to k\mid\varphi\text{ is regular}\}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathcal{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 being a unit is a 
\emph on
local 
\emph default
property (it can be checked locally, just like how a continuous function
 can be checked locally).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring.
 Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is locally a unit, meaning there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $u|_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in\mathcal{O}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(u|_{U_{i}})v_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Since the restriction maps are algebra homomorphisms we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(u|_{U_{ij}})(v_{i}|_{U_{ij}}) & =((u|_{U_{i}})v_{i})|_{U_{ij}}\\
 & =1|_{U_{ij}}\\
 & =((u|_{U_{j}})v_{j})|_{U_{ij}}\\
 & =(u|_{U_{ij}})(v_{j}|_{U_{ij}})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 Since inverses are unique, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}|_{U_{ij}}=v_{j}|_{U_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathcal{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v|_{U_{i}}=v_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 But then locally we have 
\begin_inset Formula $uv-1=0$
\end_inset

, so the sheaf condintion again implies 
\begin_inset Formula $uv-1=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a (global) unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms of (Locally) Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The datum of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the datum of a homomorphism of sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}\colon f^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{Y}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propadjunctiondirectinverse})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In particular, usually we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\#})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are locally ringed spaces.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we obtain a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 which is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{x}([t]_{f(x)})=[f^{\flat}(t)]_{x}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $[t]_{f(x)}\in\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\series default
if each 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is
\series bold
 local
\series default
, meaning
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{x}(\mathfrak{m}_{f(x)})\subseteq\mathfrak{m}_{x}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 induces a nonzero homomorphism of residue fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\colon\kappa_{Y,f(x)}\to\kappa_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{x}(t(f(x)))=f^{\flat}(t)(x)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t(f(x))\in\kappa_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}$
\end_inset

 is necessarily an injective map: it realizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{Y,f(x)}$
\end_inset

 as a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X,x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{doesntmakesense})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 wasn't local, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\colon\kappa_{Y}(f(x))\to\kappa_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

 would just be the zero map.
 Thus the local condintion on 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 allows to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{Y}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 with the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\kappa_{Y}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)$
\end_inset

 is a section, then we can view it as a function whose value at 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $t(y)\in\kappa_{Y}(y)$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq y'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{Y}(y)$
\end_inset

 may not be the same field as 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{Y}(y')$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 really takes values in different fields), where 
\begin_inset Formula $t(y)$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 under the composite map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}\to\kappa_{Y}(y).
\]

\end_inset

Intuitively, the section 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}(t)\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(f^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}(t)$
\end_inset

 as functions, meaning
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{\flat}(t)(x)=t(f(x))=f^{*}(t)(x)\label{eq:doesntmakesense}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 However we need to be careful, because 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}(t)(x)\in\kappa_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}(t)(x)\in\kappa_{Y}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 belong to different fields in general.
 The key is that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 being a local homomorphism allows us to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{Y}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 with the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\kappa_{Y}(f(x))$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 With this identification in mind (for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

) we can make sense of the identity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{doesntmakesense})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general there exist locally ringed spaces and morphisms of ringed spaces
 between them that are not morphisms of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default
ringed spaces.
 For spaces with functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 functions such as the premanifolds defined below, we will see that every
 morphism of ringed spaces is automatically a morphism of locally ringed
 spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The composition of morphisms of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is defined in the obvious way using the compatibility of
 direct images with composition (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(g\circ f)_{*}=g_{*}\circ f_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the category of (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\#}$
\end_inset

) is an additional datum for a morphism.
 For instance it might happen that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the identity but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is not an isomorphism of sheaves.
 We will usually encounter the simpler case that the structure sheaf is
 a sheaf of functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is given by composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The following special case and its globalization is the main example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 defines by composition a morphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f_{U}^{\flat}:\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha}(U) & \longrightarrow & f_{*}(\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})(U)=\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha}(f^{-1}(U))\\
t & \mapsto & t\circ f
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The induced map on stalks 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}\to\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is then also given by composing an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which yields an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $t\circ f$
\end_inset

 defined in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat}):(X,\mathcal{C}_{X}^{\alpha})\to(Y,\mathcal{C}_{Y}^{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 be any morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We claim: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is automatically a morphism of 
\emph on
locally 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}=f^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show 1, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=f_{x}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathcal{C}_{X,x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathcal{C}_{Y,f(x)}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism of local 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}_{A}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\slash\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is automatically local, or equivalently that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces an injective homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\slash\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\hookrightarrow B\slash\mathfrak{m}_{B}=\mathbb{R},
\]

\end_inset

and as a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, it is automatically surjective (indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

), hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a field and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{B})$
\end_inset

 is the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us show 2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open set of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the commutative diagram of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\end_layout

