\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation maps are surjective.
 Hence there exists a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 making the lower rectangle commutative if and only if one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(\ker(\mathrm{ev}_{f(x)}))\subseteq\ker(\mathrm{ev}_{x})$
\end_inset

, but this latter condition is satisfied because 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is local by 1.
 Moreover, as a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\mathrm{id}_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we find 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{V}^{\flat}(t)(x)=t(f(x))=f_{V}^{\star}(t)(x)$
\end_inset

, which shows 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces is an isomorphism in the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of sheaves of rings.
 We claim that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}=\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}\circ f_{x}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathcal{O}_{X},x}$
\end_inset

 is the isomorphism constructed in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propdirectstalk})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an open set.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(U')=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')
\]

\end_inset

for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and where the restrictions maps are the ones incuded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space is called an 
\series bold
open subspace 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 There is an
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon U\to X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, where the continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon U\to X$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of the underlying topological spaces and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\iota_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 is given by the restriction maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)\to\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{V}^{\flat}(s)=s|_{U\cap V}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{\#}\colon\iota^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 is the identity.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the identity for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Given any morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U}\colon U\to Y$
\end_inset

 to be the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\iota$
\end_inset

 of morphisms of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon Z\to X$
\end_inset

 be morphisms of locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
open embedding 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $i(Z)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cong i(Z)$
\end_inset

 of locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
local isomorphism 
\series default
if there exists an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}\colon U_{i}\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an open embedding for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}:=f(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 is an open subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}\colon U_{i}\to V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-spaces for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y,f(x)}\to\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closed Immersions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon Z\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of locally ringed spaces.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
closed immersion 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map of topological spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon Z\to X$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 onto a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to i_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is surjective (meaning for each 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{z}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathcal{O}_{Z,z}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=i(z)$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}=\ker(i^{\flat})$
\end_inset

 is locally generated by sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X_{1,2}\to X_{2,1}$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed spaces.
 We construct a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, obtained by gluing 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The underlying set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=X_{1}\coprod X_{2}\slash\sim
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\coprod X_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the disjoint union of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is the equivalence relation defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the structure of a topological space using the quotient topology with respect
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{1}\subseteq U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{2}\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=i_{1}(X_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=i_{2}(X_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}\colon X_{1}\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{2}\colon X_{2}\to X$
\end_inset

 being the obvious inclusion maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We given 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the structure of a locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space by defining the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{(s_{1},s_{2})\mid s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }f^{\flat}(s_{2})|{}_{U\cap X_{2,1}}=s_{1}|{}_{U\cap X_{1,2}})\}
\]

\end_inset

for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's go over specific examples of this construction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=1/x$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a ringed space 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be two presheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define the product presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\times\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 by setting
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathcal{F}\times\mathcal{G})(U)=\mathcal{F}(U)\times\mathcal{G}(U)
\]

\end_inset

for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 where the restriction maps are the products of the restriction maps for
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly this is a sheaf if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are sheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-module
\series default
 is a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 equipped with two morphisms of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}\times\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal{O}_{X}\times\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}
\]

\end_inset

called addition and scalar-multiplication respectively, such that for each
 open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, addition and scalar-multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-modules and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of sheaves.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-module homomorphism 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism for each open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The composition of two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms is again an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module homomorhism.
 We obtain a category of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Mod}_{\mathcal{O}_{X}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a locally ringed space.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-module structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 induces an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

-module structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
fiber 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(x)$
\end_inset

, is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x)$
\end_inset

-vector space
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(x):=\mathcal{F}_{x}\slash\mathfrak{m}_{x}\mathcal{F}_{x}=\mathcal{F}_{x}\otimes_{\mathcal{O}_{X,x}}\kappa(x).
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a section of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 over an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)$
\end_inset

 the image of the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $[s]_{x}\in\mathcal{F}_{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sheaves of Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a ringed space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define the 
\series bold
tensor algebra 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to be the sheaf of noncommutative graded 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-algebras
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})=\mathrm{T}_{\mathcal{O}}(\mathcal{F})=\bigoplus_{n\geq0}\mathrm{T}^{n}(\mathcal{F}).
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{0}(\mathcal{F})=\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{1}(\mathcal{F})=\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{n}(\mathcal{F})=\mathcal{F}^{\otimes n}$
\end_inset

 where the tensor product is over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{n}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 consists of all finite sums of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}u_{1,i}\otimes\cdots\otimes u_{i,n}=\sum_{i}\boldsymbol{u}_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1,i},\dots,u_{n,i}\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and where we used the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{i}:=u_{1,i}\otimes\cdots\otimes u_{i,n}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}\in\mathrm{T}^{m}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}\in\mathrm{T}^{n}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=u_{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes u_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=v_{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes v_{n}$
\end_inset

 are elementary tensors, then we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}\boldsymbol{v}=u_{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes u_{m}\otimes v_{1}\otimes\cdots\otimes v_{n}\in\mathrm{T}^{m+n}(\mathcal{F})(U).
\]

\end_inset

This gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 the structure of a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

-algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\land(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 to be the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 by the two sided ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 is generated by local sections 
\begin_inset Formula $u\otimes u$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{2}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a local section of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 inherits the structure of graded 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-module from the grading on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

.
 We denote the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\land^{n}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}=\wedge(\boldsymbol{u})=u_{1}\land\cdots\wedge u_{n},
\]

\end_inset

where in this notation we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge(\boldsymbol{u})=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=u_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =(u+v)(u+v)\\
 & =u^{2}+uv+vu+v^{2}\\
 & =uv+vu
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $uv=-vu$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\land(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 is a graded-commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 to be the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 by the two sided ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}$
\end_inset

 is generated by local sections 
\begin_inset Formula $u\otimes v-v\otimes u$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}^{2}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 are local sections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 inherits the structure of graded 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-module from the grading on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

.
 We denote the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}^{n}(\mathcal{F})(U)$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}=u_{1}\cdots u_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where in this notation we 
\begin_inset Formula $uv=vu$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 is a commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With the notation above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}^{n}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 are sheaves.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\land^{n}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf since a similar works for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}^{n}(\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}\in\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}(U_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}|_{U_{\lambda\mu}}=\omega_{\mu}|_{U_{\lambda\mu}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\mu$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf, we need to find a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega|_{U_{\lambda}}=\omega_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the restriction maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}(U)\to\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}(U_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 are all injective.
 Thus we only need to show existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 since uniqueness is already satisfied.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

 is the unique element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge^{n}\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega|_{U_{\lambda}}=\omega_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{\lambda}=\sum_{i=1}^{k_{\lambda}}u_{1,\lambda,i}\wedge\cdots\wedge u_{n,\lambda,i}=\sum_{i=1}^{k_{\lambda}}\boldsymbol{u}_{\lambda,i},
\]

\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\lambda\mu}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}|_{U_{\lambda\mu}}=\omega_{\mu}|_{U_{\lambda\mu}}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\lambda}=k=k_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and (perhaps after reordering) implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{\lambda,i}=\boldsymbol{u}_{\mu,i}$
\end_inset

 which further implies (perhaps after reordering) 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j,\lambda,i}=u_{j,\mu,i}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 we have a compatible sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{j,\lambda,i})_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j,\lambda,i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j,i}\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j,i}|_{U_{\lambda}}=u_{j,\lambda,i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\sum\boldsymbol{u}_{i}=\sum u_{1,i}\wedge\cdots\wedge u_{k,i}$
\end_inset

 is the unique element such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega|_{U_{\lambda}}=\omega_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sheaf Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be a ringed space.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-ringed, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Consider the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X,-)$
\end_inset

 from the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-modules to the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\mapsto\Gamma(X,\mathcal{F}):=\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X,-)$
\end_inset

 is left exact.
 This means that if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\to\mathcal{F}_{1}\to\mathcal{F}_{2}\to\mathcal{F}_{3}
\]

\end_inset

is an exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-modules, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\to\Gamma(X,\mathcal{F}_{1})\to\Gamma(X,\mathcal{F}_{2})\to\Gamma(X,\mathcal{F}_{3})
\]

\end_inset

is an exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.[[
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Differential Geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Euclidean Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the prototype of all manifolds.
 Not only is it the simplest, but locally every manifold looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A good understanding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is essential in generalizing differential and integral calculus to a manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be a nonnegative integer and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if its partial derivatives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\partial_{x_{i_{2}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{j}}}f
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
of all orders 
\begin_inset Formula $j\leq k$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if all of its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 A similar defintion holds for a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We treat the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as synonymous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The polynomial, sine, cosine, and exponential functions on the real line
 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{3}x^{-2/3} & \mbox{for }x\neq0\\
\mbox{undefined} & \mbox{for }x=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid x\neq0\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt=\int_{0}^{x}t^{1/3}dt=\frac{3}{4}x^{4/3}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)=f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way one can construct a function that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k+1}$
\end_inset

 at a given point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth and even bijective with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is not smooth, as shown above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuity of a function can often be seen by inspection, but the smoothness
 of a function always requires a formula.
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{5/3}$
\end_inset

 looks perfectly smooth, but it is in fact not smooth at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, since its second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $y''=(10/9)x^{-1/3}$
\end_inset

 is not defined there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the norm function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We will do this in detail.
 First we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)=\frac{x_{n}}{\|x\|}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x_{n}}^{k+1}\left(\|x\|\right) & =\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\frac{f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}+\frac{(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k+1}}\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(x)\left(x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}\right)+(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2n+1}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes our claim.
 Now given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{1}}^{k_{1}}\cdots\partial_{x_{n}}^{k_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)/\|x\|^{2(k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n})-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial (just use the same induction proof).
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, we see that the norm function is smooth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be smooth.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will only sketch the proof here.
 By the chain rule, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}(g\circ f)=(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}f
\]

\end_inset

By the product rule we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}(g\circ f)=(g''\circ f)\cdot(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{2}+(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}(g\circ f)=(g'''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{3}+3(g''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f)+(g'\circ f)\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}f.
\]

\end_inset

More generally, we will have a pattern which involves stirling numbers.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
real-analytic
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 it is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})+\frac{1}{2!}\sum_{i,j}\partial_{x_{i}}\partial_{x_{j}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})(x_{j}-p_{j})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(p)(x_{i_{1}}-p_{i_{1}})\cdots(x_{i_{k}}-p_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A real-analytic function is necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, because as one learns in real analysis, a convergent power series can
 be differentiated term by term in its region of convergence.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\sin x=x-\frac{1}{3!}x^{3}+\frac{1}{5!}x^{5}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then term-by-term differentiation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\cos x=1-\frac{1}{2!}x^{2}-\frac{1}{4!}x^{4}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The following example shows that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be real-analytic.
 The idea is to construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 whose graph, though not horizontal, is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the sense that all of its derivatives vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{smoothnotanalytic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function very flat at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathrm{d}^{n}}{\mathrm{d}x^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{n}}{\mathrm{d}x^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)=e^{-1/x}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $L(n,i)$
\end_inset

 are the Lah numbers.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 are well defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathrm{d}^{n}}{\mathrm{d}x^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to0$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 much faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

), so this function is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the Taylor series of this function at the origin is
 identically zero in any neighborhood of the origin since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathrm{d}^{n}f}{\mathrm{d}x^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 cannot be equal to its Taylor series and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is not real-analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Taylor's Theorem with Remainder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Although a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be equal to its Taylor series, there is a Taylor's theorem
 with remainder for 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions that is often good enough for our purposes.
 We say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
star-shaped
\series default
 with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Taylor's theorem with remainder).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 star-shaped with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x),\dots,g_{n}(x)\in C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\qquad g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea behind this proof is to differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 and then integerate it.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 the line segment 
\begin_inset Formula $p+t(x-p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 By the chain rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{df}{dt}(p+t(x-p)) & =\frac{df}{dt}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}),\dots,p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}))+\cdots+(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we integrate both sides with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(p+t(x-p))|_{0}^{1}=\sum(x_{i}-p_{i})\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt\label{eq:inteq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to apply this proof to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(x) & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(tx)dt\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{-e^{-1/tx}}{tx^{2}}dt\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/tx}}{x}|_{0}^{1}\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(0)+x\left(\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In elementary calculus we normally represent a vector at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 algebraically as a column of numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
v_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or geometrically as an arrow emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is tangent to a surface in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 if it lies in the tangent plane at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Such a definition of a tangent vector to a surface presupposes that the
 surface is embedded in a Euclidean space, and so would not apply to the
 projective plane, for example, which does not sit inside an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in any natural way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Directional Derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point with direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The line through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be parametized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell:=(\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{n}):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(t):=p+tv=(p_{1}+tv_{1},\dots,p_{i}+tv_{i},\dots,p_{n}+tv_{n})=:(\ell_{1}(t),\dots,\ell_{i}(t),\dots,\ell_{n}(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
directional derivative
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & :=\lim_{t\to0}\left(\frac{f(\ell(t))-f(p)}{t}\right)\\
 & =\partial_{t}f(\ell(t))|_{t=0}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\partial_{x_{i}}f(\ell(0))\cdot\partial_{t}\ell_{i}(0)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

, it is understood that the partial derivatives are to be evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a number, not a function.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{v}=\sum v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for the map that sends a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the number 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation we often omit the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is clear from the context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Germs of Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 We introduce a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that this is an equivalence relation by showing it
 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What happens if we weaken the relation a bit? Say 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we no longer have an equivalence relation.
 The reason is because this relation is not transitive: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})\sim(f_{3},U_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

, but this merely implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{1-x}
\]

\end_inset

with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=1+x+x^{2}+x^{3}+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

with domain the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

 have the same germ at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The addition and multiplication of functions induce corresponding operations
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 making it into an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two representatives.
 Then multiplication is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})\cdot(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

We need to check that this is well-defined, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}',U_{1}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}',U_{2}')$
\end_inset

 be two different represenatives respectively.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}=f_{1}'\text{ on }W_{1}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{1}'\text{ and }f_{2}=f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{2}\subset U_{2}\cap U_{2}'
\]

\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}f_{2}=f_{1}'f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{1}\cap W_{2}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{2},
\]

\end_inset

and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2})\sim(f_{1}'f_{2}',U_{1}\cap U_{2})
\]

\end_inset

and hence this is well-defined.
 Similarly, addition is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})+(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}+f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This example requires some knowledge of Algebraic Geometry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set over an algebraically closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=A(X)$
\end_inset

 be its coordinate ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be the maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 given by the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

 which vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There are two equivalent ways to define the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 are equivalence classes of elements of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 if there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(g_{2}f_{1}-g_{1}f_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The other way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the ring of all germs of polynomial functions defined on a neighborhood
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polynomial function defined on a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 here as being the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f/g,D(g))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all points such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Two such polynomial functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}/g_{1},D(g_{1}))$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}/g_{2},D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

) represent the same germ if they agree on some small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A small open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the Zariski topology is simply something of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 does not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)\cap D(g_{1})\cap D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Another way of saying this is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}h(f_{1}/g_{1}-f_{2}/g_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; this matches precisely the criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be equal in the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivations at a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 gives a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed we just need to check that it is well-defined: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

 for some open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{f(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{g(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\partial_{x_{i}}g(p).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, which implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}g(p)\\
 & =D_{v}g.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined map.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear and satisfies the Leibniz rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{v}(fg)=(D_{v}f)g(p)+f(p)D_{v}g,\label{eq:leibnizrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

precisely because the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

 have these properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, any linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series default
or a 
\series bold
point-derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the set of all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 This set is in fact a real vector space, since the sum of two derivations
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a scalar multiplication of a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are again derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus far, we know that directional derivatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

where a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the point-derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is clearly linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a linear map of vector spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaconstantfunctions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a point-derivation of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=0$
\end_inset

 for any constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linearity, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=cD(1)$
\end_inset

, so it suffices to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By the the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(1)=D(1\cdot1)=D(1)\cdot1+1\cdot D(1)=2D(1).
\]

\end_inset

Substracting 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)$
\end_inset

 from both sides gives 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Kronecker delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a useful notation that we frequently call upon: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j.\\
0 & \text{if }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 defined above is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove injectivity, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 to the coordinate function 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =D_{v}x_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{i}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}x_{j}\mid_{p}\\
 & =v_{j}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove surjectivity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,V)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Making 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 smaller if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open ball, hence star-shaped.
 By Taylor's theorem with remainder, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to both sides and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(p)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p_{i})=0$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconstantfunctions})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we get by the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Df & =D(f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x))\\
 & =D(f(p))+\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(p)+(p_{i}-p_{i})Dg_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i})-D(p_{i}))g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(Dx_{1},\dots,Dx_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vector Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 has basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}\}$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}(p),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}(p)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are now functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if the coefficient functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=\frac{-y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{x}+\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=x\partial_{x}-y\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is commonly denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplication of vector fields by functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is defined pointwise:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f\vec{v})(p)=f(p)\vec{v}(p).
\]

\end_inset

Clearly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}f\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector fields on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vec}(U)$
\end_inset

, is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Fields as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we define a new function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\vec{v}(p)f
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 gives rise to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{\infty}(U)\to C^{\infty}(U),\qquad f\mapsto\vec{v}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Leibniz rule for a vector field) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(fg)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)(fg)=\vec{v}(p)(f)\cdot g(p)+f(p)\cdot\vec{v}(p)(g),
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 varies over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this becomes an inequality of functions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an algebra over a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, a 
\series bold
derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:A\to A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(ab)=(Da)b+a(Db),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition and scalar multiplication and forms a vector space,
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Der}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 As noted above, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a derivation of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore have a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:\text{Vec}(U)\to\text{Der}(C^{\infty}(U)),\qquad\vec{v}\mapsto(f\mapsto\vec{v}f).
\]

\end_inset

Just as the tangent vectors at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the point-derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, so the vector fields on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the derivations of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Exterior Algebra of Multicovectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The basic principle of manifold theory is the linearization principle, according
 to which every manifold can be locally approximated by its tangent space
 at a point, a linear object.
 In this way linear algebra enters into manifold theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Instead of working with tangent vectors, it turns out to be more fruitful
 to adopt the dual point of view and work with linear functions on a tangent
 space.
 After all, there is only so much that one can do with tangent vectors,
 which are essentially arrows, but functions, far more flexible, can be
 added, multiplied, and composed with other maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dual Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 the vector space of all linear maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:V\to W$
\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\series bold
dual space
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to be the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
covectors
\series default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
covectors 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 can be uniquely expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 be the linear function that picks out the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}(v)=v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{e}_{i}(e_{j})=\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{for }i=j,\\
0 & \mbox{for }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 span 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(v) & =\ell\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\underline{e}_{i}(v)\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}(v)\\
 & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\right)(v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\in\mbox{Span}(\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Next we show the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}\underline{e}_{i}=0,\label{eq:linearindependence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 By applying 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:linearindependence})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
dual basis 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 is a hyperplane in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be its dual basis.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in terms of the dual basis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\underline{e}_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}a_{i}=0.$
\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ker}(\ell)=V\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{i}\right)=\left\{ (x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\mid\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right)=n-k.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 We may assume that we are working in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}=\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right) & =\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}V\left(X_{i}\right)\right)\\
 & =\text{dim}\left(V\left(X_{1},\dots,X_{k}\right)\right)\\
 & =n-k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The converse is trivial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential Forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
cotangent space 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}))^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 In parallel with the definition of a vector field, a 
\series bold
covector field 
\series default
or 
\series bold
differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\series default
on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega:U\to\bigcup_{p\in U}T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),\qquad p\mapsto\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call a differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\series bold
-form 
\series default
for short.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jacobian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
Jacobian 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p):=\begin{pmatrix}(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{1})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{1})(p)\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{m})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{m})(p)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian satisfies the following property: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\|f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon)\|}{\|\varepsilon\|}\to0
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 One can view the Jacobian as a smooth linear map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)=(J(f)(p)_{1},\dots,J(f)(p)_{m}):\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m},
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f)(p)_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}(\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i})(p)x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to itself and the Jacobian matrix is a square matrix.
 In particular, we can compute its determinant, known as the 
\series bold
Jacobian determinant
\series default
.
 The Jacobian determinant at a given point gives important information about
 the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near that point.
 For instance, the inverse function theorem tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is invertible near a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the Jacobian determinant is non-zero.
 Furthermore, if the Jacobian determinant at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 preserves orientation near 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid xy\in(-\pi/2,\pi/2)\text{ and }x+y\in(0,\infty)\}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=\tan(xy)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=\ln(x+y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in U$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}y_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0}) & x_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})\\
\frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}} & \frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian determinant is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{det}\left(J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})\right)=\frac{(y_{0}-x_{0})\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})}{x_{0}+y_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=x^{2}+xy+y$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}+y_{0}\\
x_{0}+1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})\\
 & =x_{0}^{2}+x_{0}y_{0}+y_{0}+(2x_{0}+y_{0})\varepsilon_{1}+(x_{0}+1)\varepsilon_{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=x^{2}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=y^{2}+x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}y_{0} & x_{0}^{2}\\
1 & 2y_{0}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =((x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}),(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}^{2})+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1}))\\
 & =(x_{0}^{2}y_{0},y_{0}^{2}+x_{0})+(2x_{0}y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}+x_{0}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{1}+2y_{0}\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\subset\mathbb{R}^{m}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p+\varepsilon)=f(p)+J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon)+\psi(\varepsilon),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\psi(\varepsilon)\|/\|\varepsilon\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\varepsilon):=f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be the finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space of symmetric bilinear forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, endowed with its natural topology as a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 The subset of elements that are positive-definite inner products is open
 and connected.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first prove connectedness, and then we prove openness.
 There is a natural left action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

: given 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathrm{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in W$
\end_inset

, we define a symmetric bilinear form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\cdot B=B\circ(T^{-1}\otimes T^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be its corresponding dual basis.
 Identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

 with the standard basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to see that the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\cdot B$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[T\cdot B] & =[T^{-1}]^{\top}[B][T^{-1}].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By fixing a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and computing in linear coordinates we see that the resulting map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GL}(V)\times W\to W$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 In particular, if we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}\in W$
\end_inset

 then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GL}(V)\to W$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mapsto T\cdot B_{0}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Restricting to the connected subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GL}^{+}(V)$
\end_inset

, it follows from continuity that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GL}^{+}(V)$
\end_inset

-orbit of any 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 is connected in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 But if we take 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 to be an inner product then form the definition of the action we see that
 
\begin_inset Formula $T\cdot B_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an inner product for every 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathrm{GL}^{+}(V)$
\end_inset

 (even for 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathrm{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

), and it can be shown that every inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is obtained froma single 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 by means of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathrm{GL}^{+}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the connectivity.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Higher Derivatives and Taylor's Formula Via Multilinear Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differentiability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be open, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
differentiable 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 if there exists a (necessarily unique) linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(u)\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\|f(u+h)-f(u)-\mathrm{D}f(u)h\|}{\|h\|}\to0\label{eq:coordinatefreediff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (where the norms on the top and bottom are on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, and the choices do not impact the definition since any two norms on a
 finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space are bounded by a constant positive multiple of each other).
 The linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(u)\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
total derivative 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
differentiable 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (or more simply just 
\series bold
differentiable 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is understood from context) if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at all points 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

, which sends a 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

 to the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(u)\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

, is called the 
\series bold
total derivative 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (or more simply just the total derivative if context is clear).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If we fix ordered bases for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, then we implicitly identify 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 using these bases as follows: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=v_{1},\dots,v_{m}$
\end_inset

 is an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=x_{1},\dots,x_{m}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding dual basis.
 Then a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\sum x_{i}v_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is identified with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 via the canonical linear isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\boldsymbol{v}}\colon V\simeq\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 which sends the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th standard basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{i}=(0,\dots,1,\dots0)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}=w_{1},\dots,w_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=y_{1},\dots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding dual basis.
 Then a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\sum y_{i}w_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is identified with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 via the canonical linear isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\boldsymbol{w}}\colon W\simeq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which sends the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th standard basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{i}=(0,\dots,1,\dots0)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 is identified with the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $[U]_{\boldsymbol{v}}\subseteq[V]_{\boldsymbol{v}}=\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 then is identified with the map 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]_{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\boldsymbol{w}}:=[\cdot]_{\boldsymbol{w}}\circ f\circ[\cdot]_{\boldsymbol{v}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $[U]_{\boldsymbol{v}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[W]_{\boldsymbol{w}}=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Under these identififications, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f\colon U & \longrightarrow & W\\
\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})^{\top} & \mapsto & (f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,f_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}))^{\top}=f(\boldsymbol{x})=\boldsymbol{y},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
component functions 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

 is identified the 
\series bold
Jacobian matrix
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})=\mathrm{J}_{f}(\boldsymbol{x}):=\begin{pmatrix}\partial_{x_{1}}f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}) & \cdots & \partial_{x_{m}}f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\partial_{x_{1}}f_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}) & \cdots & \partial_{x_{m}}f_{n}(\boldsymbol{x})
\end{pmatrix}=(\partial_{x_{i}}f_{j}(\boldsymbol{x})).
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{h}=(0,\dots,h_{i},\dots,0)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})^{i}$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathrm{D}}f(\boldsymbol{x})_{j}^{i})$
\end_inset

 denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th column vector (respectively the 
\begin_inset Formula $(j,i)$
\end_inset

 entry) of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Then as 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}\to0$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\|f(\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{h})-f(\boldsymbol{x})-\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})\boldsymbol{h}\|}{\|\boldsymbol{h}\|}=\left\Vert \frac{f(x_{1},\dots,x_{i}+h_{i},\dots,x_{m})-f(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})-\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})^{i}h_{i}}{h_{i}}\right\Vert \to0.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, this implies the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th component of the vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f(x_{1},\dots,x_{i}+h_{i},\dots,x_{m})^{\top}-f(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})^{\top}-\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})^{i}h_{i}}{h_{i}}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

tends to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th component of this vector is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{j}(x_{1},\dots,x_{i}+h_{i},\dots,x_{n})-f_{j}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})-h_{i}\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})_{j}^{i}}{h_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{x})_{j}^{i}=\partial_{x_{i}}f_{j}(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a two dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=(e_{1},e_{2})$
\end_inset

 be an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding dual basis.
 Thus every 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 can expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $v=a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2}$
\end_inset

 for unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=x_{1}(v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=x_{2}(v)$
\end_inset

.
 We often get lazy and simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $v=x_{1}v_{1}+x_{2}v_{2}$
\end_inset

 where we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 as the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(v) & =(x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2})(v)\\
 & =x_{1}(v)^{2}+x_{1}(v)x_{2}(v)+x_{2}(v)\\
 & =x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we got lazy at the end simply wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{1}(v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=x_{2}(v)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that we are using the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

's in two different (and admittedly contradictory) ways here.
 When we write 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

, we are thinking of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 as linear functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 When we write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v)=x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

, we are thinking of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 as the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $v=x_{1}e_{1}+x_{2}e_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 At the end of the day however, context will always makes clear how we are
 thinking of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 The matrix representation of the differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $v=x_{1}e_{1}+x_{2}e_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\boldsymbol{e}} & =\nabla_{\boldsymbol{x}}f(\boldsymbol{x})^{\top}\\
 & =(\partial_{x_{1}}f(\boldsymbol{x}),\partial_{x_{2}}f(\boldsymbol{x}))\\
 & =(2x_{1}+x_{2},x_{1}+1).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}=(\widetilde{e}_{1},\widetilde{e}_{2})$
\end_inset

 is another ordered basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}c_{11} & c_{12}\\
c_{21} & c_{22}
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\in\mathrm{GL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be a change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}C=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=C\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}=(\widetilde{x}_{1},\widetilde{x}_{2})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding dual basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 expressed in this new basis is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =x_{1}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}\\
 & =(c_{11}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{12}\widetilde{x}_{2})^{2}+(c_{11}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{12}\widetilde{x}_{2})(c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{2})+c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{2}\\
 & =c_{11}^{2}\widetilde{x}_{1}^{2}+2c_{11}c_{12}\widetilde{x}_{1}\widetilde{x}_{2}+c_{12}^{2}\widetilde{x}_{2}^{2}+c_{11}c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}^{2}+c_{12}c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}\widetilde{x}_{2}+c_{11}c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{1}\widetilde{x}_{2}+c_{12}c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{2}^{2}+c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{2}\\
 & =(c_{11}^{2}+c_{11}c_{21})\widetilde{x}_{1}^{2}+(2c_{11}c_{12}+c_{12}c_{21}+c_{11}c_{22})\widetilde{x}_{1}\widetilde{x}_{2}+(c_{12}^{2}+c_{12}c_{22})\widetilde{x}_{2}^{2}+c_{21}\widetilde{x}_{1}+c_{22}\widetilde{x}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let us consider the special case where 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 1\\
0 & -2
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\widetilde{x}_{1}^{2}-\widetilde{x}_{2}^{2}-2\widetilde{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v & =\boldsymbol{e}\boldsymbol{x}\\
 & =\boldsymbol{e}CC^{-1}\boldsymbol{x}\\
 & =\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 We can calculate the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(v)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}$
\end_inset

 basis in two ways: the first way is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}} & =\nabla_{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}}f(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}})^{\top}\\
 & =(\partial_{\widetilde{x}_{1}}f(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}),\partial_{\widetilde{x}_{2}}f(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}))\\
 & =(2\widetilde{x}_{1},-2\widetilde{x}_{2}-2)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second way is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{e}}} & =[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\boldsymbol{e}}C\\
 & =(2x_{1}+x_{2},x_{1}+1)\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1\\
0 & -2
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =(2x_{1}+x_{2},x_{2}-2)\\
 & =(2\widetilde{x}_{1},-2\widetilde{x}_{2}-2).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleexplicitdiffyeah}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be the open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\{\boldsymbol{t}=(t_{1},t_{2})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid t_{1}t_{2}\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\{\pi/2+\pi\mathbb{Z}\}\text{ and }t_{1}+t_{2}\in(0,\infty)\}
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{t})=(\tan(t_{1}t_{2}),\ln(t_{1}+t_{2}))=(f_{1}(\boldsymbol{t}),f_{2}(\boldsymbol{t})).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with its derivative at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{t}=(t_{1},t_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{t})=\begin{pmatrix}t_{2}\sec^{2}(t_{1}t_{2}) & t_{1}\sec^{2}(t_{1}t_{2})\\
\frac{1}{t_{1}+t_{2}} & \frac{1}{t_{1}+t_{2}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(\boldsymbol{t})$
\end_inset

 is literally a matrix in this case (and not an abstract linear map between
 abstract vector spaces).
 This is because we are working specifically in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be two dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=(v_{1},v_{2})$
\end_inset

 be an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with corresponding dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}=(w_{1},w_{2})$
\end_inset

 be an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with corresponding dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{1},y_{2})^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(v)=f(x_{1}v_{1}+x_{2}v_{2})=\tan(x_{1}x_{2})w_{1}+\ln(x_{1}+x_{2})w_{2}=f_{1}(v)w_{1}+f_{2}(v)w_{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f\circ y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=f\circ y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix representation of the differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $v=x_{1}e_{1}+x_{2}e_{2}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the ordered bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\boldsymbol{w}} & =\begin{pmatrix}\partial_{x_{1}}f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}) & \partial_{x_{2}}f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})\\
\partial_{x_{1}}f_{2}(\boldsymbol{x}) & \partial_{x_{2}}f_{2}(\boldsymbol{x})
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}\sec^{2}(x_{1}x_{2}) & x_{1}\sec^{2}(x_{1}x_{2})\\
\frac{1}{x_{1}+x_{2}} & \frac{1}{x_{1}+x_{2}}
\end{pmatrix},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is the same matrix that we calculated in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{exampleexplicitdiffyeah})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, except now we are expressing it using 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{v}}=(\widetilde{v}_{1},\widetilde{v}_{2})$
\end_inset

 is another ordered basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with corresponding change of basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in\mathrm{GL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{w}}=(w_{1},w_{2})$
\end_inset

 is another ordered basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with corresponding change of basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathrm{GL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, then it is straightforward to check that the matrix representation of
 the differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\boldsymbol{v}\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{v}}}^{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{w}}}=D[\mathrm{D}f(v)]_{\boldsymbol{v}}^{\boldsymbol{w}}C.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivative of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 be an ordered basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})^{\top}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding dual basis.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to V$
\end_inset

 be a linear isomorphism and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

 with the standard ordered basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 gets identified to a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $T=(T_{j}^{i})$
\end_inset

, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 gets identified to a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=(u_{1},\dots,u_{n})^{\top}$
\end_inset

, and the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 gets identified to the Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Viewing 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we see that it has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(\boldsymbol{u})=\begin{pmatrix}T_{1}^{1} & \cdots & T_{1}^{n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
T_{n}^{1} & \cdots & T_{n}^{n}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}u_{1}\\
\vdots\\
u_{n}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}T_{1}^{1}u_{1}+\cdots+T_{1}^{n}u_{n}\\
\vdots\\
T_{n}^{1}u_{1}+\cdots+T_{n}^{n}u_{n}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}T_{1}(\boldsymbol{u})\\
\vdots\\
T_{n}(\boldsymbol{u})
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus the component functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 correspond to its rows as matrix.
 These component functions are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{j}=T_{j}^{1}x_{1}+\cdots+T_{j}^{n}x_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\mathrm{D}T)(u) & =\mathrm{J}_{\boldsymbol{u}}(T)\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}(\partial_{x_{1}}T_{1})(\boldsymbol{u}) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}T_{1})(\boldsymbol{u})\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
(\partial_{x_{1}}T_{n})(\boldsymbol{u}) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}T_{n})(\boldsymbol{u})
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}T_{1}^{1} & \cdots & T_{1}^{n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
T_{n}^{1} & \cdots & T_{n}^{n}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =T.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So the derivative of a linear map at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is just the linear map itself.
 Notice that we proved this by choosing an ordered basis, but we could have
 also proven this directly using the coordinate-free definition of differentiabi
lity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:coordinatefreediff})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}T(u)=T$
\end_inset

, then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\|T(u+h)-T(u)-\mathrm{D}T(u)(h)\|}{\|h\|}=0,
\]

\end_inset

so clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}T(u)$
\end_inset

 exists, and it must be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 itself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chain Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propchainrule}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V',$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n''$
\end_inset

 respectively, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon U'\to V''$
\end_inset

 be differentiable functions.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\colon U\cap f^{-1}(U')\to V''$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U\cap f^{-1}(U')$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{D}(g\circ f)(u)=\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ\mathrm{D}f(u).\label{eq:chainrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap f^{-1}(U')=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then there is nothing to prove, so we may assume that it is nonempty.
 After choosing bases for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V''$
\end_inset

, we may identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(g\circ f)(u)$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $n''\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(i'',i)$
\end_inset

 entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}(g\circ f)_{i''}(u)$
\end_inset

, we may identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}g(f(u))$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $n''\times n'$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(i'',i')$
\end_inset

 entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{f_{i'}}g{}_{i''}(f(u))$
\end_inset

, and we may identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(u)$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $n'\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(i',i)$
\end_inset

 entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}f_{i'}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 turns into the matrix equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\partial_{x_{i}}(g\circ f)_{i''}(u))=(\partial_{f_{i'}}g{}_{i''}(f(u)))\cdot(\partial_{x_{i}}f_{i'}(u))
\]

\end_inset

which gives us a system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{x_{i}}(g\circ f)_{i''}(u)=\sum_{i'=1}^{n'}\partial_{f_{i'}}g{}_{i''}(f(u))\partial_{x_{i}}f_{i'}(u)\label{eq:classicalcasesystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i''\leq n''$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds if and only if 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:classicalcasesystem})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,i''$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:classicalcasesystem})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds since this is just the chain rule in the classical case.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here's a coordinate-free proof of the Chain Rule: again we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap f^{-1}(U')\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap f^{-1}(U')$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U=f^{-1}(U')$
\end_inset

.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

 (we show 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 with derivative given by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 There exists open balls 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}(0)\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon'}(0)\subseteq V'$
\end_inset

 together with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}\colon\mathrm{B}_{\delta}(0)\to V'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}\colon\mathrm{B}_{\delta'}(0)\to V''$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(u+h) & =f(u)+\mathrm{D}f(u)h+R_{1}(h)\\
g(f(u)+h') & =g(f(u))+\mathrm{D}g(f(u))h'+R_{2}(h')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathrm{B}_{\delta}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h'\in\mathrm{B}_{\delta'}(0)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}$
\end_inset

 have the additional property that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|R_{1}(h)\|\leq A_{u}(h)\|h\|\quad\text{and}\quad\|R_{2}(h')\|\leq B_{f(u)}(h')\|h'\|,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{u}\colon\mathrm{B}_{\delta}(0)\to\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{f(u)}\colon\mathrm{B}_{\delta'}(0)\to\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 satisfy
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}A_{u}(h)=0\quad\text{and}\quad\lim_{h'\to0}B_{f(u)}(h')=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the convergence 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{u}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 is uniform on a compact subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the convergence 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{f(u)}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 is uniform on a compact subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $K'\subseteq U'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(u)\in K'$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon,\varepsilon'>0$
\end_inset

, by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'$
\end_inset

 with smaller values if necessary, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup_{\substack{\|h\|<\delta\\
v\in K
}
}\|A_{v}(h)\|<\varepsilon\quad\text{and}\quad\sup_{\substack{\|h'\|<\delta'\\
v'\in K'
}
}\|B_{v'}(h')\|<\varepsilon'.
\]

\end_inset

We don't need the full strength of this fact; mainly we just need the fact
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h\|<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|A_{u}(h)\|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h'\|<\delta'$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|B_{f(u)}(h)\|<\varepsilon'$
\end_inset

.
 Now, in a moment, we are going to want to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 with something smaller (if necessary), but before we do this, let's see
 how the proof ought to work: to show 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, it suffices to show that it has a first order approximation of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(g\circ f)(u+h)=g(f(u))+(\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ\mathrm{D}f(u))h+R_{3}(h),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently small and where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}\colon\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\to V''$
\end_inset

 is a function with the property that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|R_{3}(h)\|\leq C_{u}(h)\|h\|
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{u}\colon\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{u}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

.
 To determine this first order approximation, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(g\circ f)(u+h) & =g(f(u+h))\\
 & =g(f(u)+\mathrm{D}f(u)h+R_{1}(h))\\
 & =g(f(u)+h')\\
 & =g(f(u))+\mathrm{D}g(f(u))h'+R_{2}(h')\\
 & =g(f(u))+(\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ\mathrm{D}f(u))h+(\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ R_{1}(h)+R_{2}(h'))\\
 & =g(f(u))+(\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ\mathrm{D}f(u))h+R_{3}(h)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $h'=\mathrm{D}f(u)h+R_{1}(h)$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}(h)=\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ R_{1}(h)+R_{2}(h')$
\end_inset

.
 In order for this to work, we need to justify the jump from the third line
 to the fourth line above.
 We show that we can do this by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 with something smaller if necessary.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|h'\| & =\|\mathrm{D}f(u)h+R_{1}(h)\|\\
 & \leq\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|\|h\|+A_{u}(h)\|h\|\\
 & =(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+A_{u}(h))\|h\|\\
 & <(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+\varepsilon)\|h\|\\
 & <(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+\varepsilon)\delta.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'/(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we can ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h\|<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h'\|<\delta'$
\end_inset

, so that it makes sense to go from the third line to the fourth line in
 our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

initial proof
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Finally, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|R_{3}(h)\| & =\|\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\circ R_{1}(h)+R_{2}(h')\|\\
 & \leq\|\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\|\|R_{1}(h)\|+\|R_{2}(h')\|\\
 & \leq\|\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\|A_{u}(h)\|h\|+B_{f(u)}(h')\|h'\|\\
 & <\|\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\|A_{u}(h)\|h\|+B_{f(u)}(h')(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+\varepsilon)\|h\|\\
 & =C_{u}(h)\|h\|,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{u}(h)=\|\mathrm{D}g(f(u))\|A_{u}(h)+B_{f(u)}(h')(\|\mathrm{D}f(u)\|+\varepsilon).
\]

\end_inset

Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $h'\to0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{u}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{f(u)}(h')\to0$
\end_inset

.
 So clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{u}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

, and we are done.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 with its derivative given by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivative of a Chart
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 be a smooth chart of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism onto its image.
 Then by the chain rule, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\mathrm{D}(1_{\varphi(U)})(\varphi(u))\\
 & =\mathrm{D}(\varphi\circ\varphi^{-1})(\varphi(u))\\
 & =\mathrm{D}\varphi(u)\circ\mathrm{D}\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(u)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}\varphi(u)$
\end_inset

 is invertible (and hence nonzero) with its inverse given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(u))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional spaces, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be open, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (or more simply 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is understood from context) if it is differentiable and its total derivative
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))$
\end_inset

 is differentiable (with total derivative denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}^{2}f=\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}^{2}f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(u) & \in W &  & f\in\mathrm{Map}(U,W)\\
(\mathrm{D}f)(u) & \in\mathrm{Hom}(V,W) &  & \mathrm{D}f\in\mathrm{Map}(U,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))\\
(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f))(u) & \in\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)) &  & \mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f)\in\mathrm{Map}(U,\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))\\
 & \vdots &  & \vdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that there are unique isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-)^{\diamond}\colon\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))\to\mathrm{Hom}(V\otimes V,W)\quad\text{and}\quad(-)_{\diamond}\colon\mathrm{Hom}(V\otimes V,W)\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces (both natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

