\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}f(u_{1})_{i}^{j}=\partial_{x_{i}}f_{j}(u_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}^{2}f(u_{1}\otimes u_{2})=(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f))^{\diamond}(u_{1}\otimes u_{2})=(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f)u
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}^{2}f(u)(u_{1}\otimes u_{2})=(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f)(u))^{\diamond}(u_{1}\otimes u_{2})=(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f))u
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}^{2}f(u)=(\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f)(u))^{\diamond}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

What does it mean to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is continuous? Upon fixing linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, such continuity amounts to continuity for each of the component functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}f_{j}\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 of the matrix-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

, and so the concrete definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 being 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the coordinate-free property that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and that the associated total derivative map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 to a new vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 With this latter point of view, wherein 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

 is a map from the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 into a finite-dimensional vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

, a very natural question is: what does it mean to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable, or even continuously so? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 map, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 be the associated total derivative map.
 As a map from an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to a finite-dimensional vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 if and only if (relative to a choice of linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

) all second-order partials 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\partial_{x_{i_{2}}}f_{j}\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fixing linear coordinates identifies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

 with a map from an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 to a Euclidean space of 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrices, with component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}f_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, this map is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 if and only if these components admit all first-order partials that are
 moreover continuous, and this is exactly the statement that the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset

's admit all second-order partials and that such partials are continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 when it is differentiable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 By the lemma, this is just a fancy way to encode the concrete definition
 that all component functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (relative to linear coordinizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

) admit continuous second-order partials.
 Next let us consider the total derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}^{2}f=\mathrm{D}(\mathrm{D}f)\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))\cong\mathrm{Hom}(V\otimes V,W)
\]

\end_inset

More to the point, how do we work with the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Hom}(V,W))$
\end_inset

? I claim that it is not nearly as complicated as it may seem, and that
 once we understand how to think about this iterated Hom-space we will see
 that the theory of higher-order partials admits a very pleasing reformulation
 in the language of multilinear mappings.
 The underlying mechanism is a certain isomorphism in linear algebra, so
 we now digress to discuss the algebraic preliminaries in a purely algebraic
 setting over any field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In general, for an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

 we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to W$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map
\series default
, or is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
times continuously differentiable
\series default
, if it is differentiable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p-1}$
\end_inset

 map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we shall say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map
\series default
, or is 
\series bold
infinitely differentiable
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Higher Derivatives as Symmetric Multilinear Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional vector spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be open in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 be a map of sets.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map 
\series default
if it is continuous.
 We have seen above that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)
\]

\end_inset

continuous if and only if, with respect to a choice of linear coordinates,
 the components 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 admit continuous first-order partial derivatives across all of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with respect to the coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 This property of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is called being a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map
\series default
, and we may rephrase it as the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and 
\begin_inset Formula $Df$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 We now make a recursive definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In general, for an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

 we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map
\series default
, or is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
times continuously differentiable
\series default
, if it is differentiable and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p-1}$
\end_inset

 map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we shall say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
map
\series default
, or is 
\series bold
infinitely differentiable
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}f(u)$
\end_inset

 to denote 
\begin_inset Formula $D(Df)(u)$
\end_inset

, and by definition since 
\begin_inset Formula $Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is a differentiable map from an open in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}f(u)$
\end_inset

 is a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{2}f:U\to\text{Hom}(V,\text{Hom}(V,W))
\]

\end_inset

and this is continuous (as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

).
 More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

, then for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\leq p$
\end_inset

 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{i}f=D(D^{i-1}f)$
\end_inset

, and arguing recursively we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{p}f(u)$
\end_inset

 is a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,\text{Hom}(V,\dots,\text{Hom}(V,W)\dots))$
\end_inset

 where there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p-1$
\end_inset

 iterated Hom's.
 That is, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f:U\to\text{Hom}(V,\text{Hom}(V,\dots,\text{Hom}(V,W)\dots))\simeq\text{Mult}(V^{p},W).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be open an let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is described as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}):U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}=W$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

 be a non-negative integer.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map if and only if all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-fold iterated partial derivatives of the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

's exist and are continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if all 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

's admit all iterated partials of all orders.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We induct on 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 being the old result that a map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to a product space is continuous if and only if its component maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 are continuous.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

, the theorem is our earlier observation that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with 
\begin_inset Formula $Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 continuous if and only if the component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 admit continuous first-order partials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p>1$
\end_inset

, so in either direction of implication in the theorem we know (from the
 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 case which has been established) that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 admits a continuous derivative map 
\begin_inset Formula $Df$
\end_inset

 and that all partials 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i}$
\end_inset

 exist as continous functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we know that the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)\simeq\text{Mat}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R})
\]

\end_inset

to the vector space of 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices has as its component functions (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matrix entries
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) precisely the first-order partials 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i}:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $Df$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p-1}$
\end_inset

, but since this latter map has the 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i}$
\end_inset

's as its component functions, by the inductive hypothesis applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $Df$
\end_inset

 (with the target vector space now 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, and linear coordinates given by matrix entries), it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $Df$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p-1}$
\end_inset

 if and only if all 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i}$
\end_inset

's admit all 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)$
\end_inset

-fold iterated partial derivatives in the linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and that these are continuous.
 Since an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)$
\end_inset

-fold partial of an arbitrary first order partial 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i}$
\end_inset

 is nothing more or less than an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-fold partial of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 if and only if all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-fold partials of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

's with respect to the linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 mapping with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

, and consider the continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th derivative mapping 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f:U\to\text{Mult}(V^{p},W).
\]

\end_inset

We want to describe this in terms of partial derivatives using linear coordinate
s on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 That is, we fix ordered bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w_{1},\dots,w_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, so for each 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

 the multilinear mapping 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u):V^{p}\to W=\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is uniquely determined by the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-tuples 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u)(e_{j_{1}},\dots,e_{j_{p}})\in W=\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j_{1},\dots,j_{p}\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 What are the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 components of this vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

? The answer is very nice: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With notation as above, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 be the dual basis to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{j}$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{j}}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the component functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 with respect to the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

's of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j_{1},\dots,j_{p}\leq n,$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u)(e_{j_{1}},\dots,e_{j_{p}})=((\partial_{j_{p}}\cdots\partial_{j_{1}}f_{1})(u),\dots,(\partial_{j_{p}}\cdots\partial_{j_{1}}f_{m})(u))\in\mathbb{R}^{m}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We induct on 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the base case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 being the old theorem on the determination of the matrix for the derivative
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(u):V\to W$
\end_inset

 in terms of first-order partials of the component functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (using linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 to define these component functions, and using linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to define the relevant partial derivative operators on these functions).
 Now we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By definition of the isomorphism in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{coriso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u)(v_{1},\dots,v_{p})=(\cdots((D^{p}f(u)(v_{1}))(v_{2})\cdots)(v_{p})\in W
\]

\end_inset

for any ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\dots,v_{p}\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F=Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the given linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, the associated 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matrix entries
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are taken as the linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 to get component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

).
 Considering 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2},\dots,v_{p}$
\end_inset

 as fixed but 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

 as varying, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u)(\cdot,v_{2},\dots,v_{p})=(\cdots((D^{p-1}F)(u)(v_{2}))\cdots)(v_{p})=D^{p-1}F(u)(v_{2},\dots,v_{p})\in\text{Hom}(V,W)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 is the target vector space for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}=e_{j_{k}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $2\leq k\leq p$
\end_inset

, the inductive hypothesis applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $F:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)=\text{Mat}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p-1}F(u)(e_{j_{2}},\dots,e_{j_{p}})=(\partial_{j_{p}}\cdots\partial_{j_{2}}F_{ij}(u))\in\text{Mat}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset

In view of how the matrix coordinatization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 was 
\emph on
defined 
\emph default
using the chosen ordered bases on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(V,W)\simeq\text{Mat}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 corresponds to pass to the 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1}$
\end_inset

th column of a matrix.
 Hence taking 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=e_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{p}f(u)(e_{j_{1}},e_{j_{2}},\dots,e_{j_{p}})=(\partial_{j_{p}}\cdots\partial_{j_{2}}F_{1j_{1}}(u),\dots,\partial_{j_{p}}\cdots\partial_{j_{2}}F_{mj_{1}}(u))\in\mathbb{R}^{m}=W.
\]

\end_inset

By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 case, 
\begin_inset Formula $F=Df:U\to\text{Hom}(V,W)=\text{Mat}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $ij$
\end_inset

-component function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ij}=\partial_{j}f_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ij_{1}}=\partial_{j_{1}}f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we get the desired formula.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{m}$
\end_inset

 be linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 relative to some ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{m})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}^{2}f(u)$
\end_inset

 is identified with the 
\series bold
Hessian 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}^{2}f(u)=\mathrm{H}_{f}(u)=\left(\frac{\partial^{2}f}{\partial x_{i}\partial x_{j}}(u)\right).
\]

\end_inset

Hence, the Hessian that appears in the second derivative test in several
 variables is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a linear map (as might be suggested by its traditional presentation as a
 matrix) but rather is intrinsically seen to be a symmetric bilinear form.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Higher-Dimensional Taylor's Formula: Motivation and Preparations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an application of the formalism of higher derivatives as multilinear
 mappings, we wish to state and prove Taylor's formula (with an integral
 remainder term) for 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 on any open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

.
 In the special case 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a non-empty open interval, this will recover the usual Taylor formula from
 calculus.
 There is also a more traditional version of the multivariable Taylor formula
 given with loads of mixed partials and factorials, and we will show that
 this traditional version is equivalent to the version we will prove in
 the language of higher derivatives as multilinear mappings.
 The power of our point of view is that it permits one to give a proof of
 Taylor’s formula that is virtually identical in appearance to the proof
 in the classical case (with 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W=\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

; proofs of Taylor's formula in the classical language of mixed partials
 tend to become a big mess with factorials, and the integral formula and
 error bound for the remainder term are unpleasant to formulate in the classical
 language.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Before we state the general case, let us first recall the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-variable Taylor formula for a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon I\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 on an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I$
\end_inset

 an interior point: for 
\begin_inset Formula $|h|$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a-h,a+h)\in I$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a+h)=f(a)+f'(a)h+\frac{f''(a)}{2!}h^{2}+\cdots+\frac{f^{(p)}(a)}{p!}h^{p}+R_{p,a}(h)
\]

\end_inset

with error term 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{p,a}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p,a}(h)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{f^{(p)}(a+th)-f^{(p)}(a)}{(p-1)!}\cdot(1-t)^{p-1}h^{p}\mathrm{d}t=h^{p}\psi_{p,a}(h),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{p,a}(h)|$
\end_inset

 can be made below any desired 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (uniformly for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in a compact subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

) since the continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(p)}$
\end_inset

 is uniformly continuous on compacts in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{p,a}(h)|/|h|^{p}\to0$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
uniformly 
\emph default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in a compact subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We calculate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}f(a+th)\right)\mathrm{d}t
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x+h)-f(x) & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}f(x+th)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}hf'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =h\int_{0}^{1}f'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =h\psi(h),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(h)=\int_{0}^{1}f'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{h\to0}\int_{0}^{1}f'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t & =\int_{0}^{1}\lim_{h\to0}f'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\lim_{h\to0}f'(x+th)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}f'(x)\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =f'(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}f(h,x)=\lim_{n\to\infty}f(1/n,x).
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{h\to0}f(h,x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|h|<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|f(h,x)-f(x)|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|f(1/n,x)-f(x)|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Taylor's Formula: Statement and Proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to W$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{r}(a)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 (relative to an arbitrary but fixed choice of norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a+h)$
\end_inset

 makes sense for 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in V$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h\|<r$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can state and prove Taylor's formula by essentially just copying
 the proof from calculus!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With the notation as above, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(a+h)=\sum_{j=0}^{p}\frac{(\mathrm{D}^{j}f)(a)}{j!}(h^{(j)})+R_{p,a}(h)\label{eq:taylorexpmutli}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p,a}(h)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t
\]

\end_inset

satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|R_{p,a}(h)\|\leq C_{p,a}(h)\|h\|^{p}\text{ and }\lim_{h\to0}C_{p,a}(h)=0\label{eq:errorestmulti}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{p,a}(h)=\sup_{t\in[0,1]}\frac{\|(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\|}{p!}.
\]

\end_inset

The convergence 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p,a}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 is uniform for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 supported in a compact subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p},W)$
\end_inset

 that is implicit in the numerator defining 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p,h,a}$
\end_inset

 is defined in terms of arbitrary but fixed choices of norms on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

: for any multilinear 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\colon V^{p}\to W$
\end_inset

 there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $B\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mu(v_{1},\dots,v_{p})\|\leq B\prod_{j=1}^{p}\|v_{j}\|$
\end_inset

, by elementary arguments exactly as in the simplest case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

, and the infimum of all such 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

's also works and is called 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mu\|$
\end_inset

.
 More concretely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mu\|$
\end_inset

 is the minimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\mu(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})\|$
\end_inset

 for the compact set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $(v_{1},\dots,v_{p})\in V^{p}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\|v_{j}\|=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\mapsto\|\mu\|$
\end_inset

 is a norm on the finite-dimensional vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}^{p}(V,W)$
\end_inset

, and in particular is a continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued function on this space of multilinear mappings.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|R_{p,a}(h)\| & =\left\Vert \int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t\right\Vert \\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{1}\left\Vert \frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\right\Vert \mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left\Vert \left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\right\Vert \mathrm{d}t\\
 & \leq\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\|(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\|\|h\|^{p}\mathrm{d}t\\
 & \leq\left(\sup_{t\in[0,1]}\|(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\|\right)\|h\|^{p}\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\frac{1}{p!}\left(\sup_{t\in[0,1]}\|(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\|\right)\|h\|^{p}\\
 & =C_{p,a}(h)\|h\|^{p}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One important consequence of the error estimate 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:errorestmulti})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is that it shows the error 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{p,a}(h)$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 expansion 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:taylorexpmutli})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a+h)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 dies off more rapidly than 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h\|^{p}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\|R_{p,a}(h)\|/\|h\|^{p}\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 with the rate of such decay actually 
\emph on
uniform 
\emph default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 supported in a fixed compact subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This is tremendously important for some applications.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A particular important case is 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

: the approximation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a+h)=f(a)+(\mathrm{D}f(a))(h)+(\mathrm{D}^{2}f(a))(h,h)+(\dots)
\]

\end_inset

has an error which dies more rapidly than 
\begin_inset Formula $\|h\|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is what underlies the reason why the symmetric bilinear Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)=(\mathrm{D}^{2}f)(a)$
\end_inset

 governs the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near critical points (that is those with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(a)=0$
\end_inset

, such as local extrema) in the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the signature of the quadratic form associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)$
\end_inset

 encodes much of the local geometry for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be an open set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 function.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a local minimizer for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
critical point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f-f(a)$
\end_inset

, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Taylor's formula, for small 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a+h)=\nabla f(a)^{\top}h+R_{a}(h)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\|R_{a}(h)\|\leq C_{a,h}\|h\|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a,h}\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}=-t\nabla f(a)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a+h_{t})=-t\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}+R_{a}(h_{t}).
\]

\end_inset

Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|R_{a}(h_{t})\|\leq\|h_{t}\|/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $t<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(a+h_{t}) & =-t\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}+R_{a}(h_{t})\\
 & \leq-t\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\|h_{t}\|\\
 & =-t\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}+\frac{t}{2}\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}\\
 & =-\frac{t}{2}\|\nabla f(a)\|^{2}\\
 & <0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\nabla f(a)\|=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be an open set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a critical point for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(a)=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)\colon V\times V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the symmetric bilinear Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}^{2}f(a)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the associated quadratic form.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)$
\end_inset

 is non-degenerate, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has an isolated local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite, an isolated local maximum at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is negative-definite, and neither a local minimum nor a maximum in the
 indefinite case.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f-f(a)$
\end_inset

, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Taylor's formula, for small 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f(a+h)}{\|h\|^{2}}=\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)(\widehat{h},\widehat{h})+R_{a}(h)=q_{f,a}(\widehat{h})+R_{a}(h)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a}(h)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{h}=h\slash\|h\|$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector pointing in the same direction as 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a+h)/\|h\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}(\widehat{h})$
\end_inset

 up to an error that ends to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 locally uniformly in 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is non-degenerate, in the positive-definite case it is bounded below by
 some 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 on the unit sphere, and hence (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

) by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small we get 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a+h)/\|h\|^{2}\geq c/2>0$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has an isolated local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, and a similar argument gives an isolated local maximum at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is negative-definite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is indefinite.
 By the spectral theorem, if we choose the norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to come from an inner product, then the pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)$
\end_inset

 is given by the inner product against an orthogonal linear map.
 Hence, in such cases we can find an orthonormal basis with respect to which
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is diagonalized, and so in the indefinite case there are lines on which
 the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite and there are lines on which the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

 is negative-definite.
 Approaching 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 along such directions gives different types of behavior for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 (isolated local minimum when approaching through the positive light cone
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

, and an isolated local maximum when approaching through the negative light
 cone for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}$
\end_inset

, provided the approach is not tangential to the null cone of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,a}(v)=0$
\end_inset

).
 This gives the familiar 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saddle point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 picture for the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, with the shape of the saddle governed by the eigenspace decomposition
 for the orthogonal map arising from the Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(a)$
\end_inset

 and the choice of inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove Taylor's Theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (applied componentwise using
 a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, say), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(a+h) & =f(a)+(f(a+h)-f(a))\\
 & =f(a)+\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{D}f(a+th)h\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =f(a)+\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{D}f(a+th)h\mathrm{d}t+\mathrm{D}f(a)h-\mathrm{D}f(a)h\\
 & =f(a)+\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{D}f(a+th)h\mathrm{d}t+\mathrm{D}f(a)h-\int_{0}^{1}\mathrm{D}f(a)h\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =f(a)+\mathrm{D}f(a)h+\int_{0}^{1}(\mathrm{D}f(a+th)-\mathrm{D}f(a))h\mathrm{d}t
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 This takes care of the case 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p>1$
\end_inset

 and we use induction.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is also of class 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p-1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(a+h) & =\sum_{j=0}^{p-1}\frac{\mathrm{D}^{j}f(a)}{j!}(h^{(j)})+R_{p-1,a}(h)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p-1,a}(h)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-2}}{(p-2)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p-1}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p-1}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p-1)})\mathrm{d}t.
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we just have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p-1,a}(h)=\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})+R_{p,a}(h)
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p,a}(h)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t.
\]

\end_inset

Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})+R_{p,a}(h) & =\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})+\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\left((\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)-(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)\right)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})+\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t-\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})+\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t-\frac{1}{p!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a)(h^{(p)})\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}(\mathrm{D}^{p}f)(a+th)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so we really just need to show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{p-1,a}(h)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{(1-t)^{p-1}}{(p-1)!}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a+th)(h^{(p)})\mathrm{d}t
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 By using the identification 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p},W)\simeq\mathrm{Hom}(V,\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W))$
\end_inset

 it suffices to prove that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W)$
\end_inset

 we have an equality
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}(p-1)(1-t)^{p-2}(\mathrm{D}^{p-1}f(a+th)-\mathrm{D}^{p-1}f(a))\mathrm{d}t=\int_{0}^{1}(1-t)^{p-1}\mathrm{D}^{p}f(a+th)h\mathrm{d}t,
\]

\end_inset

where the evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in V$
\end_inset

 on the right is really evaluation in the first slot of a symmetric multilinear
 mapping on 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{p}$
\end_inset

, since then evaluation on 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(p-1)}=(h,\cdots,h)\in V^{p-1}$
\end_inset

 (which can be moved inside a definite integral) and division by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)!$
\end_inset

 will yield what we want.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\mathrm{D}^{p-1}f\colon U\to\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 map and we want to show
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}(p-1)(1-t)^{p-2}(g(a+th)-g(a))\mathrm{d}t=\int_{0}^{1}(1-t)^{p-1}\mathrm{D}g(a+th)(h)\mathrm{d}t.
\]

\end_inset

This essentially comes down to integration by parts.
 We can rewrite our desired equation as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(a)=\int_{0}^{1}((p-1)(1-t)^{p-2}g(a+th)-(1-t)^{p-1}\mathrm{D}g(a+th)h)\mathrm{d}t.
\]

\end_inset

Consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\colon(-1,1+\varepsilon)\to\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W)
\]

\end_inset

defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(t)=-(1-t)^{p-1}g(a+th)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 is small enough so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\varepsilon)\|h\|<r$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a+th\in\mathrm{B}_{r}(a)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(-1,1+\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

, a straightforward application of the Chain Rule yields that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi'(t)=\mathrm{D}\phi(t)(1)=(p-1)(1-t)^{p-2}g(a+th)-(1-t)^{p-1}\mathrm{D}g(a+th)h
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W)$
\end_inset

.
 This is exactly the integrand we need, so we are reduced to proving 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)=\int_{0}^{1}\phi'$
\end_inset

.
 But by the second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (applied componentwise
 with respect to a basis of the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Mult}(V^{p-1},W)$
\end_inset

, say), this latter integral is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(1)-\phi(0)$
\end_inset

, and from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 this is exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Morse Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-function with 
\begin_inset Formula $2\leq p\leq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\in U$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}f(u_{0})=0$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a critical point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We seek a convenient coordinate system on a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that will help us to see how 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 behaves near 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The Morse Lemma in the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 case is this: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional vector space and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 an open set.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a non-degenerate critical point at 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\in U$
\end_inset

.
 For a suitable 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-coordinate system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}):U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

on an open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u_{0})=0$
\end_inset

, the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]=f\circ\varphi^{-1}\colon\varphi(U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

-coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[f](\boldsymbol{a})=\sum_{i=1}^{r}a_{i}^{2}-\sum_{j=1}^{s}a_{r+j}^{2}\label{eq:rewritefjklj}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\varphi(U_{0})$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)=(r,n-r)$
\end_inset

 the signature of the quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{f}(u_{0})\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 associated to the symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We could rewrite 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:rewritefjklj})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[f]=\sum_{i=1}^{r}x_{i}^{2}-\sum_{j=1}^{s}x_{r+j}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Separation of Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall deduce the Morse lemma from a more general result that is called
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

separation of variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional vector space and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 an open set.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a non-degenerate critical point at 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\in U$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\colon U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 on an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u_{0})=0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[f]=f\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon x_{1}^{2}+F$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(U_{0})\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, this theorem just says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function near the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=f'(0)=0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(0)\neq0$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is a non-degenerate critical point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\varepsilon k^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\pm1$
\end_inset

 and some smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 near the origin with 
\begin_inset Formula $k(0)=0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $k'(0)\neq0$
\end_inset

 (as such a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 provides a local 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-coordinate near the origin on the real line).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1: 
\series default
We show that since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=tg(t)$
\end_inset

 for a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 near the origin.
 Indeed, we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t):=\int_{0}^{1}f'(ty)\mathrm{d}y.
\]

\end_inset

By the theorem on differentiation through the integral sign, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g^{(n)}(t)=\int_{0}^{1}y^{n}f^{(n+1)}(ty)\mathrm{d}y.\label{eq:integrandinjklfsd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(n)}(t)$
\end_inset

 is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 since the integrand on the righthand side of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integrandinjklfsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 fixed and since the integrand on the righthand side of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integrandinjklfsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is dominated by some constant (we are secretly applying the dominated convergen
ce theoerem here).
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function, and by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{f(ty)}{t}\Big|_{y=0}^{y=1}=\frac{f(t)}{t},
\]

\end_inset

whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $t\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=tg(t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (including 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0=g(0)$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is smooth and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0)=f'(0)=0$
\end_inset

, we can repeat the process and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=t^{2}G(t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 smooth near the origin.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G(0)=f''(0)\neq0$
\end_inset

, so if this has the same sign as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\pm1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=\varepsilon t^{2}(\varepsilon G)(t)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon G$
\end_inset

 a smooth function that is positive at the origin.
 Hence, it admits a smooth positive square root (possibly on a smaller open
 neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), so we get the result for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $k=t\sqrt{\varepsilon G}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\dim V>1$
\end_inset

.
 Additive translation has no effect on derivative maps, nor on Hessians.
 Thus by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U-u_{0}=\{u-u_{0}\mid u\in U\}$
\end_inset

 and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{u_{0}}\colon U-u_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{u_{0}}(u-u_{0})=f(u)$
\end_inset

) if necessary, we may suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(0)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Since the symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{f}(0)$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, its associated quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{f}(0)\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 By the structure theorem for quadratic spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we may choose linear coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{1},\dots,y_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}_{f}(0)$
\end_inset

 is in standard diagonal form, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon y_{1}^{^{2}}+\cdots$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $-f$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y_{1}}f(0,\boldsymbol{0})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y_{1}}^{2}f(0,\boldsymbol{0})=1\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the implicit function theorem implies for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{2},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 near the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 satisfying
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{y_{1}}f(g(\boldsymbol{y}),\boldsymbol{y})=0,
\]

\end_inset

(so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{0})=0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Thus if we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 then by continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 we conclude that for 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{2}|,\dots,|a_{n}|$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

) the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 has a unique critical point at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-c,c)$
\end_inset

 and the second derivative at this critical point is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 By taking 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 possibly smaller, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{2}|,\dots,|a_{n}|<c$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sufficiently small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-c,c)$
\end_inset

 has a unique minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 with positive second derivative there.
 Define the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})=f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})-f(g(\boldsymbol{y}),\boldsymbol{y}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},\dots,a_{n}\in(-c,c)$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 is non-negative with a unique zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 and a positive second derivative at this minimum point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 is the square of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 near the origin.
 By defining the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\boldsymbol{y}):=f(g(\boldsymbol{y}),\boldsymbol{y})
\]

\end_inset

near the origin we get 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})=h^{2}+F(\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

, so we would be done as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{h,\boldsymbol{y}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 coordinate system near the origin.
 By the inverse function theorem, this amounts to the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial_{y_{1}}h)(0,\boldsymbol{0})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But such non-vanishing is clear because for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(y_{1},\boldsymbol{0})^{2}=f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{0})-f(g(\boldsymbol{0}),\boldsymbol{0})=f(y_{1},\boldsymbol{0})
\]

\end_inset

has Taylor expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{2}+\cdots$
\end_inset

 at the origin (as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0,\boldsymbol{0})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y_{1}}f(0,\boldsymbol{0})=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{y_{1}}^{2}f(0,\boldsymbol{0})=\varepsilon=1$
\end_inset

), so the Taylor expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(y_{1},\boldsymbol{0})$
\end_inset

 at the origin must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm y_{1}+\cdots$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the square of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function near the origin.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}'=y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 and note that by the inverse function theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 coordinate system near the origin.
 Thus if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 expressed in these coordinates, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K(y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function near the origin that vanishes for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}'=0$
\end_inset

.
 By applying the fundamental theorem of calculus to 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t)=K(ty_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 all fixed, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y}) & =K(y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{t}K(ty_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =y_{1}'\int_{0}^{1}(\partial_{1}K)(ty_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})\mathrm{d}t\\
 & =y_{1}'I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})\\
 & =(y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y}))I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})=\int_{0}^{1}(\partial_{1}K)(ty_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})\mathrm{d}t,
\]

\end_inset

where the integrand is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 (by differentiation through the integral sign and the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 property of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, we have made a factorization
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})=(y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y}))I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})\label{eq:fjskldfjlksdjfklsd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function near the origin.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|a_{i}|<c$
\end_inset

.
 As we have seen above, 
\begin_inset Formula $k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})\geq0$
\end_inset

 has a critical point with positive second derivative at its unique minimum
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-c,c)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 vanishing at this point, so the Taylor expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 begins in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 with positive coefficient.
 In particular, by considering Taylor expansions it follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:fjskldfjlksdjfklsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}=g(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 and has positive derivative at this point.
 Running through the same integration trick with the fundamental theorem
 of calculus again, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})=(y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y}))J(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $J(g(\boldsymbol{y}),\boldsymbol{y})>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 near the origin.
 Feeding this into 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:fjskldfjlksdjfklsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and working with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 coordinates near the origin we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
K(y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y}) & =k(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})\\
 & =(y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y}))I(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})\\
 & =(y_{1}-g(\boldsymbol{y})^{2})J(y_{1},\boldsymbol{y})\\
 & =y_{1}'^{2}\widetilde{J}(y_{1}',\boldsymbol{y})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{J}(0,\boldsymbol{0})>0$
\end_inset

.
 We may therefore extract a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 positive square root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{J}$
\end_inset

 near the origin, so indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) is a square of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function near the origin.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Manifold with Corners
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq m$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
sector 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty subset of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma=\{w\in W\mid\ell_{1}(w)\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}(w)\geq c_{k}\}\label{eq:ksectorlong}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},\dots,c_{k}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and linearly independent 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1},\dots\ell_{k}\in W^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 We often use the shorthand notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 to denote 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:ksectorlong})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in W$
\end_inset

 is a point, then the translation 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is also a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w+\Sigma=\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1}+\ell_{1}(w),\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}+\ell_{k}(w)\}.
\]

\end_inset

A 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
sector 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=W$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq k\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector.
 There are exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 translated hyperplanes 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap\partial\Sigma$
\end_inset

 contains a non-empty open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, these 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

's are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{i}=c_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 uniquely determines 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and the pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ell_{i},c_{i})$
\end_inset

 up to positive scaling.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 to an ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\ell}=(\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k},\dots,\ell_{m})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{m})$
\end_inset

 be the ordered basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 whose dual basis is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell_{i}(e_{j})=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i,j\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\sum_{i=1}^{k}c_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 denote the translated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-w$
\end_inset

.
 Then after identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 using the ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma_{w}=[0,\infty)^{k}\times\mathbb{R}^{m-k}.
\]

\end_inset

It suffices to show that there are exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 hyperplanes 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap\partial\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 contains a non-empty open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 First let us calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{int}\,\Sigma_{w} & =\mathrm{int}([0,\infty)^{k}\times\mathbb{R}^{m-k})\\
 & =\mathrm{int}([0,\infty))^{k}\times\mathrm{int}(\mathbb{R})^{m-k}\\
 & =(0,\infty)^{k}\times\mathbb{R}^{m-k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\Sigma_{w} & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{k}[0,\infty)^{i-1}\times\{0\}\times[0,\infty)^{k-i}\times\mathbb{R}^{m-k},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we make the convention that 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\infty)^{0}=\{0\}$
\end_inset

 in the union above.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the union of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{w}\cap H_{i}=\partial\Sigma_{w}\cap H_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}=\{\ell_{i}=0\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

, each of which contains a non-empty open in the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}=\{\ell_{i}=0\}\cap\bigcap\limits _{j\neq i}\{\ell_{j}>0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subseteq W$
\end_inset

 is some other hyperplane such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap\partial\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 contains a non-empty open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H\ne H_{i}$
\end_inset

, the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a proper subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap\partial\Sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 is contained in the union of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap H_{i}$
\end_inset

's, but this implies that a finite union of proper subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 contains a non-empty open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 Since the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{i}=c_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 determines the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ell_{i},c_{i})$
\end_inset

 up to a nonzero scaling factor, it remains to prove that if we switch the
 order of any of the initial defining inequalities then the sector changes.
 But this is obvious.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The lemma above makes the following definition well-posed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}=\{\ell_{i}=c_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 translated hyperplanes which are uniquely determined by the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq W$
\end_inset

.
 We also set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}=\{\ell_{i}=0\}\cap\bigcap\limits _{j\neq i}\{\ell_{j}>0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that the topological boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial\Sigma=\bigcup_{i=1}^{k}\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{i}=c_{i},\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}\}.
\]

\end_inset

A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 has 
\series bold
index 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}(x)=c_{i}$
\end_inset

 for exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 indices 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq k$
\end_inset

).
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 with index 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in H_{j}$
\end_inset

 for exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=[0,\infty)^{3}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Sigma_{0} & =\{x_{1}>0,x_{2}>0,x_{3}>0\}\\
\Sigma_{1} & =\{x_{1}=0,x_{2}>0,x_{3}>0\}\cup\{x_{1}>0,x_{2}=0,x_{3}>0\}\cup\{x_{1}>0,x_{2}>0,x_{3}=0\}\\
\Sigma_{2} & =\{x_{1}=0,x_{2}=0,x_{3}>0\}\cup\{x_{1}=0,x_{2}>0,x_{3}=0\}\cup\{x_{1}>0,x_{2}=0,x_{3}=0\}\\
\Sigma_{3} & =\{x_{1}=0,x_{2}=0,x_{3}=0\}=\{(0,0,0)^{\top}\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The following result summarizes some nice topological relations (easily
 visualized by picturing the non-negative orthant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=[0,\infty)^{3}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{3}=W$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=[0,\infty)^{2}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\{\ell_{1}\geq c_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\geq c_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sector in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,\Sigma=\Sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=\overline{\Sigma_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq r\leq k$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and the connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 and are given by the intersections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i_{1}}\cap\cdots\cap H_{i_{r}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i_{1}<\cdots<i_{r}\leq k$
\end_inset

, with this intersection also open in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i_{1}}\cap\cdots\cap H_{i_{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq k$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Sigma_{r}}=\bigcup_{r'\geq r}\Sigma_{r'}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 that lie in the closure of exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, using just 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 we can locally topologically encode the property of having index 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 has index 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 if and ony if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 admits arbitrarily small open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 that meet the closures of exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U\cap\Sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is tremendously important for globalization to manifolds with corners.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calculus on Sectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

 be two finite-dimensional vector spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'\subseteq V'$
\end_inset

 be two sectors.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq p\leq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that we are given non-empty open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to U'$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-morphism.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 there is a derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)$
\end_inset

 that is a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to V'$
\end_inset

, so by the Chain Rule if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a linear isomorphism and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim V=\dim V'$
\end_inset

.
 In general, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map then it is impossible to say anything about the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in U'\subseteq\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 in terms of the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U\subseteq\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the index could go up or down; consider putting 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1)$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or along the edge of a square in the plane.
 However, to get the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-premanifolds with corners off of the ground we just need to build a consistent
 theory of local 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-charts, and so rather than studying general 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 maps what we need to study are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms.
 That is, we need to prove:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to U'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-isomorphism then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has the same index in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U\cap\Sigma_{r})=U'\cap\Sigma_{r}'.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove the theorem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon U'\to U$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 are non-empty, the Chain Rule ensures 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim V=\dim V'$
\end_inset

; let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be this common dimension.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r}=U\cap\Sigma_{r}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r}'=U'\cap\Sigma_{r}'$
\end_inset

 .
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must carry 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must carry 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}'$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{0}=f(U_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 By symmetry, we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 since it is the intersection of two open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=U\cap\Sigma_{0}=U\cap\mathrm{int}\,\Sigma.
\]

\end_inset

The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is therefore a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 mapping in the usual sense, with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{D}f|_{U_{0}})(u_{0})=\mathrm{D}f(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 as linear maps from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 is a linear isomorphism (by the Chain Rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

) the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{0}}\colon U_{0}\to V'$
\end_inset

 between open sets in vector spaces satisfies the hypotheses for the usual
 inverse function theorem at 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 (that is, its total derivative map at 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a linear isomorphism).
 Thus, by the usual inverse function theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{0}}$
\end_inset

 gives a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism between small opens around 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U_{0})\subseteq U'\subseteq V'$
\end_inset

 contains an open set around 
\begin_inset Formula $f(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(u_{0})\in U'\cap\mathrm{int}_{V'}(\Sigma')=U'\cap\Sigma'_{0}=U_{0}'
\]

\end_inset

as desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>1$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r}$
\end_inset

 is topologically determined in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U\backslash U_{0}$
\end_inset

 admitting arbitrarily small open neighborhoods meeting the closures of
 exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The same holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r}'$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}'$
\end_inset

, so since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are inverse homeomorphisms and we have already proved that they identify
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}'$
\end_inset

 we are reduced to the case of index 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\notin f(U_{0})=U_{0}'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has index at least 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq\Sigma'$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has index exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 One this is setttled, it makes sense to define the notion of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-premanifold with corners (in the sense of being a structured 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space locally isomorphic to an open in a sector in a vector space equipped
 with its natural 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space structure given by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-functions on its open subsets), but we will need to show more, namely that
 the locally closed set of points with a given index has a natural structure
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-premanifold.
 We take up these issues and more in what follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Using the notation as in the preceding discussion, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and we seek a contradiction if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in U_{r}'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq2$
\end_inset

, which is to say (after relabelling) that we seek a contradiction if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in H_{1}'\cap H_{2}'$
\end_inset

 for two of the translated hyperplanes that give 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

faces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 (this possibility can only occur if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, so we now assume this to be the case).
 By translation, we may and do assume (for simplicity of language) that
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 are the origin in their respective vector spaces.
 In particular, any translated hyperplane through these points is a genuine
 hyperplane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that in fact if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in H'$
\end_inset

 for a hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $H'$
\end_inset

 that gives a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

face
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)\colon V\to V'$
\end_inset

 carries 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $H'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the unique hyperplane in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 that is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

face
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (here we use that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has index 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

).
 Granting this, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)$
\end_inset

 sends 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}'\cap H_{2}'$
\end_inset

, but this is impossible for dimension reasons because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)\colon V\to V'$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}'\cap H_{2}'$
\end_inset

 has codimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

.
 This contradiction settles the problem for points with index 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, granting the above claim that must now be proved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By suitable choice of linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{n}=0\}$
\end_inset

 is the unique hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 through the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 giving a face of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, and that associated to this hyperplane the inequality 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (rather than 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-t_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) arises in the definition of the sector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We can likewise suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V'=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H'=\{t_{n}'=0\}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}'\geq0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the corresponding inequality that arises in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a point of index 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, near 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is open in the half-space 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{n}\geq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, since our problems are local near 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we may replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}=\{t_{n}\geq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}'=\{t_{n}'\geq0\}$
\end_inset

 to reduce to the setup in the following result.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional nonzero vector spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}=\{\ell\geq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}'=\{\ell'\geq0\}$
\end_inset

 be closed half-spaces defined by nonzero linear functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell'\in V'^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 be an open subset around a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\partial\mathbf{H}=\{\ell=0\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbf{H}'$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

-map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in\partial\mathbf{H}'=\{\ell'=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}f(x)\colon V\to V'$
\end_inset

 sends the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 into the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\mathbf{H}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Structure on Singular Strata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq p\leq\infty$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
premanifold with corners 
\series default
is a structured 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 that is locally isomorphic (in the sense of structured 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-spaces) to an open subset of a sector in a finite-dimensional vector space
 (equipped with its natural 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space structure given by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-functions on open subsets of itself).
 If the underlying topological space is Hausdorff and second-countable,
 then we call it a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-manifold with corners
\series default
.
 We usually write 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In view of the local results on sectors, we may use any 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-chart to determine the property of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 having index 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

, and the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{r}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of points with index 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is locally closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\geq r}=\cup_{i\geq r}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 are closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\geq1}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
boundary 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial X$
\end_inset

; the intrinsic notion (that makes no reference to an ambient topological
 space containing 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

) must not be confused with the (extrinsic) notion of topological boundary
 for a subset of a topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Whitney's Extension Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Whitney).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

 be finite-dimensional nonzero vector spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a sector.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\Sigma$
\end_inset

 be an open subset and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in U$
\end_inset

 a point.
 Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq p\leq\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Any 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to V'$
\end_inset

 locally extends to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map on an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 That is, there exists an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\colon\widetilde{U}\to V'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}|_{U\cap\widetilde{U}}=f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Derivative of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-premanifolds and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-mapping.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We can define a linear mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x)\colon\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)\to\mathrm{T}_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
derivative 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\in\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)$
\end_inset

 is a tangent vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (so it is a point-derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}:\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

), then we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}F(x)(\vec{v})=\vec{v}\circ F^{*}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pullback map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 defined on germs via 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f\circ F$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\circ F^{*}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a point-derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and that the resulting map of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x)\colon\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)\to\mathrm{T}_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 sending 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\circ F^{*}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,f]_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[V,g]_{y}$
\end_inset

 be two germs at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 being a sufficiently small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

).
 Then working with representatives, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(f\cdot g) & =\vec{v}(F^{*}(f\cdot g))\\
 & =\vec{v}(F^{*}(f)\cdot F^{*}(g))\\
 & =\vec{v}(F^{*}(f))\cdot F^{*}(g)(x)+F^{*}(f)(x)\cdot\vec{v}(F^{*}(g))\\
 & =(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(f)\cdot g(y)+f(y)\cdot(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(g).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes Leibnitz Rule.
 Similarly, for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(f+rg) & =\vec{v}(F^{*}(f+rg))\\
 & =\vec{v}'(F^{*}(f)+rF^{*}(g))\\
 & =\vec{v}(F^{*}(f))+r\vec{v}(F^{*}(g))\\
 & =(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(f)+r(\vec{v}\circ F^{*})(g).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix Representation of Derivative is a Jacobian Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be respective 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 charts centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 respectively, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\simeq\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon V\simeq\varphi(V)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 having respective component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=(\varphi_{1},\dots,\varphi_{m})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=(\psi_{1},\dots,\psi_{n})$
\end_inset

 on the source and target.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)$
\end_inset

 has the ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 has the ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{\psi_{j}}|_{y}\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is natural to ask for the matrix of the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x):\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)\to\mathrm{T}_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with respect to these ordered bases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{j}=\psi_{j}\circ F$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the ordered bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{\psi_{j}}|_{y}\}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $(j,i)$
\end_inset

-entry given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}F_{j})(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $F|_{U}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}F(x)(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x})(\psi_{j}) & =(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}\circ F^{*})(\psi_{j})|_{x}\\
 & =\partial_{\varphi_{i}}(\psi_{j}\circ F)(x)\\
 & =(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}F_{j})(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}F(x)(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}((\partial_{\varphi_{i}}F_{j})(x))\partial_{\psi_{j}}|_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\xrightarrow{\simeq}\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-mapping between two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-premanifolds.
 Let's calculate the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=(t_{1},\dots,t_{m})=\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, then by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{j}=t_{j}\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

, so we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}\varphi(x)(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x})(t_{j}) & =(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}\circ\varphi^{*})(t_{j})|_{x}\\
 & =\partial_{\varphi_{i}}(t_{j}\circ\varphi)(x)\\
 & =(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}\varphi_{j})(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}\varphi(x)(\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{x})=\partial_{t_{i}}|_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Chain Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G\colon X''\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon X'\to X$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 mappings between 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 premanifolds.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x''\in X''$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x'')=x'\in X'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x')=x\in X$
\end_inset

, the composite linear mapping
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathrm{d}F)(G(x''))\circ\mathrm{d}G(x'')\colon\mathrm{T}_{x''}(X'')\to\mathrm{T}_{x'}(X')\to\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)
\]

\end_inset

is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(F\circ G)(x'')$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We choose a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}''\in\mathrm{T}_{x''}(X'')$
\end_inset

, so we want to prove
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}(F\circ G)(x'')(\vec{v}'')=(\mathrm{d}F)(G(x''))(\mathrm{d}G(x'')(\vec{v}''))
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 This is an equality of point derivations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and by the definitions of the derivative mappings the left side is 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}''\circ(F\circ G)^{*}$
\end_inset

 and the right side is 
\begin_inset Formula $(\vec{v}''\circ G^{*})\circ F^{*}=\vec{v}''\circ(G^{*}\circ F^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, it suffices to show that the composite of the mappings 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\mathcal{O}_{x'}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{*}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x'}'\to\mathcal{O}_{x''}''$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $(F\circ G)^{*}$
\end_inset

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula $(F\circ G)^{*}=G^{*}\circ F^{*}$
\end_inset

, however this is clear.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Derivative Mappings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be respective 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 charts centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 respectively, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\simeq\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon V\simeq\varphi(V)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 having respective component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 on the source and target.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)$
\end_inset

 has the ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{x_{i}}|_{x}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 has the ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{y_{j}}|_{y}\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is natural to ask for the matrix of the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x):T_{x}(X)\to T_{y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 with respect to these ordered bases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{j}=y_{j}\circ F$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}F(x)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the ordered bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{x_{i}}|_{x}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{y_{j}}|_{y}\}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $(j,i)$
\end_inset

-entry given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial_{x_{i}}F_{j})(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $F|_{U}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}F(x)(\partial_{x_{i}}|_{x})(y_{j}) & =(\partial_{x_{i}}\circ F^{*})(y_{j})|_{x}\\
 & =\partial_{x_{i}}(y_{j}\circ F)(x)\\
 & =(\partial_{x_{i}}F_{j})(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}F(x)(\partial_{x_{i}}|_{x})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}((\partial_{x_{i}}F_{j})(x))\partial_{y_{j}}|_{y}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}\varphi(x)(\partial_{x_{i}}|_{x}) & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}((\partial_{x_{i}}\varphi_{j})(x))\partial_{t_{j}}|_{t}.\\
 & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}((\partial_{x_{i}}x_{j})(x))\partial_{t_{j}}|_{t}\\
 & =\partial_{t_{i}}|_{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parametric Curves and Velocity Vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 premanifold with corners.
 A 
\series bold
parametrized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 curve 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $c\colon I\to X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 a nontrivial (not a point nor the empty set) interval, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(0)=p$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\partial X$
\end_inset

, then we also require 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to be in the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Note that a parametirze curve is the data of the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and it may not be injective or have smooth image.
 For instance, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $c\colon(-1,1)\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)=(t^{2},t^{3})$
\end_inset

 has image contained in the locus 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{2}-x_{1}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in the plane that has a cusp at the origin.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $c'\colon(-1/2,1/2)\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $c'(t)=c(2t)$
\end_inset

 has the same image as 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, but we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 different than 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 moves twice as quickly as 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a nontrivial interval and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\colon I\to X$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 mapping.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in I$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
velocity vector 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma'(a):=\mathrm{d}\gamma(a)(\partial_{t}|_{a})\in\mathrm{T}_{\gamma(a)}(X)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}|_{a}\in\mathrm{T}_{a}(I)$
\end_inset

 is the canonical basis vector (sending a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 germ 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to the old-fashioned derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(a)$
\end_inset

 in the sense of calculus).
 In particular, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma'(a)=\sum\gamma_{i}'(a)\partial_{\varphi_{i}}|_{\gamma(a)}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Charts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 A 
\series bold
real
\series default
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-chart 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (or more simply 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
chart 
\series default
or just 
\series bold
chart
\series default
) consists of a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open and nonempty and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we say the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
contains 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, and we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
centered 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=0$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\series default
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
topological 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-premanifold 
\series default
(or more simply an
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-premanifold
\series default
) if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is contained in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-chart of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a
\series bold
 topological 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-manifold 
\series default
(or more simply 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-manifold
\series default
 or just 
\series bold
manifold
\series default
) if it is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-premanifold and is Hausdorff and second countable.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\simeq\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For any set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Map}(S,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Map}(S,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 has the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra, where addition and multiplication are defined pointwise.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}\colon\mathrm{Map}(\varphi(U),\mathbb{R})\to\mathrm{Map}(U,\mathbb{R})
\]

\end_inset

be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}g=g\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

 for all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon\varphi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}g$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
pullback 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a function, we define it 
\series bold
pushforward 
\series default
with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to be the map 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1})^{*}f=f\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard linear coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

: thus 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}(\boldsymbol{a})=a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We often denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 to be the pullback of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

: thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}=t_{i}\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We can think of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 as being coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

: we call them 
\series bold
local coordinates 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\varphi_{1}^{3}+\cdots+\varphi_{n}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x) & =(\varphi_{1}^{3}+\cdots+\varphi_{n}^{3})(x)\\
 & =(t_{1}^{3}+\cdots+t_{n}^{3})\varphi(x)\\
 & =(t_{1}^{3}+\cdots+t_{n}^{3})(\boldsymbol{a})\\
 & =a_{1}^{3}+\cdots+a_{n}^{3},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Functions are not the only thing we can pullback (or pushforward).
 Indeed, we can pullback the partial derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t_{i}}$
\end_inset

: we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\varphi_{i}}:=\partial_{t_{i}}\circ(\varphi^{-1})^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{\varphi_{i}}(\varphi_{j}) & =\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Furthermore, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the pushforward of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\varphi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 in this case: 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t_{i}}=\partial_{\varphi_{i}}\circ\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\varphi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear map which satisfies Leibniz law precisely because 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi^{-1})^{*}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplesphereexample}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{n}=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\|\boldsymbol{x}\|=1\}.
\]

\end_inset

Here we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

.
 This description 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 comes equipped with 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
coordinates: every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\boldsymbol{x}\|=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)$
\end_inset

 be the north pole and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}=S^{n}\backslash\{\boldsymbol{x}_{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{N},\varphi_{N})$
\end_inset

 be a chart where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}=(t_{1},\dots,t_{n})$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{N}(\boldsymbol{x})=\left(\frac{x_{1}}{1-x_{n+1}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{1-x_{n+1}}\right)=(t_{1},\dots,t_{n})=\boldsymbol{t}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}(U_{N})=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}^{-1}\colon\varphi(U_{N})\to U_{N}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{N}^{-1}(\boldsymbol{t})=\left(\frac{2t_{1}}{\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}+1},\dots,\frac{2t_{n}}{\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}+1},\frac{\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}-1}{\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}+1}\right)=\boldsymbol{x}.
\]

\end_inset

To see why this is the case, first note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}$
\end_inset

 is continuous since each of its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N,i}=t_{i}\circ\varphi_{N}$
\end_inset

 (given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N,i}=x_{i}/(1-x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

) is continuous as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}\neq-1$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is continuous as well.
 Futhermore, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi_{N,i}\circ\varphi_{N}^{-1})(\boldsymbol{t}) & =\varphi_{N,i}(\boldsymbol{x})\\
 & =\frac{x_{i}}{1-x_{n+1}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{1-\frac{\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}-1}{1+\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}}}\right)\left(\frac{2t_{i}}{1+\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1+\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}}{2}\right)\left(\frac{2t_{i}}{1+\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}}\right)\\
 & =t_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}(\varphi_{N}^{-1}(\boldsymbol{t}))=\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

.
 A similar calculation shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}^{-1}(\varphi_{N}(\boldsymbol{x}))=\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{S}=(0,\dots,0,-1)$
\end_inset

 be the south pole and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}=S^{n}\backslash\{\boldsymbol{x}_{S}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{N},\varphi_{N})$
\end_inset

 be a chart where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}=(\widetilde{t}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{t}_{n})$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{S}(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}})=\left(\frac{\widetilde{x}_{1}}{1+\widetilde{x}_{n+1}},\dots,\frac{\widetilde{x}_{n}}{1+\widetilde{x}_{n+1}}\right)=(\widetilde{t}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{t}_{n})=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{S}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{S}(U_{S})=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{S}^{-1}\colon\varphi(U_{S})\to U_{S}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{S}^{-1}(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}})=\left(\frac{2\widetilde{t}_{1}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}},\dots,\frac{2\widetilde{t}_{n}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}},\frac{1-\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}\right)=\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}}.
\]

\end_inset

Now observe that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi_{N,i}\circ\varphi_{S}^{-1})(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}) & =\varphi_{N,i}(\widetilde{\boldsymbol{x}})\\
 & =\frac{\widetilde{x}_{i}}{1-\widetilde{x}_{n+1}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{2\widetilde{t}_{i}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{1-\left(\frac{1-\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}\right)}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{2\widetilde{t}_{i}}{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}\right)\left(\frac{1+\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}{2\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\widetilde{t}_{i}}{\|\widetilde{\boldsymbol{t}}\|^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}\circ\varphi_{S}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{S}(U_{N}\cap U_{S})=\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 A similar calculation shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{S,i}\circ\varphi_{N}^{-1}=t_{i}/\|\boldsymbol{t}\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 and hence is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}(U_{N}\cap U_{S})=\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphereexample})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we noticed that the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 came equipped with global coordinates.
 This makes it easy, for example, to define functions out of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In general however, a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 will not come equipped with global coordinates (but when they do, we should
 definitely make use of them!).
 Here's another manifold which admits nice global coordinates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleprojectiveplane}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Real Projective Plane) The real projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 which pass through the origin.
 We wish to describe every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

global coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{0},a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{\boldsymbol{a}}$
\end_inset

 denote the linear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{\boldsymbol{a}}=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 With this notation in mind, observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a line which passes through the origin, then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 has the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=L_{\boldsymbol{a}}=\mathrm{V}(\ell_{\boldsymbol{a}}):=\left\{ \boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\ell_{\boldsymbol{a}}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is unique up to scaling by a nonzero constant.
 This means that if 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\boldsymbol{a}}=L_{\boldsymbol{a}'}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\boldsymbol{a}=\boldsymbol{a}'$
\end_inset

 (that is, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda a_{i}=a_{i}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore we have a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\mapsto L_{\boldsymbol{a}}$
\end_inset

 which is surjective but not one-to-one.
 However if we define an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\sim\boldsymbol{a}'$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\boldsymbol{a}=\boldsymbol{a}'$
\end_inset

, then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 induces a bijection from 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\})\slash\sim$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which sends the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{a}]:=[a_{0}:a_{1}\cdots:a_{n}]$
\end_inset

 (represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{0},a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

) to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\boldsymbol{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus our global coordinates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 look like 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{a}]=[a_{0}:a_{1}\cdots:a_{n}]$
\end_inset

, where we keep in mind that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{a}]=[\lambda\boldsymbol{a}]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now that we've described what the global coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 look like, let's give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 the structure of a topological space.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the projection map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 inherits the sturcture a topological space via the quotient topology.
 This is the weakest topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 In particular, a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}\subseteq\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is said open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Note that in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 be the open ball in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 centered at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 and with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi^{-1}\pi(\mathrm{B}_{r}(\boldsymbol{a})) & =\{\boldsymbol{b}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\pi(\boldsymbol{b})\in\pi(\mathrm{B}_{r}(\boldsymbol{a}))\}\\
 & =\{\boldsymbol{b}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid[\boldsymbol{b}]=[\boldsymbol{a}']\text{ where }\|\boldsymbol{a}-\boldsymbol{a}'\|<r\}\\
 & =\{\boldsymbol{b}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\|\boldsymbol{a}-\boldsymbol{b}/\lambda\|<r\text{ for some }\lambda\neq0\}\\
 & =\{\boldsymbol{b}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\|\lambda\boldsymbol{a}-\boldsymbol{b}\|<\lambda r\text{ for some }\lambda\neq0\}\\
 & =\bigcup_{\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\}}\mathrm{B}_{\lambda r}(\lambda\boldsymbol{a}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Now in general, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if the corresponding quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon X\to X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In this case, a lot of nice things happen.
 First of all, 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

 is automatically second-countable.
 Secondly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then its images 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho(B_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Thirdly, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff if and only if the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\sim}=\{(x,y)\in X\times X\mid x\sim y\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is second countable since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is and to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, we just need to check that the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=\Gamma_{\sim}$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 In our case, the graph looks like
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Gamma & =\{(\boldsymbol{a},\boldsymbol{b})\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\mid[\boldsymbol{a}]=[\boldsymbol{b}]\}\\
 & =\{(\boldsymbol{a},\lambda\boldsymbol{a})\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\mid\text{for some }\lambda\neq0\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 by using the sequential criterion for subspaces of a metric space to be
 closed: if 
\begin_inset Formula $((\boldsymbol{a}_{n},\lambda_{n}\boldsymbol{a}_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{a}_{n},\lambda_{n}\boldsymbol{a}_{n})\to(\boldsymbol{a},\lambda\boldsymbol{a})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{n}\to\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}\to\lambda$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{a},\lambda\boldsymbol{a})\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 the structure of a real manifold.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is covered by 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 open sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{U}_{i}:=\mathrm{D}(x_{i}):=\{[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{RP}^{n}\mid x_{i}\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined since if 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\widetilde{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda\boldsymbol{x}]\in\widetilde{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\widetilde{\mathbb{R}}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda x_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 This also implies that it is open since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\widetilde{U}_{i})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}\mid x_{i}\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

 has a nice representative: if 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\widetilde{U}_{i}$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\boldsymbol{x}]=[x_{0}:\cdots:x_{i}:\cdots:x_{n}]=\left[\frac{x_{0}}{x_{i}}:\cdots:1:\cdots:\frac{x_{n}}{x_{i}}\right]=[\boldsymbol{x}/x_{i}].
\]

\end_inset

This gives us an idea of how to define our chart: let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{U}_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 be the chart, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=(x_{0,i},\dots,x_{j,i},\dots x_{n,i})=\boldsymbol{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}([\boldsymbol{x}])=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{i}},\dots,\frac{x_{j}}{x_{i}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{x_{i}}\right)=\boldsymbol{x}_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j,i}:=t_{j}\circ\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th coordinate function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j,i}\colon\mathbb{RP}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j,i}([\boldsymbol{x}])=x_{j}/x_{i}.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(\widetilde{U}_{i})=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}^{-1}\colon\phi_{i}(\widetilde{U}_{i})\to U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}^{-1}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})=\left[x_{0,i}:\cdots:x_{j,i}:\cdots:x_{n,i}\right]=[\boldsymbol{x}].
\]

\end_inset

Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq i'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{j,i}\circ\phi_{i'}^{-1}(\boldsymbol{x}_{i'}) & =\phi_{j,i}(\left[x_{0,i'}:\cdots:x_{j,i'}:\cdots:x_{n,i'}\right])\\
 & =x_{j,i'}/x_{i,i'}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Construction of Products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 premanifolds.
 The topological product 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod X_{i}$
\end_inset

 ought to admit a natural 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 premanifold structure, using as local 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 charts the maps
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We first recall a few definitions from point-set topology.
 A topological space is 
\series bold
second countable
\series default
 if it has a countable basis.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is any open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Hausdorff
\series default
 if for every pair of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

, there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 An 
\series bold
open cover
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 whose union 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The Hausdorff condition and second countability are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hereditary properties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; they are inherited by subspaces: a subspace of a Hausdorff space is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is second countable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is second countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, choose a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'=U\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighboorhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $V'=V\cap M'$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the subspace topology and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\cap V'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}'\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a countable basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}'=B_{i}\cap M'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that there is a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
chart
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate neighborhood
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate open set
\series default
, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
coordinate map
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
coordinate system on 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
centered
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart on the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\phi|_{V})$
\end_inset

 is a chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi|_{V}:V\to\phi(V)$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
topological manifold
\series default
 is a Hausdorff, second countable, locally Euclidean space.
 It is said to be of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if it is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is covered by a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map.
 It is the prime example of a topological manifold.
 Every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is also a topological manifold, with chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,1_{U})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cusp).
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a topological manifold.
 By virtue of being a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, it is Hausdorff and second countable.
 It is locally Euclidean because it is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,x^{2/3})\mapsto x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=5, xmin=-5, ymax=5, ymin=-5, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({x^3},{4*x^2});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A cross).
 The cross can be described as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(r,0)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}\cup\{(0,r)\mid r\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We show that the cross in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with the subspace topology is not locally Euclidean at the intersection
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(0,0)$
\end_inset

, and so cannot be a manifold.
 Suppose the cross is locally Euclidean of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 homeomorphic to an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=B_{\varepsilon}(0)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 mapping to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 The homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to B$
\end_inset

 restricts to a homemorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}\to B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is either connected if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 or has two connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 has four connected components, there can be no homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $U\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B\setminus\{p\}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradiction proves that the cross is not locally Euclidean at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1/2]
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines=none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmax=1, xmin=-1, ymax=1, ymin=-1, ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({0},{x});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red, samples=60] ({x},{0});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compatible Charts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi:V\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 are two charts of a topological manifold.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the image 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 will also be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi:V\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 of a topological manifold are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
compatible
\series default
 if the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\psi^{-1}:\psi(U\cap V)\to\phi(U\cap V)\qquad\psi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap V)\to\psi(U\cap V)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 These two maps are called the 
\series bold
transition functions
\series default
 between the charts.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is empty, then the two charts are automatically 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible.
 To simplify this notation, we will sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We will also sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}=\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are interested only in 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts, we often omit mention of 
\begin_inset Formula $"C^{\infty}"$
\end_inset

 and speak simply of compatible charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility is clearly reflexive and symmetric, but not necessarily transitiv
e.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the three coordinate functions are simultaneously defined only
 on the triple intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{123}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}=(\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{2})^{-1}\circ(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, but only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{123})$
\end_inset

, not necessarily on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13})$
\end_inset

.
 A priori we know nothing about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{3}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{13}\setminus U_{123})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
atlas
\series default
 or simply an 
\series bold
atlas 
\series default
on a locally Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts that cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on a circle).
 The unit circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 may be described as the set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0\leq t\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the two open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<\frac{1}{2}\}\qquad U_{2}=\{e^{2\pi it}\in\mathbb{C}\mid0<t<1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-2,0) circle (1cm);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (-3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=white, inner sep=0.5pt, label=below left:$$] (x) at (3,0)
 {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_1 $] (x) at (-2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[label=below:$ U_2 $] (x) at (2,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:U_{i}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(e^{2\pi it})=t\qquad\phi_{2}(e^{2\pi it})=t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are branches of the complex log funciton 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/i)\log z$
\end_inset

 and are homeomorphisms onto their respective images.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}$
\end_inset

 consists of two connected components, the lower half 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the upper half 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid-\frac{1}{2}<t<0\}\qquad B=\{e^{2\pi it}\mid0<t<\frac{1}{2}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{12})=\phi_{1}(A\cup B)=\phi_{1}(A)\cup\phi_{1}(B)=\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{2}(U_{12})=\phi_{2}(A\cup B)=\phi_{2}(A)\cup\phi_{2}(B)=\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\cup\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transisition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{12})\to\phi_{2}(U_{12})$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{2}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t+1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(-\frac{1}{2},0\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)=\begin{cases}
t-1 & \mbox{for }t\in\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)\\
t & \mbox{for }t\in\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible charts and form a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
compatible with an atlas
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 if it is compatible with all the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 of the atlas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{compatible}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on a locally Euclidean space.
 If two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 are both compatible with the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, then they are compatible with each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}=(\sigma\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i}\circ\psi^{-1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}\psi(V\cap W\cap U_{i})=\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V\cap W)$
\end_inset

 and the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i}\circ\psi^{-1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V\cap W)$
\end_inset

.
 What the equality means in the proof above is that the two maps are equal
 on their common domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is said to be 
\series bold
maximal
\series default
 if it is not contained in a larger atlas; in other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 is any other atlas containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
smooth
\series default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold is a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 together with a maximal atlas.
 The maximal atlas is also called a 
\series bold
differentiable structure
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 A manifold is said to have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 if all of its connected components have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is also called a 
\series bold
curve
\series default
.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold is a 
\series bold
surface
\series default
, and an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, to check that a topological manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold, it is not necessary to exhibit a maximal atlas.
 The existence of any atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will do, because of the following proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 on a locally Euclidean space is contained in a unique maximal atlas.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Adjoin to the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 all charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 that are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{compatible})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

 are compatible with one another.
 So the enlarged collection of charts is an atlas.
 Any chart compatible with the new atlas must be compatible with the original
 atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction belongs to the new atlas.
 This proves existence.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 is another maximal atlas containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

, then all the charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'$
\end_inset

 are compatible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and so by construction must belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'\subset\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Since both are maximal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}'=\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This proves uniqueness.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In summary, to show that a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold, it suffices to check that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff and second countable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From now on, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will mean a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 We use the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interchangeably.
 In the context of manifolds, we denote the standard coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{1},\dots,r^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is a chart of a manifold, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=r^{i}\circ\phi$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=(x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)=(U,x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{1}(p),\dots,x^{n}(p))$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1},\dots,x^{n}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
coordinates
\series default
 or 
\series bold
local coordinates 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 By abuse of notation, we sometimes omit the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So the notations 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$
\end_inset

 stands alternately for local coordinates on the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and for a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological manifold can be endowed with different (non-compatible) different
iable structures.
 For instance, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We can give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{1})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to x$
\end_inset

.
 We can also give the space the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\varphi_{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These two charts are not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-compatible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\circ\varphi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{\frac{1}{3}}$
\end_inset

, and this is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{\frac{1}{3}}\right)=\frac{1}{3}x^{-\frac{2}{3}}$
\end_inset

 is not continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An Atlas For a Product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propproductofmanifolds}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\mid i\in I\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}=\{(V_{j},\psi_{j})\mid j\in J\}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlases for the manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, respectively, then the collection 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}=\{(U_{i}\times V_{j},\phi_{i}\times\psi_{j}:U_{i}\times V_{j}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}^{n})\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\}
\]

\end_inset

of charts is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m+n$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ U_{i}\times V_{j}\mid(i,j)\in I\times J\right\} $
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

, so we just need to show that any two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise compatible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1}\times V_{1},\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2}\times V_{2},\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two charts in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)^{-1}=\left(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}\right)\times\left(\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}\times\psi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on their respective domains.
 The same proof shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{2}\times\psi_{2}\right)\circ\left(\phi_{1}\times\psi_{1}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}\times\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of pairwise 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatible charts that cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propproductofmanifolds})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that the infinite cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and the torus 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Euclidean Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Euclidean space).
 The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote coordinates functions and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$
\end_inset

 to denote real numbers.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p)=a_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(p)=a_{2}$
\end_inset

, and etc...
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The real half line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}:\{a\in\mathbb{R}\mid a>0\}$
\end_inset

 is also a smooth manifold, with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}_{>0},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A homeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{log}:\mathbb{R}_{>0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now consider the half-open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,2\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 Open sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 where and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq a<b<2\pi$
\end_inset

 form a basis for this topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Right-Half Infinite Strip and the Right-Half Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}_{>0}\times$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{-\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We illustrate this space below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [dashed, fill=gray!20] (-10,-2) rectangle (10,2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,2) -- (10,-2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-10,0.5) -- (10,0.5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=blue] (-10,0) -- (10,0);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=below:$ (1 
\backslash
text{,} 0 ) $] (a) at (-9,0) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=above:$ (r 
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
theta ) $] (a) at (0,0.5) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{R}_{>0}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the right-half plane.
 We illustrate this space below: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [dashed, fill=gray!20] (-10,-5) rectangle (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (-10,5) -- (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,5) -- (10,-5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=white] (10,-5) -- (-10,-5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=red] (-10,0) -- (10,5);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw[color=blue] (-10,0) -- (10,0);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=below:$ (1 
\backslash
text{,} 0 ) $] (a) at (-9,0) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=above:$ (a 
\backslash
text{,} b ) $] (a) at (0,2.5) {};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can give both 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the structure of a smooth manifold by simply using the identity charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r,\theta)=(\varphi_{1}(r,\theta),\varphi_{2}(r,\theta))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(r,\theta) & =r\sin\theta\\
\varphi_{2}(r,\theta) & =r\cos\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\theta)\in M$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(r,\theta)}(\varphi)=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\theta & r\cos\theta\\
\cos\theta & -r\sin\theta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:N\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(a,b)=(\psi_{1}(a,b),\psi_{2}(a,b))$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{1}(a,b) & =\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}\\
\psi_{2}(a,b) & =\arctan\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,b)}(\psi)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}}\begin{pmatrix}a & b\\
-b & a
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Manifolds of Dimension Zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Manifolds of dimension zero).
 In a manifold of dimension zero, every singleton subset is homeomorphic
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and so is open.
 Thus, a zero-dimensional manifold is a discrete set.
 By second countability, this discrete set must be countable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Graph of a Smooth Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Graph of a smooth function).
 For a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
graph
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the subset
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(f)=\{(p,f(p))\in A\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then the two maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:\Gamma(f)\to U\qquad(p,f(p))\mapsto p
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1,f):U\to\Gamma(f)\qquad p\mapsto(p,f(p))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are continuous and inverse to each other, and so are homeomorphisms.
 The graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)$
\end_inset

 of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has an atlas with a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Gamma(f),\phi)$
\end_inset

, and is therefore a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 This shows that many familiar surfaces of calculus, for example an elliptic
 paraboloid or a hyperbolic paraboloid, are manifolds.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplecirclestereographic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Circle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the unit circle centered at the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x^{2}+y^{2}=1\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall describe an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 using stereographic projection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=S^{1}\backslash\{(-1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which passes through the points 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation of this line is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=t(X+1).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passes through 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and is not tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

, it must pass through a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is illustrated in the image below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = none, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-3,xmax=3,ymin=-3,ymax=3,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick=
\backslash
empty ,ytick=
\backslash
empty ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({0},{x}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,samples=80] ({x},{2*x + 2}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$ (-1
\backslash
text{,}0) $] (a) at (axis cs:-1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(x
\backslash
text{,}y)$] (c) at (axis cs:-0.6,0.8) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.3pt, label=left:$(0
\backslash
text{,}t)$] (b) at (axis cs:0,2) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 lies on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and the unit circle, we get the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+y^{2}-1 & =0,\\
y-t(x+1) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the second relation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=t(x+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first relation, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{2}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}}=\frac{1-x}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, to get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\\
y & =\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}:U_{1}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset

This map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq-1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{1-t^{2}}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}=S^{1}\backslash\{(1,0)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Following the same line of reasoning as the paragraph above, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}:U_{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto\frac{y}{1-x}.
\]

\end_inset

Again, this map is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq1$
\end_inset

, and the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}^{-1}:\mathbb{R}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\mapsto\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}:=\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{12}(t) & =(\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{2}^{-1})(t)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(\frac{t^{2}-1}{1+t^{2}},\frac{2t}{1+t^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as a local coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 as global coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Projective Line
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\in\mathbb{R},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in their domains.
 The inverse maps are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{0}^{-1}(t)=(1:t)\in U_{0}\qquad\phi_{1}^{-1}(t)=(t:1)\in U_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(t) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(t\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(t:1\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that this is the same transition map we calculated in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplecirclestereographic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{examplesphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sphere) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 the six charts corresponding to the six hemispheres - the front, rear,
 right , left, upper, and lower hemispheres
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b,c)=(b,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b,c)=(a,c)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{5}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c>0\}\qquad\phi_{5}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{6}=\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid c<0\}\qquad\phi_{6}(a,b,c)=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{14}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(a,b,c)\in S^{2}\mid b<0<a\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{4}(U_{14})=\{(a,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }a>0\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a,c) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a,c)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right)\\
 & =\left(\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}},c\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is easy to see that this is indeed a smooth map in its domain (since
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-c^{2}-a^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

).
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(a,c)}(\phi_{14})=\begin{pmatrix}\frac{a}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}} & \frac{c}{\sqrt{1-c^{2}-a^{2}}}\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{45}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{45}(a,b) & =\phi_{4}\circ\phi_{5}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{4}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{nsphere}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{n}=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\|\boldsymbol{x}\|=1\}.
\]

\end_inset

Here we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n},x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this description 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 comes equipped with 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
coordinates: every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\boldsymbol{x}\|=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)$
\end_inset

 be the north pole and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}=S^{n}\backslash\{\boldsymbol{x}_{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}\colon U_{N}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{N}(\boldsymbol{x})=\varphi_{N}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\left(\frac{x_{1}}{1-x_{n+1}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{1-x_{n+1}}\right)=(y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,y_{n}(\boldsymbol{x})),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=t_{i}\circ\varphi_{N}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this map by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We often get lazy and write 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=y_{i}$
\end_inset

 where we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 in this case as a real number (and not a function) which gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U_{N}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f=y_{1}^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(\boldsymbol{x}) & =(y_{1}^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}^{3})(\boldsymbol{x})\\
 & =y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}(\boldsymbol{x})^{3}\\
 & =y_{1}^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}^{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in U_{N}$
\end_inset

, where we got lazy at the end and simply wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 When we write 
\begin_inset Formula $f=y_{1}^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}^{3}$
\end_inset

, we are thinking of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 as functions 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\colon U_{N}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

When we write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=y_{1}^{3}+\cdots+y_{n}^{3}$
\end_inset

, we are thinking of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 as the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\varphi_{N}^{-1}(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})=\varphi_{N}^{-1}(\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{x})=y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

we have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U_{N}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=y_{1}+y_{2}+\cdots+y_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are used in to different (and admittedly contradictory) ways: either as
 a function 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\colon U_{N}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or as the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\emph on
local 
\emph default
coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 in the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

: each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in U_{N}$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the there is a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,y_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}))\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

We denote this map by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{N}=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we often get lazy and write 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})=(y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,y_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}))$
\end_inset

 where now we we think of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 in this case as 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

 It is straightforward to check that this map is a homeomorphism.
 Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\emph on
local 
\emph default
coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 in the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

: every point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

 can be identitified uniquely the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(y_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,y_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}))$
\end_inset

 Here, we view the Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 gives us local coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

, and we can 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using stereographic projections (from the north pole and the south pole),
 we can define two charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth manifold.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)$
\end_inset

 be the north pole 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}=(0,\dots,0,1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the north pole and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{S}=(0,\dots,0,-1)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be the south pole.
 Define the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{N}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{S}:S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
stereographic projection 
\series default
from the north pole (resp.
 south pole), by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1-x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\quad\text{and}\quad\phi_{S}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})=\frac{1}{1+x_{n+1}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

The inverse stereographic projections are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{N}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},-1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}^{-1}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\frac{1}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}\left(2x_{1},\dots,2x_{n},1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{N}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}=S^{n}\backslash\{p_{S}\}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{S}$
\end_inset

 are two open subsets convering 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, both homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, it is easily checked that on the overlap, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{N}\cap U_{S}$
\end_inset

, the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{S}\circ\phi_{N}^{-1}=\phi_{N}\circ\phi_{S}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}),
\]

\end_inset

that is, the inversion of center 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O}=(0,\dots,0)$
\end_inset

 and power 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, this map is smooth on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{O\}$
\end_inset

, so we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{N},\phi_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{S},\phi_{S})$
\end_inset

 form a smooth atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Real Projective Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampleprojectiveplane}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Projective Plane) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the projective plane over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 the three charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)=:(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)=:(c,d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=D(X_{2})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{2}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}\right)=:(e,f)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism is because given that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

, we use the equivalence relation to write the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

 are two real rumbers which uniquely determine the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 be the intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}:=\{(x_{0}:x_{1}:x_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\left\{ \left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can also write this in terms of local coordinates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(U_{01})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\{(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid c\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's calculate the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}:=\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}:\phi_{1}(U_{01})\to\phi_{0}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 using the local coordinates.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{01}\left(c,d\right) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(c,d\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}:\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}},\frac{x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},\frac{d}{c}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}(c,d)=\frac{1}{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}(c,d)=\frac{d}{c}$
\end_inset

), the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{c}^{m}\partial_{d}^{n}\phi_{01}^{i}$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{01}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are rational functions (i.e.
 ratio of two polynomials) and are they are defined everywhere since 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

 in
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similarly, one can easily show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\phi_{10}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{a},\frac{b}{a}\right)\\
\phi_{20}\left(a,b\right) & =\left(\frac{1}{b},\frac{a}{b}\right)\\
\phi_{02}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{f}{e},\frac{1}{e}\right)\\
\phi_{12}\left(e,f\right) & =\left(\frac{e}{f},\frac{1}{f}\right)\\
\phi_{21}(c,d) & =\left(\frac{c}{d},\frac{1}{d}\right)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

It is instructive to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{ji}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{jk}=\phi_{ik}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riemann Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riemann sphere) In this example we describe a 
\series bold
complex manifold
\series default
.
 A complex manifold is the complex analogue of a manifold, however in the
 complex manifold case, we require the transition maps to be holomorphic,
 and not just 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 be the projective line over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 (also known as the Riemann sphere).
 Define in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 the two charts given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{0}=D(X_{0})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{0}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=D(X_{1})=\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{1}\neq0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(x_{0}:x_{1})=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{01}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x_{0}:x_{1})\in\mathbb{P}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\mid x_{0}\neq0\text{ and }x_{1}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}(U_{01})=\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}(z) & =\phi_{0}\circ\phi_{1}^{-1}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{1}}:1\right)\\
 & =\phi_{0}\left(1:\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{x_{1}}{x_{0}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto\frac{1}{z}$
\end_inset

 is holomorphic in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobius Strip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to give this set the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold.
 First we consider the set of all nonvertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonvertial is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid y=ax+b\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}:U_{v}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}\mapsto(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Next we consider the set of all nonhorizontal lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonhorizontal is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x=cy+d\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}:U_{h}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}\mapsto(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}\cup U_{h}=\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, we glue the topologies from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{h}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{vh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{hv}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{vh}(c,d) & =\varphi_{v}\circ\varphi_{h}^{-1}(c,d)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{c,d}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{hv}(a,b) & =\varphi_{h}\circ\varphi_{v}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{a,b}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These maps are clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, they look very similar to the transition maps for the projective
 plane, except they are twisted by a negative sign.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can also describe 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

: Any line in the euclidean plane is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by+c=0$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that these coefficients uniquely determine the line and they
 are homogeneous.
 Hence there is a well defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by mapping the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(ax+by+c)$
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[a:b:c]$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective, but not surjective.
 However if we remove the point 
\begin_inset Formula $[0:0:1]$
\end_inset

, then the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathcal{L}\to\mathbb{R}\mathbb{P}^{2}\backslash\{[0:0:1]\}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grassmannians
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-planes through the origin in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane is a linear subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and has a basis consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 linearly independent vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\dots,v_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore completely specified by an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=[a_{1}\cdots a_{k}]$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, where the 
\series bold
rank 
\series default
of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rk}A$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the number of linearly independent columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is called a 
\series bold
matrix representative 
\series default
of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Two bases 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\dots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 determine the same 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-plane if there is a change-of-basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $g=[g_{ij}]\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{j}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}g_{ij}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 In matrix notation, this says 
\begin_inset Formula $B=Ag$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrices of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, topologized as a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 the equivalence relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\sim B\text{ if and only if there is a matrix }g\in\text{GL}(k,\mathbb{R})\text{ such that }B=Ag.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a bijection between 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 We give the Grassmannian 
\begin_inset Formula $G(k,n)$
\end_inset

 the quotient topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $F(k,n)/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
real Grassmann manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined as the space of all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspaces of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The topology in 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)$
\end_inset

 may be described as induced by the embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $G(n,k)\to\text{End}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 which assigns to a 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in G(n,k)$
\end_inset

, the orthogonal projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\to P$
\end_inset

 combined with the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $P\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $G(4,2)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}\sim\begin{pmatrix}c_{11} & c_{12}\\
c_{21} & c_{22}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & a_{13} & a_{14}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & a_{23} & a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}c_{11}a_{11}+c_{12}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}\\
c_{21}a_{11}+c_{22}a_{21} & c_{11}a_{12}+c_{12}a_{22} & c_{11}a_{13}+c_{12}a_{23} & c_{11}a_{14}+c_{12}a_{24}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{11}c_{22}-c_{21}c_{12}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Grassmanians: Algebraic Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a vector space over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}(V)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Also, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq d\leq n+1$
\end_inset

, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}_{d}(V)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of codimension-
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have a decomposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{G}(V)=\bigcup_{d=0}^{n+1}\mathbb{G}_{d}(V)
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{G}_{0}(V) & =V\\
\mathbb{G}_{1}(V) & =\{\text{hyperplanes in }V\}\\
 & \vdots\\
\mathbb{G}_{n}(V) & =\{\text{lines that pass through the origin in }V\}\\
\mathbb{G}_{n+1}(V) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $V=F^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, then this set is called the 
\series bold
Grassmanian of codimension-
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 subspaces in 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

-space 
\series default
(over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

) and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}(d,n)(F)$
\end_inset

 (or more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}(d,n)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is understood.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $d=1$
\end_inset

 it is called the 
\series bold
projective space 
\series default
and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 By the dual relationship between subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 (whereby a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corresponds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $(V\slash W)^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}_{d}(V)$
\end_inset

 can also be viewed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}_{n+1-d}(V^{\lor})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Fix an ordered basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=e_{0},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{i_{1},\dots,i_{d}\}$
\end_inset

 be a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 distinct indices where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i_{1}<\cdots<i_{d}\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{I}\subseteq\mathbb{G}_{d}(V)$
\end_inset

 denote the subset of codimension-
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 linear subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 for which the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

's with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 projective to a basis of the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $V\slash W$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{I}$
\end_inset

's cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{G}_{d}(V)$
\end_inset

 as a set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have a bijection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{G}_{n+1-d}(\mathbb{R}^{n+1}) & \longleftrightarrow & \left\{ A\in\mathrm{M}_{n+1,d}(\mathbb{R})\mid A\text{ has full rank}\right\} \slash\sim\\
W & \to\\
\mathrm{im}\,A & \leftarrow & A
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the equivalence relation is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\sim B\text{ if and only if }AC=B\text{ for some }C\in\mathrm{GL}_{d}(\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to describe the codimension-
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we want to describe the subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 which have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 A subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be described using a
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mn}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

