\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Smooth Maps on a Manifold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we've defined smooth manifolds, it is time to consider maps between
 them.
 Using coordinate charts, one can transfer the notion of smooth maps from
 Euclidean spaces to manifolds.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in an atlas, the smoothness of a map turns out
 to be independent of the choice of charts and is therefore well defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 or 
\series bold
smooth at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a function defined on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Observe that the definition of the smoothness of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is independent of the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, for if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any other chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ\psi^{-1}\mid_{\psi(U\cap V)}=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ(\phi\circ\psi^{-1}),
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Also observe that in the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not assumed to be continuous.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, being a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

 in an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of continuous functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f\circ\phi^{-1})\circ\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are only interested in functions that are smooth on an open set,
 there is no loss of generality in assuming at the onset that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 a real-valued function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset\psi(V)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will prove the proposition as a cyclic chain of implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): This follows directly from the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function, since by (2) every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 has a coordinate neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in V$
\end_inset

.
 By the remark above, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(V)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The smoothness conditions of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will be a recurrent motif: to prove the smoothness of an object, it is
 sufficient that a smoothness criterion hold on the charts of some atlas.
 Once the object is shown to be smooth, it then follows that the same smoothness
 criterion holds on 
\emph on
every 
\emph default
chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a map and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
pullback 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}h$
\end_inset

, is the composite function 
\begin_inset Formula $h\circ F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this terminology, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 if and only if its pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi^{-1})^{*}f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 of Euclidean space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be rotation counterclockwise by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi^{*}x & =(\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y\\
\phi^{*}y & =(\sin\theta)x+(\cos\theta)y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},e_{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $x(e_{1})=$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi^{*}x)(a,b) & =x\left(\phi(a,b)\right)\\
 & =x\left(\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b,\sin\theta a+\cos\theta b\right)\\
 & =\cos\theta a-\sin\theta b\\
 & =((\cos\theta)x-(\sin\theta)y)(a,b).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smooth Maps Between Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We emphasize again that unless otherwise specified, by a manifold we always
 mean a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold.
 We use the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interchangeably.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be manifolds of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 A continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at a point 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, a map from the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 The continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the definition, we needed 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 to be open so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(F^{-1}(V)\cap U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps between manifolds are by definition continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In case 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{m},1_{\mathbb{R}^{m}})$
\end_inset

 as a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the definition above, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

 if and only if there is a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, we recover the definition of a function being 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at a point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We show now that the definition of the smoothness of a map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 at a point is independent of the choice of charts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is any chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

, there are charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta})$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 compatibility of charts in a differentiable structure, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on open subsets of Euclidean spaces.
 Hence, the composite
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}\mid_{\phi\left(F^{-1}(V\cap V_{\beta})\cap U\cap U_{\alpha}\right)}=(\psi\circ\psi_{\beta}^{-1})\circ(\psi_{\beta}\circ F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{\alpha}\circ\phi^{-1}),
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Notes_190117_135420_7a4_1.jpg
	lyxscale 20
	scale 20
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a map in terms of charts).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be smooth manifolds, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are atlases 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U\cap F^{-1}(V))\to\mathbb{R}^{m}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart about 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{V}$
\end_inset

.
 By (2), 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map, 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 was an arbitrary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

