\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G:M\to P$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of manifolds, then the composite 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F:N\to P$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(W,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 be charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}=(\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1})\circ(\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ G\circ\psi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ F\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 As a composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps of open subsets of Euclidean spaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\circ(G\circ F)\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
diffeomorpism 
\series default
of manifolds is a bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 whose inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the next two propositions, coordinate maps are diffeomorphisms,
 and conversely, every diffeomorphism of an open subset of a manifold with
 an open subset of a Euclidean space can serve as a coordinate map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6.10}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then the coordinate map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism, so it suffices to check that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are smooth.
 To test the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (U,\phi)\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and the atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (\phi(U),\text{id}_{\phi(U)})\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a single chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{id}_{\phi(U)}\circ\phi\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.8})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To test smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to U$
\end_inset

, we use the same atlases as above.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\circ\phi^{-1}\circ\text{id}_{\phi(U)}:\phi(U)\to\phi(U)
\]

\end_inset

is the identity map, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F:U\to F(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is a chart in the differentiable structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 in the maximal atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop6.10})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As composites of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 maps, both 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi_{\alpha}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\alpha}\circ F^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is compatible with the maximal atlas.
 By the maximality of the atlas, the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,F)$
\end_inset

 is in the atlas.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Smoothness in Terms of Components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In this subsection, we derive a criterion that reduces the smoothness of
 a map to the smoothness of real-valued functions on open sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness of a vector-valued function) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 has an atlas such that for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the atlas, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Smoothness in terms of components).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a manifold.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},\dots,F_{m}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if for every chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}:N\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Just as in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 case, we introduce an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 be represent a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0},\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{0}\cap U,\phi_{\mid U})$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(f\mid_{U_{0}\cap U},U_{0}\cap U)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may always assume that a germ can be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we obtain an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\phi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\phi^{-1},\phi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 Of course this map depends on our choice of chart.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 was another chart, then we'd obtain another isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\varphi}:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\mapsto(f\circ\varphi^{-1},\varphi(U))$
\end_inset

.
 We can relate these two isomorphisms via the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We describe the structure of a premanifold as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{M}(U):=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:\phi_{i}(U\cap U_{i})\to\mathbb{R}\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see that this is a premanifold, fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 open let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1}:\phi_{i_{0}}(U_{i_{0}}\cap U)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{M}(U)$
\end_inset

 because the change of charts between 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-diffeomorphisms.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}=(f\circ\phi_{i_{0}}^{-1})\circ(\phi_{i_{0}}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

 yields an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{M|U_{i_{0}}})\cong(Y_{i_{0}},\mathcal{O}_{i_{0}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $(M,\mathcal{O}_{M})$
\end_inset

 is a ringed space that is locally isomorphic to a manifold.
 Hence it is a premanifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Smooth Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:\mathbb{R}\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)=(\cos t,\sin t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}.$
\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we use the atlas which consists of a single chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R},\text{id})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 we use the atlas which consists of the charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{2},\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{3},\phi_{3})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{4},\phi_{4})$
\end_inset

 where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us do some computations.
 First, let's compute the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{14}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{14}(a) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{4}^{-1}(a)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{13}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{24}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}\\
\phi_{23}(a) & =\sqrt{1-a^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

.
 Let's compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{1}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\phi_{1}(F(t))\\
 & =(\phi_{1}((\cos t,\sin t))\\
 & =\sin t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similar computations shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\phi_{2}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\sin t\\
(\phi_{3}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t\\
(\phi_{4}\circ F\circ\text{id})(t) & =\cos t.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

These maps are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=(t^{2},t^{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a,b,c)=c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{6},\phi_{6})$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\circ\phi_{6}^{-1})(a,b) & =f\left(\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\right)\\
 & =f\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-a^{2}-b^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}-b^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us show that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 To avoid confusing functions with points, we will denote a point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and use 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 to mean the standard coordinate functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $x(a,b)=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(a,b)=b$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 restrict to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $i:S^{1}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $i(p)=(x(p),y(p))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and so the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{S^{1}}=f\circ i$
\end_inset

 with be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 too.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider first the function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 We use the following atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{1}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b>0\}\qquad\phi_{1}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{2}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid b<0\}\qquad\phi_{2}(a,b)=a
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{3}=\{(a,b)\in S^{1}\mid a>0\}\qquad\phi_{3}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{4}=\{(a,b)\in S^{2}\mid a<0\}\qquad\phi_{4}(a,b)=b
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

, it is a coordinate function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, it suffices to check the smoothness of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1}:\phi_{3}(U_{3})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{3}^{-1})(b)=x\left(\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq\pm1$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{1-b^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\circ\phi_{4}^{-1})(b)=x\left(-\sqrt{1-b^{2}},b\right)=-\sqrt{1-b^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on the four open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1},U_{2},U_{3},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{4}$
\end_inset

, which cover 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is similar.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the unit sphere with its smooth structure given in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{examplesphere})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let's construct a smooth function on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(U_{16})=\{(b,c)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid b^{2}+c^{2}<1\text{ and }c<0\}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\phi_{6}(U_{16})=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a^{2}+b^{2}<1\text{ and }0<a\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(b,c)=b^{2}+c^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\phi_{1}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}^{*}(f):\phi_{6}(U_{16})\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{16}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}(a,b) & =\phi_{1}\circ\phi_{6}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\phi_{1}\left(a,b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{16}^{*}(f)(a,b) & =(f\circ\phi_{16})(a,b)\\
 & =f\left(b,\sqrt{1-b^{2}-a^{2}}\right)\\
 & =1-a^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to the open unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

 with inverse given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\dots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right):=\beta^{-1}(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let us first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\beta(x)\| & =\sqrt{\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}+\cdots+\left(\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & <\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)\in B_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 This comes down to checking the component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are smooth:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x:=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\mapsto\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}:=\beta_{i}(x).
\]

\end_inset

This follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is smooth follows by the same reasoning.
 Finally, checking that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\beta^{-1}(x))=x$
\end_inset

 is tedious but trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta(\beta^{-1}(x)) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}},\cdots,\frac{x_{n}}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}}\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right)\\
 & =\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inverse Function Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally invertible 
\series default
or a 
\series bold
local diffeomorphism 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in N$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $F|_{U}:U\to F(U)$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},\dots,F_{n}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one would like to know whether they form a coordinate system, possibly
 on a smaller neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to whether 
\begin_inset Formula $F=(F_{1},\dots,F_{n}):N\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a local diffeomorphism at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse function theorem provides an answer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Inverse function theorem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Ler 
\begin_inset Formula $F:W\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map defined on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is locally invertible at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if and only if the Jacobian determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(J(F)_{p})$
\end_inset

 is not zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Inverse function theorem for manifolds).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tangent Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By definition, the 
\series bold
tangent space 
\series default
to a manifold at a point is the vector space of derivations at the point.
 A smooth map of manifolds induces a linear map, called its 
\series bold
differential
\series default
, of tangent spaces at corresponding points.
 In local coordinates, the differential is represented by the Jacobian matrix
 of partial derivatives of the map.
 In this sense, the differential of a map between manifolds is a generalization
 of the derivative of a map between Euclidean spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Tangent Space at a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Just as for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we define a 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be an equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions defined in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, two such functions being equivalent if they agree on some, possibly smaller,
 neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The set of germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 real-valued functions at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 The addition and multiplication of functions make 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 into a ring; which scalar multiplication by real numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 becomes an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Generalizing a derivation at a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we define a 
\series bold
derivation at a point 
\series default
in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, or a 
\series bold
point-derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

, to be a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:C_{p}^{\infty}(M)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(fg)=(Df)g(p)+f(p)Dg.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
tangent vector 
\series default
at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}+y^{3}+x+1:=t$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x_{0},y_{0})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{2}\to T_{f(p)}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by taking a derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f(p)}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{*}D)(g)=D(g\circ f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x^{3}-x:=t$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}\mapsto(3x_{0}^{2}-1)\partial_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\mapsto\left(f_{1}(x,y),f_{2}(x,y)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1}(x,y) & =x\\
f_{2}(x,y) & =\frac{xy^{2}}{y^{2}+1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{(x_{0},y_{0})}(f_{1},f_{2})=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
\frac{y_{0}^{2}}{y_{0}^{2}+1} & \frac{2x_{0}y_{0}}{(y_{0}^{2}+1)^{2}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2x_{0}y_{0}}{(y_{0}^{2}+1)^{2}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We describe 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 in another way.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the set of paths through 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}_{p}:=\{\gamma:(-a,a)\to M\mid\gamma\text{ is }C^{\infty}\text{ and }\gamma(0)=p\}.
\]

\end_inset

We define an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}$
\end_inset

 as follows: we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}\sim\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 if there exist a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'(0)=(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'(0).
\]

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 are paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is independent of the choice of chart.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is another chart centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi\circ\gamma_{1})' & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1}\circ\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'\\
 & =(\psi\circ\gamma_{2})'
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi\circ\varphi^{-1})'$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The tangent space at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{p}M:=\mathcal{P}_{p}/\sim.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ \left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)\mid\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the cylinder.
 Define the two charts 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M,\psi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M\cap\left\{ (\frac{-\pi}{,2},\frac{\pi}{2})\times(\frac{-\pi}{,2},\frac{\pi}{2})\times\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)=(\alpha,\beta)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\psi\left(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha,\beta\right)=(\cos\alpha,\beta).
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{1}(t)=(\cos(t^{2}),\sin(t^{2}),t)\qquad\text{and}\qquad\gamma_{2}(t)=(0,1,t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})(t)=(t^{2},t)\qquad\text{and}\qquad(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})(t)=\left(\frac{\pi}{2},t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\varphi\circ\gamma_{1})'(0)=(0,1)=(\varphi\circ\gamma_{2})'(0)
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}\sim\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partial Derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 be a chart and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 As a function into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 components 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1},\dots,\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=x_{i}\circ\phi$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, we define the 
\series bold
partial derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\series default
denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi_{i}}f$
\end_inset

, to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{\phi_{i}}\mid_{p}f:=(\partial_{\phi_{i}}f)(p):=\partial_{x_{i}}(f\circ\phi^{-1})(\phi(p)):=\partial_{x_{i}}\mid_{\phi(p)}(f\circ\phi^{-1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the projective plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Use the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\{(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})\in\mathbb{P}^{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid a{}_{0}\neq0\}\qquad\phi(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})=\left(\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}},\frac{a_{2}}{a_{0}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{1}(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2}) & =(x_{1}\circ\phi)(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})\\
 & =x_{1}(\phi(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2}))\\
 & =x_{1}\left(\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}},\frac{a_{2}}{a_{0}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a_{1}}{a_{0}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}(a_{0}:a_{1}:a_{2})=a_{2}/a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polar Coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following smooth map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\\
\theta & =\text{arctan}\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
dr & =\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dx+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dy\\
d\theta & =\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
rdrd\theta & =\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dx+\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}dy\right)\left(\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy\right)\\
 & =\left(xdx+ydy\right)\left(\frac{-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dx+\frac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(xdx+ydy\right)\left(-ydx+xdy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(-xydxdx+x^{2}dxdy-y^{2}dydx+xydydy\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(x^{2}dxdy-y^{2}dydx\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(x^{2}dxdy+y^{2}dxdy\right)\\
 & =\frac{x^{2}+y^{2}}{x^{2}+y^{2}}dxdy\\
 & =dxdy.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we can integrate the Gaussian as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{\infty}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-(x^{2}+y^{2})}dxdx & =\int_{0}^{\pi/2}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-r^{2}}rdrd\theta.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inverse map is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =r\cos\theta\\
y & =r\sin\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Immersion, Embedding, Submersion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is called an
\series bold
 immersion 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}:T_{p}N\to T_{F(p)}M$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
immersion 
\series default
if it is an immersion at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
submersion 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if the induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}:T_{p}N\to T_{F(p)}M$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
submersion 
\series default
if it is an submersion at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The prototype of an immersion is the inclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in a higher-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})=(a_{1},\dots,a_{n},0,\dots,0).
\]

\end_inset

The prototype of a submersion is the projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 onto a lower-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(a_{1},\dots,a_{m},a_{m+1},\dots,a_{n})=(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $i:U\to M$
\end_inset

 is both an immersion and submersion.
 This example shows in particular that a submersion need not be onto.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Critical Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F:N\to M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
critical point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*,p}$
\end_inset

 is not surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
critical value 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(q):=\{p\in N\mid F(p)=q\}$
\end_inset

 contains a critical point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 Then the set of critical values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Measure Theory on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 be the Lebesgue measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(a,b)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(I)=b-a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are disjoint intervals, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(I\cup J)=\mu(I)+\mu(J)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, you can cover 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 by a union of intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\{I_{n}\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\bigcup_{n}I_{n}\right)<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, define the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n}:=\left(\frac{-1}{4n},\frac{1}{4n}\right)\cup\left(1-\frac{1}{4n},1+\frac{1}{4n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a disjoint union of intervals which covers 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu(A_{n}) & =\frac{1}{4n}-\frac{-1}{4n}+1+\frac{1}{4n}-\left(1-\frac{1}{4n}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(A_{n})\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ (x,x+\sin(x))\mid x\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the projection onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,x+\sin(x))\mapsto x+\sin(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A critical point is 
\series bold
degenerate 
\series default
if the associated Hessian matrix is 
\series bold
singular
\series default
 (i.e.
 has determinant equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left\{ \left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)\mid\theta\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\left\{ \left(x,y,0\right)\mid x,y\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is homeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be the projection map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)\mapsto\left(\cos\theta,\theta,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(M,\psi_{M})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(N,\psi_{N})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{M}\left(\cos\theta,\theta,\sin\theta+2\right)=\theta\qquad\text{and}\qquad\psi_{N}\left(x,y,0\right)=(x,y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\pi}{4},2+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)\in M$
\end_inset

? Then answer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a continuous function
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}:=\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\right)
\]

\end_inset

 A critical point is 
\series bold
degenerate 
\series default
if the associated Hessian matrix is 
\series bold
singular 
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent Bundle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold.
 The 
\series bold
Tangent Bundle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TM:=\bigcup_{p\in M}T_{p}M.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}:=\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then an atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}_{T}:=\{(U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{n},\phi_{i}\times\text{id})\}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, if we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}:=\phi_{i}\times\text{id}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}:U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{2n}$
\end_inset

 and we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n},y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 as the local coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The tangent bundle of the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to the cylinder.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There exist a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,v)\mapsto v$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default
is a smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ\omega=\text{id}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Intuitively, a vector field is the data of a vector at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 comes with two gadgets.
 The first gadget is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
parameter 
\series default
flow and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The second gadget is called a 
\series bold
differential operator
\series default
 and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 of a smooth manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the natural projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p,v)=p$
\end_inset

, makes 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 into a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
vector bundle 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, which we now define.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given any map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

, we call the inverse image 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(p):=\pi^{-1}(\{p\})$
\end_inset

 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
fiber 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The fiber at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For any two maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi':E'\to M$
\end_inset

 with the same target space 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:E\to E'$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
fiber-preserving 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(E_{p})\subset E_{p}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, this says that the following diagram commutes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E 
\backslash
arrow[rr, "
\backslash
phi "] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, "
\backslash
pi ", swap] && E'  
\backslash
arrow[dl, "
\backslash
pi ' "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 &M 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A surjective smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds is said to be 
\series bold
locally trivial of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a vector space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, there are an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a fiber-preserving diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\pi^{-1}(U)\to U\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in U$
\end_inset

 the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\mid_{E_{q}}:E_{q}\to\{q\}\times\mathbb{R}^{r}
\]

\end_inset

is a vector space isomorphism.
 Such an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivializing open set 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivialization 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U,\phi)\}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U\}$
\end_inset

 and open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, is called a 
\series bold
local trivialization 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U\}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivializing open cover 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\series bold
vector bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

 consisting of manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and a surjective smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 that is locally trivial of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
total space 
\series default
of the vector bundle and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
base space
\series default
.
 By abuse of language, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Properly speaking, the tangent bundle of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(TM,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is the total space of the tangent bundle.
 In common usage, 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is often referred to as the tangent bundle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gluing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given two local trivializations 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:\pi^{-1}(U_{i})\to U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}:\pi^{-1}(U_{j})\to U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

, we obtain a smooth gluing map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}\to U_{i}\cap U_{j}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This map preserves images to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and hence it sends 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,v)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,g_{ji}(v))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix smoothly depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the gluing map is uniquely specified by a smooth map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{ji}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\to\text{GL}_{k}(\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset

These are called 
\series bold
transition functions 
\series default
of the bundle, and since they come from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, they clearly satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, as well as the cocycle condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{ij}g_{jk}g_{ki}=\text{id}\mid_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k}}\text{ }
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To build a vector bundle, choose an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 and form the pieces 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\times\mathbb{R}^{k}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then glue these together on the double overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\cap U_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 via functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}:U_{i}\cap U_{j}\to\text{GL}_{k}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as well as the cocycle condition, the resulting space has a vector bundle
 structure.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}\to M$
\end_inset

 be the projection to the first factor.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is a vector bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
product bundle 
\series default
of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The vector space structure on the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(p)=\{(p,v)\mid v\in\mathbb{R}^{r}\}$
\end_inset

 is the obvious one: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p,u)+(p,v)=(p,u+v)\text{ and }b\cdot(p,v)=(p,bv)\text{ for }b\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

A local trivialization on 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is given by the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{M\times\mathbb{R}}:M\times\mathbb{R}\to M\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the infinite cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is the product bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 over the circle.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{E}:E\to M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{F}:F\to N$
\end_inset

 be two vector bundles, possibly of different ranks.
 A 
\series bold
bundle map 
\series default
from 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a pair of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:E\to F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The diagram 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} E 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
widetilde{f} "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
pi _{_E} ", swap] & F 
\backslash
arrow[d, "
\backslash
pi _{_F} "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 M 
\backslash
arrow[r, "f", swap]  & N 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is commutative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is linear one each fiber; i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:E_{p}\to F_{f(p)}$
\end_inset

 is a linear map of vector spaces for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collection of all vector bundles together with bundle maps between them
 forms a category.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds induces a bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:TN\to TM$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(p,v)=(f(p),f_{*}(v))\in\{f(p)\}\times T_{f(p)}M\subset TM
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}N$
\end_inset

.
 This gives rise to a covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 from the category of smooth manifolds and smooth maps to the category of
 vector bundles and bundle maps: to each manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we associate its tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, and to each 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:N\to M$
\end_inset

 of manifolds, we associate the bundle map 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f)=(f,\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are two vector bundles over the same manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then a bundle map from 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a bundle map in which the base map is the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 For a fixed manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we can also consider the category of all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector bundles over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bundles maps over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In this category it makes sense to speak of an isomorphism of vector bundles
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Any vector bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to the product bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
trivial bundle
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left\{ (x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid\text{det}\begin{pmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{pmatrix}=0\right\} =\left\{ (x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x^{2}+\left(y-\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{4}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This can be realized as the circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 centered at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1/2)$
\end_inset

 in the plane.
 There is natural vector bundle associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in M$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}:=\text{Ker}\left(\begin{smallmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}\left(\begin{smallmatrix}x & 1-y\\
y & x
\end{smallmatrix}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Smooth Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
section 
\series default
of a vector bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:E\to M$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $s:M\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ s=1_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This condition means precisely that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 into the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a section is 
\series bold
smooth 
\series default
if it is smooth as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a function that assigns a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of the tangent bundle, a vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is simply a section of the tangent bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\to M$
\end_inset

 and the vector field is 
\series bold
smooth 
\series default
if it is smooth as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{(x,y)}=-y\partial_{x}+x\partial_{y}
\]

\end_inset

defines a smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Whitney Sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,M,\pi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(E',M,\pi')$
\end_inset

 be two vector bundles.
 We can construct a new vector bundle called the 
\series bold
Whitney sum
\series default
, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi,\pi'):E\oplus E'\to M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E=L\oplus L'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 are line bundles.
 Then we can make a new bundle called 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Throughout this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
locally ringed 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 to be the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As every ring has a unique structure as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-algebra, we simply say (
\series bold
locally) ringed space 
\series default
instead of 
\series bold
(locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-ringed space
\series default
.
 Usually we will denote a (locally) 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space by 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of a finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{X}^{\infty}(U):=\{f:U\to\mathbb{R}\mid f\text{ is }C^{\infty}\text{ function}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{X}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Differential Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
cotangent space 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}M$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the dual space of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{p}^{*}M=(T_{p}M)^{\lor}=\text{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(T_{p}M,\mathbb{R}).
\]

\end_inset

An element of the cotangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}M$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
covector 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a linear function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{p}:T_{p}M\to\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
covector field
\series default
, also called a 
\series bold
differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\series default
or more simply a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
form
\series default
, on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense it is dual to a vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, which assigns to each point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a tangent vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There are many reasons for the great utility of differential forms in manifold
 theory, among which is the fact that they can be pulled back under a map.
 This is in contrast to vector fields, which in general cannot be pushed
 forward under a map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Differential of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 real-valued function on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, its 
\series bold
differential 
\series default
is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(df)_{p}(X_{p})=X_{p}f.
\]

\end_inset

Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(df)_{p}$
\end_inset

 we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $df\mid_{p}$
\end_inset

 for the value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bump Functions and Partitions of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition of unity on a manifold is a collection of nonnegative functions
 that sum to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Usually one demands in addition that the partition of unity be 
\series bold
subordinate 
\series default
to an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 What this means is that the partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is indexed over the same set as the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the index 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity is one of the most technical tools in the theory of
 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds.
 It is the single feature that makes the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds so different from that of real-analytic or complex manifolds.
 In this section we construct 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump functions on any manifold and prove the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity on a compact manifold.
 The proof of the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity of a general manifold is more technical and is postponed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition of unity is used in two ways: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
to decompose a global object on a manifold into a locally finite sum of
 local objects on the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 of an open cover.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
to patch together local objects on the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 into a global object on the manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, a partition of unity serves as a bridge between global and local analysis
 on a manifold.
 This is useful because while there are always local coordinates on a manifold,
 there may be no global coordinates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Bump Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
support 
\series default
of a real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the closure in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of the subset on which 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq0$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}f:=\overline{f^{-1}(\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\})}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 By a 
\series bold
bump function at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
supported in
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 we mean any continuous nonnegative function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The support of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-1,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tan(\pi x/2)$
\end_inset

, is the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

, and not the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

, because the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\mathbb{R}\backslash\{0\})$
\end_inset

 is taken in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

 and not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{smoothnotanalytic})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to build a smooth bump function function from 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The main challenge in building a smooth bump function from 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is to construct a smooth version of a step function.
 We seek 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 by dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 by a positive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

, for the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)/\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 will be zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 should be a positive function that agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

, for then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)/\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 will be identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 The simplest way to construct such an 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)$
\end_inset

 is to add to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 a nonnegative function that vanishes for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 One such nonnegative function is 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1-t)$
\end_inset

.
 This suggests that we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(t)=f(t)+f(1-t)$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{f(t)}{f(t)+f(1-t)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given two positive real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

, we make a linear change of variables to map 
\begin_inset Formula $[a^{2},b^{2}]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\mapsto\left(\frac{x-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right):
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x)=g\left(\frac{x-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 step function such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }x\leq a^{2}\\
1 & \text{if }x\ge b^{2}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Now replace 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 to make the function symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)=h(x^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(x)=1-k(x)=1-g\left(\frac{x^{2}-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that is identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-a,a]$
\end_inset

 and has support in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-b,b]$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x-q)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to extend the construction of a bump function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on the closed balled 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B_{a}(\mathbf{0})}$
\end_inset

 and has support in the closed ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{B_{b}(\mathbf{0})}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(x)=\rho\left(\|x\|\right)=1-g\left(\frac{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}-a^{2}}{b^{2}-a^{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

As a composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 To get a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, take 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(x-q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extending 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Bump Functions to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose we have manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(U_{i})\cong B_{b}(\phi(q))$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

, and choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}\subseteq U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(V_{i})\cong B_{a}(\phi(q))$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

.
 We've shown now to construct a bump function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(q)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{a}(\phi_{i}(q))$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=0$
\end_inset

 outside 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{b}(\phi_{i}(q))$
\end_inset

.
 Now we pull back 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to get a bump function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\phi_{i}^{*}\rho)(q')=\rho(\phi_{i}(q'))\text{ for all }q'\in U_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally we extend this function a bump function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\rho}(q')=\begin{cases}
(\phi_{i}^{*}\rho)(q') & \text{if }q'\in U_{i}\\
0 & \text{if }q'\notin U_{i}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Let us show that this function is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q'\in U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we simply choose the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widetilde{\rho}\circ\phi_{i}^{-1})(x)=(\phi^{*}\rho)(\phi_{i}^{-1}(x))=\rho(x),
\]

\end_inset

shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $q'\notin U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we choose a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{j},U_{j})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widetilde{\rho}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1})(x)=\widetilde{\rho}(\phi_{j}^{-1}(x))=0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho}$
\end_inset

 we constructed is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Extension of a Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 cannot be extended to a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

; an example is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sec x$
\end_inset

 on the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi/2,\pi/2)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 However, if we require that the global function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 agree with the given function only on some neighborhood of a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 extension is possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 extension of a function) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function defined on a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 that agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in some possibly smaller neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump map 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:M\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 supported in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that is identically 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(q)=\begin{cases}
\rho(q)f(q) & \text{if }q\in U\\
0 & \text{if }q\notin U
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the product of two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin\text{supp}\rho$
\end_inset

, and so there is an open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin U$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This proposition says that the natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(M)\to C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Thus, every germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 can be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,M)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partitions of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a finite open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
partition of unity subordinate to 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of nonnegative functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}:M\to\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=1.\label{eq:partitionofunity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an infinite set, for the sum in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:partitionofunity})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to make sense, we will impose a 
\series bold
local finiteness 
\series default
condition.
 A collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 of subsets of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
locally finite 
\series default
if every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a neighborhood that meets only finitely many of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is contained in only finitely many of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{r,n}$
\end_inset

 be the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r-\frac{1}{n},r+\frac{1}{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{r,n}\mid r\in\mathbb{Q},\text{ }n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not locally finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
partition of unity 
\series default
on a manifold is a collection of nonnegative 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}:M\to\mathbb{R}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The collection of supports, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\text{supp}\rho\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, is locally finite, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we say that a partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
subordinate to the open cover 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the collection of supports, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\text{supp}\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, is locally finite, every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 lies in only finitely many of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}(q)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the open intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,\infty)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{V}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth step function which is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\infty,0)$
\end_inset

 and equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{U}=1-\rho_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{V}\subset V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\rho_{U}\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{U},\rho_{V}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity subordinate to the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U,V\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Existence of a Partition of Unity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection we begin a proof of the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity on a manifold.
 Because the case of a compact manifold is somewhat easier and already has
 some of the features of the general case, for pedagogical reasons we give
 a separate proof for the compact case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma13.5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\dots,\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 are real-valued funcitons on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}\right)\subset\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}\text{supp}\rho_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\text{supp}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}\text{supp}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a compact manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in M$
\end_inset

, find an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 from the given cover and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bump function at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 supported in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}(q)>0$
\end_inset

, there is a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}>0$
\end_inset

.
 By the compactness of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W_{q}\mid q\in M\}$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcover, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{W_{q_{1}},\dots,W_{q_{m}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q_{1}},\dots,\psi_{q_{m}}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding bump functions.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:=\sum_{j=1}^{m}\psi_{q_{j}}$
\end_inset

 is positive at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in W_{q_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{j}=\frac{\psi_{q_{j}}}{\psi},\quad j=1,\dots,m.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{m}\varphi_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{j}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q_{j}}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\varphi_{j}=\text{supp}\psi_{q_{j}}\subset U_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The next step is to make the index set of the partition of unity the same
 as that of the open cover.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)\in I$
\end_inset

 to be an index such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{\tau(j)}.
\]

\end_inset

We group the collection of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 into subcollections according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)$
\end_inset

 and define for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i}=\sum_{\tau(j)=i}\varphi_{j};
\]

\end_inset

if there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(j)=i$
\end_inset

, the sum is empty and we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i\in I}\rho_{i}=\sum_{i\in I}\sum_{\tau(j)=i}\varphi_{j}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}\varphi_{j}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma13.5})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{supp}\rho_{i}\subset\bigcup_{\tau(j)=i}\text{supp}\varphi_{j}\subset U_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of unity subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integration on Manifolds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Riemann Integral of a Function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
closed rectangle 
\series default
in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $R=[a_{1},b_{1}]\times\cdots\times[a_{n},b_{n}]$
\end_inset

 of closed intervals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},b_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:R\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a bounded function defined on a closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{vol}(R)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of the closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{vol}(R):=\prod_{i=1}^{n}(b_{i}-a_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
partition 
\series default
of the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 is a set of real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{0},\dots,p_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=p_{0}<p_{1}<\cdots<p_{n}=b.
\]

\end_inset

A 
\series bold
partition 
\series default
of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{P_{1},\dots,P_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, where each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $[a_{i},b_{i}]$
\end_inset

.
 The partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 divides the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 into closed subrectangles, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define the 
\series bold
lower sum 
\series default
and the 
\series bold
upper sum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P):=\sum_{R_{j}}\left(\inf_{R_{j}}f\right)\text{vol}(R_{j}),\qquad U(f,P):=\sum_{R_{j}}\left(\sup_{R_{j}}f\right)\text{vol}(R_{j}),
\]

\end_inset

where each sum runs over all subrectangles of the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 For any partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $L(f,P)\leq U(f,P)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, more is true: for any two partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq U(f,P'),
\]

\end_inset

which we show next.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P'=\{P_{1}',\dots,P_{n}'\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
refinement 
\series default
of the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{P_{1},\dots,P_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\subset P_{i}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is a refinement of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, then each subrectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is subdivided into subrectangles 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{jk}'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

, and it is easily seen that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq L(f,P'),
\]

\end_inset

because if 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{jk}'\subset R_{j}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf_{R_{j}}f\leq\inf_{R_{jk}'}f$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is a refinement of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(f,P')\leq U(f,P).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Any two partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 of the rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 have a common refinement 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\{Q_{1},\dots,Q_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}=P_{i}\cup P_{i}'$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(f,P)\leq L(f,Q)\leq U(f,Q)\leq U(f,P').
\]

\end_inset

It follows that the supremum of the lower sum 
\begin_inset Formula $L(f,P)$
\end_inset

 over all partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is less than or equal to the infimum of the upper sum 
\begin_inset Formula $U(f,P)$
\end_inset

 over all partitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We define these two numbers to be the 
\series bold
lower integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

 
\series default
and the 
\series bold
upper integral 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

, respectively:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\int}_{R}f:=\sup_{P}L(f,P),\qquad\overline{\int}_{R}f:=\inf_{P}L(f,P).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a closed rectangle in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:R\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
Riemann integrable 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\int}_{R}f=\overline{\int}_{R}f$
\end_inset

; in this case, the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is this common value, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{R}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a bounded monotone increasing function on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 Indeed, consider the partition 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}=\{p_{0}<p_{1}<\cdots<p_{2n-1}<p_{2n}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=-1+i/3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U(f,P_{n})-L(f,P_{n}) & =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{2n}f(-1+i/3)-\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=0}^{2n-1}f(-1+i/3)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{2n}f(-1+i/3)-\sum_{i=0}^{2n-1}f(-1+i/3)\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\left(f(1)-f(-1)\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then the 
\series bold
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by zero 
\series default
is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f}(x)=\begin{cases}
f(x) & \text{if }x\in A,\\
0 & \text{if }x\notin A.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded function on a bounded set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Enclose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in a closed rectangle 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and define the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}=\int_{R}\widetilde{f}(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}
\]

\end_inset

if the right-hand side exists.
 In this way we can deal with the integral of a bounded function whose domain
 is an arbitrary bounded set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
volume 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\text{vol}(A)$
\end_inset

 of a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{A}1dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 if the integral exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integrability Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we describe some conditions under which a function defined
 on an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is said to have 
\series bold
measure zero 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there is a countable cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{R_{i}\}_{i=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by closed rectangles 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\text{vol}(R_{i})<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}(Lebesgue's theorem)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 on a bounded subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable if and only if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Disc}(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

 of discontinuities of the extended function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 has measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcontextriemint}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has compact support, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Being continuous on a compact set, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Being compact, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 agrees with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, the extended function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as well.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, there is an open ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 On this open ball, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}=0$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By Lebesgue's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-1,1)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tan(\pi x/2)$
\end_inset

, is defined on an open subset of finite length in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but it not bounded.
 The support of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

, which is not compact.
 Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 does not satisfy the hypotheses of either Lebesgue's theorem or 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propcontextriemint})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Note that it is not Riemann integrable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
domain of integration 
\series default
if it is bounded and its topological boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{bd}(A)$
\end_inset

 is a set of measure zero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every bounded continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 defined on a domain of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable over 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by zero.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is necessarily continuous at all interior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous at all exterior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 also, because every exterior point has a neighborhood contained entirely
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash A$
\end_inset

, on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is identically zero.
 Therefore, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Disc}(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

 of discontinuities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial(A)$
\end_inset

, a set of measure zero.
 By Lebesgue's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is Riemann integrable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Integral of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-Form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once a set of coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 has been fixed on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be identified with functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, since every 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 for a unique function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way the theory of Riemann integration of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 carries over to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, with standard coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Its 
\series bold
integral 
\series default
over a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset U$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the Riemann integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}\omega=\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}:=\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\cdots dx_{n},
\]

\end_inset

if the Riemann integral exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a bounded continuous function defined on a domain of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{A}f(x)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us see how the integral of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=fdx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n}$
\end_inset

 on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 transforms under a change of variables.
 A change of variables on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is given by a diffeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\supset V\to U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},\dots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the standard coordinates on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}:=x_{i}\circ T$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are connected, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dT_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dT_{n}=\text{det}\left(J(T)\right)dy_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dy_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{V}T^{*}\omega & =\int_{V}(T^{*}f)T^{*}dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge T^{*}dx_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)dT_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dT_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)\det(J(T))dy_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dy_{n}\\
 & =\int_{V}(f\circ T)\det(J(T))dy_{1}\cdots dy_{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

On the other hand, the change-of-variables formula from advanced calculus
 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega=\int_{U}fdx_{1}\cdots dx_{n}=\int_{V}(f\circ T)|\det(J(T))|dy_{1}\cdots dy_{n},
\]

\end_inset

with an absolute-value sign around the Jacobian determinant.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}T^{*}\omega=\pm\int_{U}\omega,
\]

\end_inset

depending on whether the Jacobian determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(J(T))$
\end_inset

 is positive or negative.
 In particular, the integral of a differential form is not invariant under
 all diffeomorphisms of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, but only under orientation-preserving diffeomorphisms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Integral of a Differential Form over a Manifold
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integration of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is not so different from integration of a function.
 Our approach to integration over a general manifold has several distinguishing
 features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The manifold must be oriented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On a manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one can integrate only 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms, not functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-forms must have compact support.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an oriented manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, with an oriented atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 giving the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{c}^{k}(M)$
\end_inset

 the vector space of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-forms with compact support on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a chart in this atlas.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(U)$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega=\int_{\phi(U)}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega.
\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is another chart in the oriented atlas with the same 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\psi^{-1}\psi(U)\to\phi(U)$
\end_inset

 is an orientation-preserving diffeomorphism, and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\phi(U)}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega=\int_{\psi(U)}(\phi\circ\psi^{-1})^{*}(\phi^{-1})^{*}\omega=\int_{\psi(U)}(\psi^{-1})^{*}\omega.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U}\omega$
\end_inset

 on a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of the atlas is well defined, independent of the choice of coordinates
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 By linearity of the integral on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\tau\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(U)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{U}\omega+\tau=\int_{U}\omega+\int_{U}\tau.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{c}^{n}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a partition of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 subordinate to the open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has compact support and a partition of unity has locally finite supports,
 all except finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 are identically zero.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\sum_{\alpha}\rho_{\alpha}\omega
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\emph on
finite 
\emph default
sum.
 Also since 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}\left(\rho_{\alpha}\omega\right)\subset\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha})\cap\text{supp}(\omega)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha}\omega)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of the compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{supp}(\rho_{\alpha}\omega)$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form with compact support in the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, its integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 Therefore, we can define the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be the finite sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{M}\omega:=\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega.\label{eq:integralofnform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For this integral to be well defined, we must show that it is independent
 of the choices of oriented atlas and partition of unity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

 be another oriented atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 specifying the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\chi_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

 a partition of unity subordinate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{\beta}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta},\phi_{\alpha}|_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}})\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta},\psi_{\beta}|_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}})\}$
\end_inset

 are two new atlases of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 specifying the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega & =\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\chi_{\beta}\omega & (\text{because }\sum_{\beta}\chi_{\beta}=1)\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}\omega & (\text{these are finite sums})\\
 & =\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}\int_{U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}}\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}\omega,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last line follows from the fact that the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\alpha}\chi_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\alpha}\cap V_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 By symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\beta}\int_{V_{\beta}}\chi_{\beta}\omega$
\end_inset

 is equal to the same sum.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\alpha}\int_{U_{\alpha}}\rho_{\alpha}\omega=\sum_{\beta}\int_{V_{\beta}}\chi_{\beta}\omega,
\]

\end_inset

proving that the integral 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:integralofnform})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quotients and Gluing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many important topological spaces (and manifolds) that are constructed
 by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

identifying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pieces of spaces.
 This typically takes the form of gluing along open sets or passing to quotients
 by (reasonable) equivalence relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Quotient Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that an equivalence relation on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a reflexive, symmetric, and transitive relation.
 The 
\series bold
equivalence class 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is the set of all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into disjoint equivalence classes.
 We denote the set of equivalence classes by 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 and call this set the 
\series bold
quotient 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural 
\series bold
projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/\sim$
\end_inset

 
\series default
that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 to its equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Assume now that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space.
 We define a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 by declaring a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 to be open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, both the empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and the entire quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 are open.
 Further, since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}\right)=\bigcup_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}\left(U_{i}\right)\text{ and }\pi^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}U_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\pi^{-1}\left(U_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

the collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed under arbitrary unions and finite intersections, and is therefore
 a topology.
 It is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 With this topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
quotient space 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 The way we defined the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 makes the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Continuity of a Map on a Quotient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and is constant on each equivalence class.
 Then it induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:X/\sim\to Y$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}([x])=f(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The induced map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:X/\sim\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous if and only if the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\overline{f}\circ\pi$
\end_inset

 is a composition of two continuous functions.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(V)=\pi^{-1}\left(\overline{f}^{-1}(V)\right)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By the definition of quotient topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous since 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 was arbitary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Identification of a Subset to a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim x\text{ for all }x\in X\text{ and }x\sim y\text{ for all }x,y\in A.
\]

\end_inset

This is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\series bold
identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to a point
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the quotient space obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 by identifying the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 to a point.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 the unit circle in the complex plane.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:I\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=e^{2\pi ix}$
\end_inset

, assumes the same value at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and so induces a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:I/\sim\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 As the continuous image of a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous bijection from the compact space 
\begin_inset Formula $I/\sim$
\end_inset

 to the Hausdorff space 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence it is a homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Open Equivalence Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

An equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:X\to X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is open.
 In other words, the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if for every open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(U))=\bigcup_{x\in U}[x]
\]

\end_inset

of all points equivalent to some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be the equivalence relation on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that identifies the two points 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}/\sim$
\end_inset

 be the projection map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is not an open map.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-2,0)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(\pi(V))=(-2,0)\cup\{1\},
\]

\end_inset

which is not open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 that defines the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)\in X\times X\mid x\sim y\}.
\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
graph 
\series default
of the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremquotientishausdorff}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff if and only if the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is a sequence of equivalent statements: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 iff for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in(X\times X)\backslash R$
\end_inset

, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U\times V)\cap R=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 iff for every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $x\not\sim y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 iff for any two points 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

, there exist neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)\cap\pi(V)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now show that this last statement is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 being Hausdorff.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]$
\end_inset

 respectively, so 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\neq[y]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exist disjoint open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[y]\in B$
\end_inset

.
 By the surjectivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(\pi^{-1}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(\pi^{-1}B)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\pi^{-1}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\pi^{-1}B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\pi(V)$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an open equivalence relation on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{B_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then its image 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B(\alpha)\}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of open sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be an open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]\in W$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

 is open, there is a basic open set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B\subset\pi^{-1}(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]=\pi(x)\in\pi(B)\subset W$
\end_inset

, which proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\pi(B_{\alpha})\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $S/\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation on a second-countable space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then the quotient space is second-countable.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotients by Group Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many important manifolds are constructed as quotients by actions of groups
 on other manifolds, and this often provides a useful way to understand
 spaces that may have been constructed by other means.
 As a basic example, the Klein bottle will be defined as a quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 by the action of a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The circle as defined concretely in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by additive translation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a discrete group, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 be a right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
continuous 
\series default
if it is continuous as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\colon X\times G\to G$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is continuous if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{g}\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{g}(x)=xg$
\end_inset

 is continuous (and hence a homeomorphism with inverse being 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{g^{-1}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
free 
\series default
if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 the stabilizer subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Stab}_{G}(x)=\{g\in G\mid xg=x\}
\]

\end_inset

is the trivial subgroup (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $xg=x$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
properly discontinuous
\series default
 when it is continuous for the discrete topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that the 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-translate 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}g$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

 is necessarily finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

What does it mean for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to be continuous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,g)\in X\times G$
\end_inset

? It means that for all open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $xg$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $gy\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, we can characterize continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 using the sequential criterion: let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},g_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times G$
\end_inset

 which converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,g)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n}g_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $xg$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has the discrete topology, eventually we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}=g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},g_{n})\to(x,g)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can restate the sequential criterion as: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}g\to xg$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a locally Hausdorff space, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on the right via a properly discontinuous action.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we get an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}g$
\end_inset

 for only finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 This property is unaffected by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 with a smaller open subset around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so by the locally Hausdorff property we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 The key is that we can do better: there exists an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}g$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=xg$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if the action is also free then 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U'_{x}g$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Indeed, observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $xg\neq x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\cap U_{x}g\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then by the Hausdorff property of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}^{g}\subseteq U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $xg$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}\cap V_{x}^{g}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 By continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{g}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, there exists an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}_{x}^{g}\subseteq U_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}_{x}^{g}g\subseteq V_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

.
 By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}g\subseteq V_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}\cap U_{x}^{g}g=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 We now set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{x}'=\bigcap_{\begin{subarray}{c}
g\in G\backslash\mathrm{Stab}(x)\\
U_{x}\cap U_{x}g\neq\emptyset
\end{subarray}}U_{x}^{g}
\]

\end_inset

The intersection is finite, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'$
\end_inset

 is open (and contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 since each 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}^{g}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 Furthermore we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}'\cap U_{x}'g\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xg=g$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The interest in free and properly discontinuous actions is that for such
 actions in the locally Hausdorff case we may find an open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 around each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}g$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for such actions we may say that in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash G$
\end_inset

 we are identifying points in the same 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbit with this identification process not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crushing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by identifying points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are arbitrarly close to each other.
 An example where things go horribly wrong is the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 via additive translations.
 This is a continuous action, but the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\slash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is very bad: any two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

-orbits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 contain arbitrarily close points! Here are some examples of free and properly
 discontinuous actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The antipodal map on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n+1})\mapsto(-x_{1},\dots,-x_{n+1})=-\boldsymbol{x},
\]

\end_inset

viewed as an action of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the cyclic group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

) is free and properly discontinuous: freeness is clear, as is continuity,
 and for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 the points near 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 all have their antipodes far away! For instance, consider the small open
 ball centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}(\boldsymbol{x})=\{\boldsymbol{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\mid\|\boldsymbol{y}-\boldsymbol{x}\|<\varepsilon\},
\]

\end_inset

and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{S^{n}}(\boldsymbol{x}):=\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}(\boldsymbol{x})\cap S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{S^{n}}(\boldsymbol{x})\subseteq S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is open and a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

, and choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 small enough (say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\leq1/2$
\end_inset

), we can ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{S^{n}}(\boldsymbol{x})\cap\mathrm{B}_{\varepsilon}^{S^{n}}(-\boldsymbol{x})=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $X:=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{C}}(x^{3}+y^{3}+z^{3}-1)\subseteq\mathbb{C}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)\mapsto(\zeta_{3}x,\zeta_{3}y,\zeta_{3}z)$
\end_inset

, viewed as an action of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is free and properly discontinuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S^{1}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be a product of two circles, where the circle 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{1}=\{z\in\mathbb{C}\mid|z|=1\}
\]

\end_inset

is viewed as a topological group (using multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, so both the group law and inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto1/z=\overline{z}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are continuous).
 The visibly continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $(z,w)\mapsto(1/z,-w)=(\overline{z},-w)$
\end_inset

 reflects through the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis in the first circle and rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $180$
\end_inset

-degree in the second circle, and it is its own inverse.
 Thus, this give an action by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which is free and properly discontinuous.
 The associated quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash G$
\end_inset

 will be called the (set-theoretic) 
\series bold
Klein bottle
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a locally Hausdorff topological space equipped with a free and properly
 discontinuous action by a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 There is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash G$
\end_inset

 such that the quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon X\to X\slash G$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map that is a local homeomorphism (i.e.
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 admits a neighborhood mapping homeomorphically onto an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\slash G$
\end_inset

).
 Moreover, the quotient map is open.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq X\slash G$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if its preimage in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is open, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an open set that is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $Ug$
\end_inset

 for all nontrivial 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to X\slash G$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its open image 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 and the natural map 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times G\to\pi^{-1}(\overline{U})$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,g)\mapsto ug$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism when 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is given the discrete topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The topology in this theorem is called the 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
, and it is locally Hausdorff since 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X/G$
\end_inset

 is a local homeomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sketch: we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an open map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 The inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a disjoint union of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{g\in G}U_{x}.g$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U_{x})$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be any open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}.g\cap U_{x}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G\backslash\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\subset U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(U)=\pi\left(\bigcup_{x\in U}U_{x}\right)=\bigcup_{x\in U}\pi(U_{x})
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(U)$
\end_inset

 is open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Möbius Strip) Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(-a,a)\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

, and let the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 act on it with the non-trivial element acting by 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\mapsto(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 This is easily checked to be a continuous action for the discrete topology
 of the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and it is free and properly discontinuous.
 The quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Möbius strip 
\series default
of height 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To check that the Möbius strip 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff, we use the quotient criterion: the set of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 with the form 
\begin_inset Formula $((t,w),(t',w'))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(t,w)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')=(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

 is checked to be closed by using the sequential criterion in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\sim(t'_{n},w'_{n})$
\end_inset

 are sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 which converge 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\sim(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)\neq(t',w')$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(t',w')$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U'=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and such that eventually 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n},w_{n})\neq(t_{n}',w_{n}')$
\end_inset

 (We can do this because they converge to different limits and our space
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff).
 Thus, eventually we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{n}',w_{n}')=(-t_{n},-w_{n})\to(-t,-w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have a right action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{x}\cdot\boldsymbol{a}=(x_{1}+a_{1},x_{2}+a_{2})\label{eq:Torusactionfwefd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=(a_{1},a_{2})\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in(x_{1},x_{2})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The action 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:Torusactionfwefd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is free since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\cdot\boldsymbol{a}=\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Next observe that the action 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:Torusactionfwefd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is properly discontinuous.
 Indeed, it is continuous as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\times\mathbb{Z}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 since for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1},x_{2})=\boldsymbol{x}\mapsto\boldsymbol{x}\cdot\boldsymbol{a}=(x_{1}+a_{1},x_{2}+a_{2})
\]

\end_inset

is continuous (as the component functions are continuous).
 Furthermore, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{\boldsymbol{x}}=\{\boldsymbol{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid\|\boldsymbol{y}-\boldsymbol{x}\|_{\infty}<1/2\}=(x_{1}-1/2,x_{1}+1/2)\times(x_{2}-1/2,x_{2}+1/2),
\]

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is the open square centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 whose sides have length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\boldsymbol{x}}\cdot\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{Z}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Möbius Strip in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that the Möbius strip 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 (with height 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

) was defined as an abstract smooth manifold made as a quotient of 
\begin_inset Formula $(-a,a)\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

 by a free and properly discontinuous action by the group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Using the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}/2\pi\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mapsto(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)$
\end_inset

, we consider the standard parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as a local coordinate on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For finite 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(t,\theta)\mapsto(2a\cos2\theta+t\cos\theta\cos2\theta,2a\sin2\theta+t\cos\theta\sin2\theta,t\sin\theta).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(-t,\pi+\theta)=f(t,\theta)$
\end_inset

 by inspection, it follows from the universal property of the quotient map
 
\begin_inset Formula $(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to M_{a}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 uniquely factors through this via a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}:M_{a}\to\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Our goal is to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is an embedding and to use this viewpoint to understand some basic properties
 of the Möbius strip.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is an immersion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first reduce the problem to working with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is given by a simple explicit formula across its entire domain (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 does not have global coordinates.
 Of course, working locally for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the same
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as working locally for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, so the reduction step to working with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 isn't really necessary if one says things a little differently.
 However, it seems a bit cleaner to just make the reduction step right away
 and so to thereby work with the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that feel a bit more concrete than the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 at the global level.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:(-a,a)\times S^{1}\to M_{a}$
\end_inset

 be the natural quotient map.
 Each point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{a}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the Chain Rule gives that the injection 
\begin_inset Formula $df(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $d\overline{f}(p(\xi_{0}))\circ dp(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $dp(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 an isomorphism (as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a local 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism, via the theory of quotients by free and properly discontinuous
 group actions).
 Hence, the tangent map for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is injective at 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\xi_{0})$
\end_inset

 if and only if the tangent map for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is injective at 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is therefore enough (even equivalent!) to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an immersion.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Construction of Manifolds From Gluing Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The definition of a manifold assumes that the underlying set, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, is already known.
 However, there are situations where we only have some indirect information
 about the overlap of the domains 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the local charts defining our manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, in terms of the transition functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}:\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})\to\phi_{j}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}),
\]

\end_inset

but where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 itself is not known.
 Our goal in this subsection is to try and reconstruct a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by gluing open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 using the transition functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defngluingmanifold}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be an integer with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be either an integer with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 A set of 
\series bold
gluing data 
\series default
is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}=((\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K}),
\]

\end_inset

satisfying the following properties, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a (nonempty) countable set and 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\{(i,j)\in I\times I\mid\Omega_{ij}\neq\emptyset\}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 called a 
\series bold
parametrization domain
\series default
, for short, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-domain
\series default
, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise disjoint (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}\cap\Omega_{j})=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in I\times I$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ii}=\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Each nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

) is called a 
\series bold
gluing domain
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}:\Omega_{ij}\to\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 bijection for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 called a 
\series bold
transition function 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
gluing function
\series default
) and the following condition holds:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
cocycle condition 
\series default
holds: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\cap\Omega_{jk}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk})\subseteq\Omega_{ik}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ki}(x)=(\phi_{kj}\circ\phi_{ji})(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{ji}\cap\Omega_{jk})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\partial(\Omega_{ij})\cap\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\partial(\Omega_{ji})\cap\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

, there are open balls, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, so that no point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}\cap\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the image of any point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\cap\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In practical applications, the index set, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, is of course finite and the open subsets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, may have special properties (for example, connected; open simplicies,
 etc.).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}\subseteq\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}\subseteq\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint, so are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The cocycle condition may seem overly complicated but it is actually needed
 to guarantee the transitivity of the relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, which we will define shortly.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

 are bijections, the cocycle condition implies the following conditions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ii}=\text{id}_{\Omega_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 This follows by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j=k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}=\phi_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from (a) and by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $k=i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(U_{i},\phi_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an atlas on it.
 Then set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}=\phi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}=\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}:\Omega_{ji}\to\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding transition maps.
 Then it's easy to check that the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

, and the gluing functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}$
\end_inset

, satisfy the conditions of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defngluingmanifold})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk}) & =(\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1})(\phi_{j}(U_{j}\cap U_{k}))\\
 & =\phi_{i}(U_{j}\cap U_{k})\\
 & =\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{j}\cap U_{k})\\
 & \subseteq\phi_{i}(U_{i}\cap U_{k})\\
 & =\Omega_{ik}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us show that a set of gluing data defines a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold in a natural way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For every set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

, whose transition functions are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define the binary relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, on the disjoint union, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega:=\coprod_{i\in I}\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the open sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, as follows: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim y\text{ if and only if there exists }(i,j)\in K\text{ such that }x\in\Omega_{ij},\text{ }y\in\Omega_{ji},\text{ and }y=\phi_{ji}(x).
\]

\end_inset

The cocycle condition ensures that this is an equivalence relation.
 Indeed, (a) implies reflexivity and (b) implies symmetry.
 The crucial step is to check transitivity.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim z$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are some 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}(x)=y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{kj}(y)=z$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{kj}\circ\phi_{ji})(x)=\phi_{ki}(x)=z$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

, as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\mathcal{G}}:=\Omega/\sim
\]

\end_inset

be the quotient space by the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=\coprod_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}\left(\pi\left(U\right)\right)=\coprod_{i\in I}\left(\bigcup_{j\in I}\phi_{ij}\left(U_{j}\cap\Omega_{ji}\right)\cup U_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ij}\left(U_{j}\cap\Omega_{ji}\right)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is second-countable since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is second-countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an open equivalence relation, we can use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremquotientishausdorff})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff by showing that the graph 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\left\{ (x,y)\in\Omega\times\Omega\mid x\sim y\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\times\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by showing that if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\Omega\times\Omega$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in R$
\end_inset

.
 That is to say, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\Omega_{i}\times\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})\in\Omega_{i}\times\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 (since it will eventually be in there anyways).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=y_{n}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In order for us to have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

, then it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\sim y_{n}$
\end_inset

 in arbitrarily small neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we need to show that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\partial(\Omega_{ij})\cap\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\partial(\Omega_{ji})\cap\Omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose open balls 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 so that no point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}\cap\Omega_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the image of any point of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\cap\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies that no point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to some point in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}\to y$
\end_inset

, as the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n},y_{n})$
\end_inset

 must eventually be in the neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{in}_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to\coprod_{i\in I}\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the natural injection and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}:=\pi\circ\text{in}_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to M_{\mathcal{G}}.
\]

\end_inset

Since we already noted that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, we conclude that every 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=\tau_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, it is immediately verified that the 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\phi_{i})$
\end_inset

 are charts and this collection of charts forms a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 atlas for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}^{-1}(\Omega_{jk})\subseteq\Omega_{ik}$
\end_inset

 is needed in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 to be transitive.
 The picture below illustrates how things could go wrong:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename cocyclecondition.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobius Strip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the set of all lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to give this set the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

-manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all nonvertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonvertical is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid y=ax+b\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}:U_{v}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a,b}^{v}\mapsto(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all nonhorizontal lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A nonhorizontal is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid x=cy+d\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such line is uniquely determined by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}:U_{h}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c,d}^{h}\mapsto(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 We give 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 a topology using the bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{v}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}(U)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{h}$
\end_inset

 into a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}\cup U_{h}=X$
\end_inset

.
 To get a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we glue the topologies from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

: a set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{h}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{v}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the transition maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{vh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{hv}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{vh}(c,d) & =\varphi_{v}\circ\varphi_{h}^{-1}(c,d)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{c,d}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{v}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{c},-\frac{d}{c}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{hv}(a,b) & =\varphi_{h}\circ\varphi_{v}^{-1}(a,b)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{a,b}^{v}\right)\\
 & =\varphi_{h}\left(\ell_{\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}}^{h}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether, our gluing data consists of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega_{1}=\Omega_{2}=\mathbb{R}^{2},\qquad\Omega_{12}=\Omega_{21}=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\},\qquad\phi_{12}:(a,b)\mapsto\left(\frac{1}{a},-\frac{b}{a}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This manifold is called the 
\series bold
Mobius strip
\series default
.
 We can visualize it as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Mobiusstrip.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can describe this manifold in another way as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be the group given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G:=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{R}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

The group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a natural open subgroup
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Aff}(\mathbb{R})=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a,b\in\mathbb{R}\text{ and }a\neq0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 can be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}=\Omega_{2}=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Aff}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 can be identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{12}=\Omega_{21}=\{(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid a\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these identifications, the transition map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{12}$
\end_inset

 is identified with the inverse map! Indeed, the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1/a & -b/a\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given a set of gluing data, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, it is natural to consider the collection of manifolds, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, parametrized by maps, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}:\Omega_{i}\to M$
\end_inset

, whose domains are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

's and whose transition functions are given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}$
\end_inset

's, that is, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

We will say that such manifolds are 
\series bold
induced 
\series default
by the set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The parametrization maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the property: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})\cap\tau_{j}(\Omega_{j})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

 and if so, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}(\Omega_{i})\cap\tau_{j}(\Omega_{j})=\tau_{i}(\Omega_{ij})=\tau_{j}(\Omega_{ji}).
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, they also satisfy the consistency condition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}=\tau_{j}\circ\phi_{ji},
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a manifold induced by the set of gluing data 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

, then because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

's are injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, the two properties stated above for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

's also hold for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 We will see that the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

universal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 manifold induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 in the sense that every manifold induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathcal{G}}$
\end_inset

 by some 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Interestingly, it is possible to characterize when two manifolds induced
 by the same set of gluing data are isomorphic in terms of a condition on
 their transition functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given any set of gluing data, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=(\Omega_{i})_{i\in I},(\Omega_{ij})_{(i,j)\in I\times I},(\phi_{ji})_{(i,j)\in K})$
\end_inset

, for any two manifolds 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 given by families of parametrizations 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega_{i},\theta_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega_{i},\theta'_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, respectively, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:M\to M'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 isomorphism, then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 bijections, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}:W_{ij}\to W'_{ij},$
\end_inset

 for some open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij},W'_{ij}\subseteq\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{ji}'(x)=\rho_{j}\circ\phi_{ji}\circ\rho_{i}^{-1}(x),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}=\theta_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ji}'=\theta'{}_{j}^{-1}\circ\theta'{}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}=(\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i})\mid_{W_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 to itself and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'{}_{i}^{-1}\circ f\circ\theta_{i}(\Omega_{ij})=\Omega_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij}=W'_{ij}=\Omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ringed Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{locallyringedspacesdefn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
ringed space 
\series default
is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of commutative 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebras on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
locally 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\series default
is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that the stalk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 is a local ring for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We then denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x):=\mathcal{O}_{X,x}/\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 its residue field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equivalence between 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structures and maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq p\leq\infty$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological premanifold.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}=\{(\phi_{i},U_{i})\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}'=\{(\phi{}_{i'}',U{}_{i'})\}$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlases on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\colon U_{i}\to V_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'_{i'}\colon U'_{i'}\to V'_{i'}$
\end_inset

 are homeomorphisms onto nonempty open subsets of finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces, and the resulting homeomorphisms
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i_{1}}\circ\phi_{i_{2}}^{-1}\colon\phi_{i_{2}}(U_{i_{1}}\cap U_{i_{2}})\to\phi_{i_{1}}(U_{i_{1}}\cap U_{i_{2}})\quad\text{and}\quad\phi_{i_{1}'}'\circ\phi-1\colon\phi_{i_{2}'}'(U_{i_{1}'}'\cap U_{i_{2}'}')\to\phi_{i_{1}'}'(U_{i_{1}'}'\cap U_{i_{2}'}')
\]

\end_inset

between open domains in the vector spaces are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms in the usual sense.
 Let us say that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}-\{(\phi_{i},U_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
standardized 
\series default
if the following two conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for each 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{i},U_{i})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 the target vector space for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\colon U_{i}\to V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 uniquely determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty), and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 has no repititions in the sense that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 we have either 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\neq U_{j}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=U_{j}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=n_{j}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=U_{j}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty) the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i},\phi_{j}\colon U_{i}\rightrightarrows\mathbb{R}^{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 do not coincide.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are insisting on the lack of repetitions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

, we may and do drop the indexing set for such atlases: a standardized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 atlas is a certain kind o fsubset of the set of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto an open subset of a Euclidean space (note that
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is permitted to vary, though it is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}'$
\end_inset

 are standarized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlases on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then it makes sense to ask if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}\subseteq\mathscr{A}'$
\end_inset

.
 This means that each 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is equal to some 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi',U')\in\mathscr{A}'$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a standarized atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

' 
\series bold
dominates 
\series default
a standarized atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}\subseteq\mathscr{A}'$
\end_inset

 in the sense just defined.
 It is clear that if two standardized atlases dominate each other then they
 are literally equal.
 A standardized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
maximal 
\series default
if it is not strictly contained inside of another standarized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 atlas of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Structures to Maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Atlases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty open set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon(U,\mathcal{O}\mid_{U})\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-isomorphism onto an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U)\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 given its usual 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structure).
 The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 atlas because of two facts: a composite of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 maps is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

, and for maps between opens in finite-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 is the same as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notion (in terms of structured 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-spaces).
 It is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is standardized.
 We want to prove that the standardized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is maximal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us see that we can recover 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any nonempty open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}\colon\phi(U\cap U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in the target Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 on the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

 says exactly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}\in\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}(\phi(U\cap U_{0}))$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}$
\end_inset

 denoting the usual 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 defines a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-isomorphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}|_{U})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi(U),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}|_{\phi(U)})$
\end_inset

, by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, it follows that composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 carries 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}(\phi(U'))$
\end_inset

 bijectively over to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U')$
\end_inset

 for any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $U'=U\cap U_{0}$
\end_inset

, we conclude that the condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)$
\end_inset

 in the theorem says exactly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 is an atlas, so as we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 the opens 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 cover 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, it follows that as we vary 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi,U)\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 the opens 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{0}$
\end_inset

 cover 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 By the locality axiom for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 if and only if its restriction to each 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{0}$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

, and hence if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}\colon\phi(U\cap U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on the open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From Maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Atlases to 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-Structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal standarized 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

-atlas on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For any non-empty open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 to be the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

, the composite map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ\phi^{-1}\colon\phi(U\cap U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U\cap U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in the Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 that is the target of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\emptyset)=\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\mapsto\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-space structure on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and open 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{0}\subseteq U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{0}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\phi^{-1}:\phi(U_{0})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on the open domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(U_{0})$
\end_inset

 in a Euclidean space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The usual notion of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

 function on an open set in a Euclidean space is preserved under restirction
 to smaller opens and can be checked by working on an open covering.
 Thus, the first claim in the lemma follows easily from the definition of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
deRham Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y)=\langle P(x,y),Q(x,y)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a smooth vector field representing a force on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a parametrized curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)=(x(t),y(t))$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq t\leq b$
\end_inset

.
 Then the work done by the force in moving a particle from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is given by the line integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{C}Pdx+Qdy$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Such a line integral is easy to compute if the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the gradient of a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\text{grad}f=\langle\partial_{x}f,\partial_{y}f\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

By Stoke's theorem, the line integral is simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{C}\partial_{x}fdx+\partial_{y}fdy=\int_{C}df=f(q)-f(p).
\]

\end_inset

A necessary condition for the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\langle P,Q\rangle$
\end_inset

 to be a gradient is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{y}=\partial_{y}\partial_{x}f=\partial_{x}\partial_{y}f=Q_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question is now the following: if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{y}-Q_{x}=0$
\end_inset

, is the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\langle P,Q\rangle$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 the gradient of some scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

? In terms of differential forms, the question becomes the following: if
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=Pdx+Qdy$
\end_inset

 is closed on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, is it exact? The answer to this question is sometimes yes and sometimes
 no, depending on the topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
de Rham Complex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a manifold and let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 denote the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{0}(M):=C^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have the following cochain complex over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramomega}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} ( 
\backslash
Omega (M),d) := & 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
Omega ^0 (M) 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d"] & 
\backslash
Omega ^1 (M)  
\backslash
arrow[r," d  "] & 
\backslash
Omega ^2 (M) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "d" ] & 
\backslash
cdots, 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 denotes the exterior derivative.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the cohomology of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

 and call it the 
\series bold
deRham cohomology 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the cycles of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B(M)$
\end_inset

 to be the boundaries of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega(M),d)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components, then its de Rham cohomology in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(M)=\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 An element of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(M)$
\end_inset

 is specified by an ordered- 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-tuple of real numbers, each real number representing a constant function
 on a connected component of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since there are no nonzero exact 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-forms, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{0}(M)=Z^{0}(M).
\]

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a closed 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $df=0$
\end_inset

.
 On any chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
df=\sum_{\lambda=1}^{n}(\partial_{x_{\lambda}}f)dx_{\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $df=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if and only if all the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{\lambda}}f$
\end_inset

 vanish identically on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 being locally constant on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the closed 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are precisely the locally constant functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function must be constant on each connected component on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 connected components, then a locally constant function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be specified by an ordered set of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 real numbers.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{0}(M)=\mathbb{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the de Rham cohomology 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{k}(M)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 is a vector space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}\in A_{k}(T_{p}M)$
\end_inset

, the space of alternating 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-linear functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}(T_{p}M)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

, the only 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the zero form.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of de Rham Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (De Rham cohomology of the real line) Since the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is connected, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{0}(\mathbb{R}^{1})=\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

For dimensional reasons, there are no nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that every 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)dx$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is exact if and only if three is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)dx=dg=g'(x)dx,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)$
\end_inset

 is the calculus derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is simply an antiderivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, for example 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt.
\]

\end_inset

This proves that every 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(\mathbb{R}^{1})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (De Rham cohomology of the circle) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the unit circle in the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

-plane.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is connected, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{0}(S^{1})=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{k}(S^{1})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(S^{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=(\cos t,\sin t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $i:[0,2\pi]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be the inclusion map.
 Restricting the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,2\pi]$
\end_inset

 gives a parametrization 
\begin_inset Formula $F:=h\circ i:[0,2\pi]\to S^{1}$
\end_inset

 of the circle.
 A nowhere-vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=-ydx+xdy$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h^{*}\omega & =-\sin td(\cos t)+\cos td(\sin t)\\
 & =(\sin^{2}t+\cos^{2}t)dt\\
 & =dt.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F^{*}\omega & =i^{*}h^{*}\omega\\
 & =i^{*}dt\\
 & =dt,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{S^{1}}\omega & =\int_{F([0,2\pi])}\omega\\
 & =\int_{[0,2\pi]}F^{*}\omega\\
 & =\int_{0}^{2\pi}dt\\
 & =2\pi.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the cirle has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, all 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are closed, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{1}(S^{1})=Z^{1}(S^{1})$
\end_inset

.
 The integration of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 defines a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:Z^{1}(S^{1})=\Omega^{1}(S^{1})\to\mathbb{R},\quad\varphi(\alpha)=\int_{S^{1}}\alpha.
\]

\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\omega)=2\pi\neq0$
\end_inset

, the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\Omega^{1}(S^{1})\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is onto.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By Stokes's theorem, the exact 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, we will show that all 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-forms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 are exact.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=f\omega$
\end_inset

 is a smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}=h^{*}f=f\circ h\in\Omega^{0}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset

 is periodic of period 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\int_{S^{1}}\alpha\\
 & =\int_{F([0,2\pi])}F^{*}\alpha\\
 & =\int_{[0,2\pi]}(i^{*}h^{*}f)(t)\cdot F^{*}\omega\\
 & =\int_{0}^{2\pi}\overline{f}(t)dt.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 Hairy Ball Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the unit sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

.
 FIf 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd then there exists a nowhere-vanishing smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2k+1$
\end_inset

 the consider the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}=\mathbb{R}^{2k+2}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=(-x_{2}\partial_{x_{1}}+x_{1}\partial_{x_{2}})+\cdots+(-x_{2k+2}\partial_{x_{2k+1}}+x_{2k+1}\partial_{x_{2k+2}})=\sum_{j=0}^{k}(-x_{2j+2}\partial_{x_{2j+1}}+x_{2j+1}\partial_{x_{2j+2}}).
\]

\end_inset

For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 it is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{2k+2})$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the line spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

, so it lies in the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 orthogonal to this line.
 In other words, the smooth section 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 of the pullback bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(T(\mathbb{R}^{n+1}))|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 takes values in the subbundle 
\begin_inset Formula $T(S^{n})$
\end_inset

, which is to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth vector field on the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a visibly nowhere-vanishing vector field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The above construction does not work if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, so there arises the question of whether there exists a nowhere-vanishi
ng smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 for even 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The answer is negative, and is called the 
\series bold
hairy ball 
\series default
theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 must vanish somewhere if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

, and assume that it is nowhere-vanishing.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}:[0,\pi/\|\vec{v}(p)\|]\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the smooth parametric great circle (with constant speed) going from
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-p$
\end_inset

 with velocity vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}'(0)=\vec{v}(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 (This would not make sense if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Working in the plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, we get the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{p}(t)=\cos\left(t\|\vec{v}(p)\|\right)p+\sin\left(t\|\vec{v}(p)\right)\frac{\vec{v}(p)}{\|\vec{v}(p)\|}\in S^{n}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(These algebraic formulas would not make sense if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 vanishes somewhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

).
 Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mapping 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F:S^{n}\times[0,1]\to S^{n},
\]

\end_inset

defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,t)\mapsto\gamma_{p}(\pi t/\|\vec{v}(p)\|)$
\end_inset

.
 The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 makes it clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map (and is continuous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is merely continuous and nowhere-vanishing).
 Now obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p,0)=p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(p,1)=-p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 defines a smooth homotopy from the identity map on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 to the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mapsto-p$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 (and is a continuous homotopy if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is merely continuous and nowhere-vanishing).
 Thus, to prove the hairy ball theorem we just have to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even then the identity and antipodal maps 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 are not smoothly homotopic to each other; likewise to get the continuous
 version we just need to prove that there is no continuous homotopy deforming
 one of these maps into the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove the 
\emph on
non-existence 
\emph default
of such a homotopy, we shall use the (smooth) homotopy invariance of deRham
 cohomology.
 Indeed, by this homotopy-invariance we get that under the existence of
 such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $A:S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 induces the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}:\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{k}(S^{n})\to\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{k}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th deRham cohomology of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let us focus on the case 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

.
 To get a contradiction, we just have to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 as a self-map of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{H}_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
the identity map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=\sum_{i=1}^{n+1}(-1)^{i-1}x_{i}dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge\widehat{dx}_{i}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $d\omega=(n+1)dx_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge dx_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, so for the unit ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 with its standard orientation we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{B^{n+1}}d\omega=(n+1)\text{vol}(B^{n+1})\neq0.
\]

\end_inset

By Stokes' theorem for 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\omega|_{S^{n}}$
\end_inset

 and we give 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}=\partial B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 the induced boundary orientation, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{S^{n}}\eta=\int_{B^{n+1}}d\omega\neq0.
\]

\end_inset

Hence, by Stokes' theorem for the boundaryless smooth compact oriented manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 we conclude that the top-degree differential form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is not exact.
 That is, its deRham cohomology class 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]\in H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is non-zero.
 (Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is not closed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, but its pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is necessarily closed on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 purely for elementary reasons, as 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By the existence of the smooth homotopy between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the identity map, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 is the identity map, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[A^{*}(\eta)]=A^{*}([\eta])$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the top-degree differential forms 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}(\eta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 differ by an exact form.
 But the antipodal map 
\begin_inset Formula $A:S^{n}\to S^{n}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the negation map 
\begin_inset Formula $N:\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\to\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, and by inspection of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega_{\mathbb{R}^{n+1}}^{n}(\mathbb{R}^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{*}(\omega)=(-1)^{n+1}\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, pulling back this equality to the sphere gives 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}(\eta)=(-1)^{n+1}\eta$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{S^{n}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{dR}}^{n}(S^{n})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\eta]=A^{*}([\eta])=[A^{*}(\eta)]=[(-1)^{n+1}\eta]=(-1)^{n+1}[\eta].
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even we therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]=-[\eta]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]=0.$
\end_inset

 But we have already seen via Stokes' theorem for the boundaryless manifold
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 and for the manifold with boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\eta]$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 This completes the proof.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R}):=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid ad-bc=1\right\} \subset\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be a path in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=\begin{pmatrix}a(t) & b(t)\\
c(t) & d(t)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=I:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then by differentiating the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)d(t)-b(t)c(t)=1$
\end_inset

 and evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\dot{a}(0)d(0)+a(0)\dot{d}(0)-\dot{b}(0)c(0)-b(0)\dot{c}(0)\\
 & =\dot{a}(0)+\dot{d}(0).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Or 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{a}(0)=-\dot{d}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tr}\left(\dot{\gamma}(0)\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose we have a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Tr}(A)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Can we find a path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(0)=A$
\end_inset

? Indeed, we can.
 The matrix exponential works: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{tA}:=I+A+\frac{1}{2}A^{2}+\frac{1}{6}A^{3}+\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

This is because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{tA}\right) & =\frac{d}{dt}\left(I+tA+\frac{1}{2}t^{2}A^{2}+\frac{1}{6}t^{3}A^{3}+\cdots\right)\\
 & =\frac{d}{dt}(I)+\frac{d}{dt}(tA)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d}{dt}(t^{2}A^{2})+\frac{1}{6}\frac{d}{dt}(t^{3}A^{3})+\cdots\\
 & =A+tA^{2}+\frac{1}{2}t^{2}A^{3}+\cdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{tA}\right)_{\mid t=0}=A$
\end_inset

.
 Also we have 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{tA}\in\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{det}(e^{tA}) & =e^{\text{Tr}(tA)}\\
 & =e^{0}\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R}):=\left\{ A\in\text{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})\mid AA^{t}=I\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be a path in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{SO}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=\begin{pmatrix}a(t) & b(t)\\
c(t) & d(t)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=I:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then by differentiating the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\gamma(t)\gamma(t)^{t}$
\end_inset

 and evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\dot{\gamma}(0)\gamma(0)^{t}+\gamma(0)\dot{\gamma}(0)^{t}\\
 & =\dot{\gamma}(0)+\dot{\gamma}(0)^{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(0)$
\end_inset

 is a skew-symmetric matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Field in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 be a vector field in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega:=(0,y,0):=y\partial_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's find a path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}=\omega(\gamma)$
\end_inset

.
 A general path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma(t):=(a(t),b(t),c(t))\qquad\text{and}\qquad\dot{\gamma}(t)=(\dot{a}(t),\dot{b}(t),\dot{c}(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega($
\end_inset

So we need 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{a}(t) & =0\\
\dot{b}(t) & =b(t)\\
\dot{c}(t) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=(a(0),b(0)e^{t},c(0))$
\end_inset

 works.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lie Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
Lie group 
\series default
is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 that is also a group such that the two group operations, multiplication
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\times G\to G,\qquad(a,b)\mapsto ab,
\]

\end_inset

and inverse
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\to G,\qquad a\mapsto a^{-1},
\]

\end_inset

are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

, denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}:G\to G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{a}(x)=ax$
\end_inset

, the operation of 
\series bold
left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
, and by 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}:G\to G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}(x)=xa$
\end_inset

, the operation of 
\series bold
right multiplication 
\series default
by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 We also call left and right multiplications 
\series bold
left 
\series default
and 
\series bold
right translations
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Actually smoothness of invsersion can be dropped from the definition of
 a Lie Group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifold and suppose it is equipped with a group structure such that the
 composition law 
\begin_inset Formula $m:G\times G\to G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inversion 
\begin_inset Formula $G\to G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shearing transformation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma:G\times G\to G\times G,
\]

\end_inset

defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma(g,h)=(g,gh)$
\end_inset

.
 This is bijective since we are using a group law, and it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 since the composition law 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 (Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $M,M',M''$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 manifolds, a map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M'\times M''$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its component maps 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to M''$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, due to the nature of product manifold structures.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 Granting this, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} G=
\backslash
{ e 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
times G  
\backslash
arrow[r] & G 
\backslash
times G 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
Sigma ^-1 "]  & G 
\backslash
times G 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, but explicitely this composite map is 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto(g,g^{-1})$
\end_inset

, so its second component 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 bijection, the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 property for its inverse is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 being a 
\series bold
local isomorphism 
\series default
(i.e.
 each point in its source has an open neighborhood carried diffeomorphically
 onto an open neighborhood in the target).
 By the Inverse Function Theorem, this is equivalent to the isomorphism
 property for the tangent map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\Sigma(g,h):T_{g}(G)\oplus T_{h}(G)=T_{(g,h)}(G\times G)\to T_{(g,gh)}(G\times G)=T_{g}(G)\oplus T_{gh}(G)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We shall now use left and right translations to reduce this latter 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem to the special case 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h=e$
\end_inset

, and in that special case we will be able to compute the tangent map explicitel
y and see the isomorphism property by inspection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Algebraic Geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout these notes, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 Unless otherwise specified, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be a positive integer.
 In this case, we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 to denote a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 Similarly we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]=K[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 to denote a polynomial ring in the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{T}=T_{1},\dots,T_{n}$
\end_inset

 with coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 whenever context is clear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will define 
\series bold
affine algebraic sets
\series default
.
 Before we do this, we first introduce the following notation: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a set of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{K}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

 to be the set of common zeros of the polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}_{K}(\mathcal{P})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }f\in\mathcal{P}\}.
\]

\end_inset

If the underlying field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, then we will simplify our notation and write
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{K}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

 is another set of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\subseteq\mathcal{Q}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{Q})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
inclusion-reversing
\series default
.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 is a Noetherian ring, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated as an ideal, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\mathrm{V}(\mathcal{P})=\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}),
\]

\end_inset

where we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})=\mathrm{V}(\{f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

 since the reverse inclusion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is inclusion-reversing.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}f_{i}\right)(\boldsymbol{x}) & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})\cdot0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}f_{i}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maximal ideals defined by points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\colon K[\boldsymbol{T}]\to K$
\end_inset

 be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}(T_{i})=x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 to be the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ev}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}=\{f\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}_{x}\cong K$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be another ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 in terms of the maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in K^{n}\mid\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use this reformulation many times throughout this article.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Zariski Topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are almost ready to define algebraic sets, but first we need to prove
 the following lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following relations hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(0)=K^{n}\text{ and }\mathrm{V}(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For two ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 of ideals, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(0)=K^{n}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\not\supseteq\langle1\rangle$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{ab}\subseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}\subseteq\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 from the inclusion-reversing property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{ab}$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But this follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}\right)=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda})$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is very important to pay close attention to what is actually used in
 proofs.
 For example, in the proof of the second statement of this lemma, we only
 used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal (even though it is a maximal ideal).
 This gives us an idea for how we can generalize things.
 In particular, we will be replacing maximal ideals of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 with arbitrary prime ideals.
 Keep this in mind! 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This lemma implies that there is a unique topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 for which the closed subsets are exactly those of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 We call this topology the 
\series bold
Zariski topology
\series default
 and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 to mean the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the Zariski topology.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
dimensional affine space
\series default
.
 Closed subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
affine algebraic sets
\series default
.
 In particular, note that singletons are closed since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{x}\}=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The unit circle in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be described as the variety 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

 and can be pictured below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $y$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-2,xmax=2,ymin=-2,ymax=2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-2,2},ytick={-2,2},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=80] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a nice parametrization of the unit circle which we now describe:
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a line which passes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is not the tangent line to the unit circle at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathrm{V}(y-m(x+1))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the line, and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passes through a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\neq(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 on the unit circle.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 lies on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and the unit circle, we get the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+y^{2}-1 & =0,\\
y-m(x+1) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the second relation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=m(x+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $m(x+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first relation, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{2}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}}=\frac{1-x}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, to get the following parametrization:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\frac{1-m^{2}}{1+m^{2}},\\
y & =\frac{2m}{1+m^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now suppose we throw in the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x$
\end_inset

.
 What does the affine variety 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x^{2}+y^{2}-1,y-x)$
\end_inset

 look like? The affine variety 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x^{2}+y^{2}-1,y-x)$
\end_inset

 consists of the points 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1},r_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}^{2}+r_{2}^{2}-1=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}-r_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 There are two such points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

, and they correspond to two intersection points of the unit circle with
 the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 as pictured below: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $y$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-2,xmax=2,ymin=-2,ymax=2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-2,2},ytick={-2,2},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=80] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=80] ({x},{x});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=right:$ p_1 $] (w) at (axis
 cs:0.707,0.707) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.5pt, label=left:$ p_2 $] (z) at (axis
 cs:-0.707,-0.707) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}_{K}(x^{2}+y^{2}-1)=\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}_{K}(y^{2}-x^{3}+x)=\mathrm{V}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 at the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(1,0)$
\end_inset

 as pictured below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $y$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-2,xmax=2,ymin=-2,ymax=2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-2,2},ytick={-2,2},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=100] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=below left:$ p $] (w) at (axis
 cs:-1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=below right:$ q $] (z) at
 (axis cs:1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle f\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle g\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cap Y$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes_{\Bbbk}B=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle f,g\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x+1,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

, thus the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}-u(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1-x$
\end_inset

 (this is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{p}$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}+ux(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}
\]

\end_inset

Then a calculation shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{p}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}-u(x+1),y^{2}+ux(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2},(x+1)^{2}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim_{\Bbbk}(A_{p}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{p})=4$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 intersect at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 Next, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(1,0)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}=\langle x-1,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

, thus the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}-\widetilde{u}(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}=1+x$
\end_inset

 (this is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{q}$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}+\widetilde{u}x(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}
\]

\end_inset

Then a calculation shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{q}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}-\widetilde{u}(1-x),y^{2}+\widetilde{u}v(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2},x-1\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim_{\Bbbk}(A_{q}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{q})=2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 intersect at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose we perturn 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 a bit; say 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}((x+t)^{2}+y^{2}-1)=\mathrm{V}(f_{t})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in K$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we can picture 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 intersecting 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as below: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $y$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-2,xmax=2,ymin=-2,ymax=2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-2,2},ytick={-2,2},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=100] ({cos(deg(x))+1/2},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=above:$ p_1 $] (w) at (axis
 cs:-0.33,0.54) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=below:$ p_2 $] (w) at (axis
 cs:-0.33,-0.54) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=right:$ q_1 $] (z) at (axis
 cs:1.2,0.73) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=right:$ q_2 $] (z) at (axis
 cs:1.2,-0.73) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Thus the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 splits into two points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and one can check that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 interesect at both 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hilbert's Nullstellensatz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 It is often advantageous to characterize the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in terms of some underlying geometric spaces.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a ring a functions on some space, then perhaps the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be described in terms of certain subspaces of that space.
 Let's us consider two examples of when we can/cannot do this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be the ring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
of continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to understand what the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 look like.
 First let's start with the maximal ideals.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}=\{f\in C(\mathbb{R})\mid f(x)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can describe a bunch of maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 in terms points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us a nice geometric way of describing some of the maximal ideals
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, but the question remains: does this describe all of the maximal ideals
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

? The answer is no.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 vanishes outside some compact set.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, and hence can be extended to a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is not of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since we can always find an 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The takeaway here is that the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 are complicated, and the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 doesn't do a good enough job at characterizing these ideals.
 One would need to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to a much larger space (like the hyperreals 
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

) in order to characterize the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact Hausdorff space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 be the ring of continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Again, we can characterize many of the maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, namely for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}=\{f\in C(X)\mid f(x)=0\}.$
\end_inset

 In this case, it turns out that all of the maximals ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\neq\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\in C(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, choose an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x}\mid x\in X\}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact, there exists a finite subcollection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x}\}$
\end_inset

 which covers 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{x_{1}},\dots,U_{x_{n}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\sum_{i=1}^{n}f_{x_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition.
 However note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 exists, or in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 This is a contradiction.
 We've just shown that the maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 does a nice job at describing the maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X).$
\end_inset

 On the other hand, there is still much more work to be done if we want
 to characterize 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 in terms of subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 We can interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 as the ring of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

.
 We also know some nice subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

, namely the affine algebraic subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 (which also happen to be the 
\emph on
closed 
\emph default
subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 in the Zariski topology).
 Every such affine algebraic subspace has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can characterize the affine algebraic subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 in terms of the ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 However we really want to go backwards: can we characterize the ideals
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[T]$
\end_inset

 in terms of the affine algebraic subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

? Hilbert Nullstellensatz tells us that we can almost do this; in particular
 we can characterize the 
\emph on
radical 
\emph default
ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[T]$
\end_inset

 in terms of the affine algebraic subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, there is a one-to-one correspondence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\text{radical ideals of }\overline{K}[T]\}\leftrightarrow\{\text{affine algebraic subspaces of }\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})\}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 gives a nice characterization of the radical ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 With this motivation out of the way, we now are ready to state Hilbert's
 Nullstellensatz in a more general setting:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hilbert's Nullstellensatz) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
Jacobson
\series default
, that is, for every prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{p}=\bigcap_{\begin{subarray}{c}
\mathfrak{m}\supset\mathfrak{p}\\
\mathfrak{m}\text{ is maximal}
\end{subarray}}\mathfrak{m}.
\]

\end_inset

Moroever, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We shall not prove this result here since a proof is best left for a course
 in Commutative Algebra (see my Algebra notes for such a proof).
 Instead, we will focus on the consequences of this theorem in regards to
 algebraic geometry.
 First let us consider some consequences when working over the algebraically
 closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

-algebra, thus from the Nullstellenatz, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}\hookrightarrow\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a finite extension of fields; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 by the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\to\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\overline{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal which contains the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}=\langle T_{1}-x_{1},\dots,T_{n}-x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore both are equal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The proposition above tells us that the set of all points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with the set of all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we really do need 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}$
\end_inset

 to be algebraically closed for this to hold.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle T^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]/\langle T^{2}+1\rangle\cong\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle T^{2}+1\rangle$
\end_inset

 does not come from a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 doesn't even vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there are more maximal ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 than just the ones which correspond to points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (there are more maximals ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

 than just those of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}=\langle T-x\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

).
 On the other hand, the Nullstellensatz guarentees that for all maximal
 ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

, we will have either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]\slash\mathfrak{m}\cong\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In the second case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and in the first case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\mathfrak{m}_{z,\overline{z}}=\langle(T-z)(T-\overline{z})\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a complex number in the upper-half plane (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Im}(z)>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Correspondence Between Radical Ideals and Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we shall focus on the consequences of Hilbert's Nullstellensatz when
 working over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily algebraically closed).
 To do this, we introduce the following notation: let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{K}(Z)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all functions which vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}_{K}(Z)=\{f\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }x\in Z\}.
\]

\end_inset

If the underlying field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, then we will simplify our notation and write
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{K}(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

, thus it is also called the ideal of functions which vanish on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Furthemore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Z)=\bigcap_{x\in Z}\mathfrak{m}_{x}.
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}\subset A\\
\mathfrak{p}\text{ prime ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{p}=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\subset A\\
\mathfrak{m}\text{ maximal ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{m}.
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, the first equality holds in arbitrary commutative rings and the
 second equality follows from Hilbert's Nullstellensatz.
 We shall use this fact to prove the following proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.12}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

 be a subset.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{IV}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)=\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(\overline{K})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}) & =\bigcap_{\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})}\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}\\
 & =\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\\
\text{maximal ideal}
}
}\mathfrak{m}\\
 & =\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 This is a simple assertion for which we do not need the Nullstellensatz.
 On the one hand we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathrm{VI}(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)\supseteq\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand let 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Z)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Z)\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Changing the Underlying Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be an extension of fields and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(L)$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
defined over 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{L}(V)$
\end_inset

 can be generated by polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}_{L}(V)=\mathrm{I}_{K}(V)L[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

.
 The set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series bold
-rational points 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(K)=V\cap\mathbb{A}^{n}(K).
\]

\end_inset

Now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a Galois extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{Gal}(L\slash K)$
\end_inset

.
 There is a natural action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(L)$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(\boldsymbol{x})=\sigma(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=(\sigma(x_{1}),\dots,\sigma(x_{n}))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(L)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{A}^{n}(L)$
\end_inset

, then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in G$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(f(\boldsymbol{x}))=f(\sigma(\boldsymbol{x})).
\]

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(L)$
\end_inset

 induces an action on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and clearly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(K)=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in V\mid\sigma(\boldsymbol{x})=\boldsymbol{x}\text{ for all }\sigma\in G\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\overline{\mathbb{Q}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq3$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathrm{V}_{\overline{\mathbb{Q}}}(T_{1}^{n}+T_{2}^{n}-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Fermat's last theorem, proven by Andrew Wiles in 1995, states that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\mathbb{Q})=\begin{cases}
\{(1,0),(0,1)\} & \text{if }n\text{ is odd.}\\
\{(\pm1,0),(0,\pm1)\} & \text{if }n\text{ is even.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}})$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many points.
 Let us try to describe these points using a fixed embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}\subseteq\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=re^{i\theta}$
\end_inset

 be its polar representation where 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{1/n}=r^{1/n}e^{i\theta/n}$
\end_inset

.
 We also set 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{n}=e^{2\pi i/n}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\overline{\mathbb{Q}}\subseteq\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\overline{\mathbb{Q}})=\begin{cases}
(\alpha,\zeta_{n}^{k}(1-\alpha^{n})^{1/n}) & 1\leq k\leq n\text{ if }1-\alpha^{n}\neq0\\
(\alpha,0) & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms of Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having defined affine algebraic sets, we now wish to define morphisms between
 them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(I)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(J)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a function.
 Then there exists functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\colon\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)$
\end_inset

 such that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{x})=(f_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}),\dots,f_{n}(\boldsymbol{x}))=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})=\boldsymbol{y}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{1},\dots,y_{n})\in Y$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 We call the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
representation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
components 
\series default
of this representation.
 Note that this representation need not be unique: there may exist a different
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\widetilde{f}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{f}_{n})$
\end_inset

 which represents 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as well.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
polynomial representation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 if each component function is a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{x}]=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
if there exists a polynomial representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
isomorphism 
\series default
if there exists a morphim 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g=1_{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=1_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all morphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{m}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the defining equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of morphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(y_{2}^{2}-y_{1})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x^{2},x)=\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism since it is represented by the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x]$
\end_inset

 and since it lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in Y$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)^{2}-x^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{y})=y_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a morphism since it is represented by the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g=y_{2}$
\end_inset

 and since it clearly lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, observe that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=(y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\circ g)(\boldsymbol{y}) & =f(y_{2})\\
 & =(y_{2}^{2},y_{2})\\
 & =(y_{1},y_{2})\\
 & =\boldsymbol{y},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}\in Y$
\end_inset

 to get from the second line to the third line.
 A similar calculation shows 
\begin_inset Formula $(g\circ f)(x)=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 being its inverse.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(x_{2}-x_{1}^{2},x_{3}-x_{1}^{3})=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},p_{2})$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(y_{2}-y_{1}-y_{1}^{2})=\mathrm{V}(q)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})=(x_{1}x_{2},x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3})=\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is represented by the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=x_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}$
\end_inset

, thus to see if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism, we just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we must check that the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q=y_{2}-y_{1}-y_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}=f(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

: we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
q(\boldsymbol{y}) & =y_{2}-y_{1}-y_{1}^{2}\\
 & =x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}-(x_{1}x_{2})^{2}\\
 & =x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}\\
 & =x_{3}-x_{1}^{3}\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in X$
\end_inset

 to get from the third line to the fifth line.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is in fact a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 Note that the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\colon K[\boldsymbol{y}]\slash\langle q\rangle\to K[\boldsymbol{x}]\slash\langle p_{1},p_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}(y_{1})=f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}(y_{2})=f_{2}$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{*}(y_{1}) & =x_{1}x_{2}\\
f^{*}(y_{2}) & =x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(T_{2}'^{2}-T_{1}')$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(x^{2},x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism since it is represented by the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=T^{2}$
\end_inset

 and since it lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in Y$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)^{2}-x^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $g\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)=g(y_{1},y_{2})=y_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a morphism since it is represented by the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g=T_{2}'$
\end_inset

 and since it clearly lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, observe that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(f\circ g)(y) & =f(g(y))\\
 & =f(y_{2})\\
 & =(y_{2}^{2},y_{2})\\
 & =(y_{1},y_{2})\\
 & =y\\
 & =1_{Y}(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 to get from the third line to the fourth line.
 Similarly, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(g\circ f)(x) & =g(f(x))\\
 & =g(x^{2},x)\\
 & =x\\
 & =1_{X}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of affine algebraic sets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(T_{2}-T_{1}^{2},T_{3}-T_{1}^{3})=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},p_{2})$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2})=\mathrm{V}(q)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=(x_{1}x_{2},x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3})=(y_{1},y_{2})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is represented by the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=T_{1}T_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=T_{1}^{2}T_{2}^{2}+T_{3}$
\end_inset

, thus to see if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism, we only need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we must check that the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q=T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2}$
\end_inset

 vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},y_{2})$
\end_inset

: we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
q(y) & =y_{2}-y_{1}-y_{1}^{2}\\
 & =x_{1}^{2}x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}-(x_{1}x_{2})^{2}\\
 & =x_{3}-x_{1}x_{2}\\
 & =x_{3}-x_{1}^{3}\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}(x)=0=p_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 to get from the third line to the fifth line.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is in fact a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 Note that the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}\colon K[T_{1}',T_{2}']/\langle T_{2}'-T_{1}'-T_{1}'^{2}\rangle\to K[T_{1},T_{2},T_{3}]/\langle T_{2}-T_{1}^{2},T_{3}-T_{1}^{3}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{*}(T_{1}') & =T_{1}T_{2}\\
f^{*}(T_{2}') & =T_{1}^{2}T_{2}^{2}+T_{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)\to V(T_{2}^{2}-T_{1}^{2}(T_{1}+1))$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto(x^{2}-1,x(x^{2}-1))$
\end_inset

, is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(K)\neq2$
\end_inset

, it is not bijective: 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 are both mapped to the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(K)=2$
\end_inset

, it is bijective but not an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(1-T_{1}T_{2})$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x_{1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=\mathbb{A}^{1}(K)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is not an algebraic set.
 This shows that the image of an algebraic set is not necessarily an algebraic
 set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=x^{2}+4x+1$
\end_inset

.
 By completing the square, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =x^{2}+4x+1\\
 & =\left(x+2\right)^{2}-3\\
 & =\widetilde{x}^{2}-3\\
 & =\widetilde{f},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=x+2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}=\widetilde{x}^{2}-3$
\end_inset

.
 Now set 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{V}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\{-2-\sqrt{3},-2+\sqrt{3}\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{V}=\{-\sqrt{3},\sqrt{3}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to\widetilde{V}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto x+2:=\widetilde{x}$
\end_inset

 and similarly a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{V}\to V$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}\mapsto\widetilde{x}-2:=x$
\end_inset

.
 These maps are inverse to each other, so 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cong\widetilde{V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of an affine algebraic set is still not satisfactory.
 We list three problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Open subsets of affine algebraic sets do not carry the structure of an affine
 algebraic set in a natural way.
 In particular, we cannot glue affine algebraic sets along open subsets
 (although this is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural operation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for geometric objects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intersections of affine algebraic sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 are closed and hence again affine algebraic sets.
 But we cannot distinguish between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(X)\cap\mathrm{V}(Y)\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(Y)\cap\mathrm{V}(X^{2}-Y)\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 although the geometric situation seems to be different.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Affine algebraic sets seem not to help in studying solutions of polynomial
 equations in more general rings than algebraically closed fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Morphisms are continuous with respect to the Zariski topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now want to show that morphisms are continuous with respect to the Zariski
 topology.
 We first need a lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaamy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})\cap\mathrm{V}(q_{1},\dots,q_{s})=\mathrm{V}(p_{1},\dots,p_{r},q_{1},\dots,q_{s}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(q_{1},\dots,q_{s})$
\end_inset

 is another closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(Z)=\mathrm{V}(p_{1}\circ f,\dots,p_{r}\circ f,q_{1}\circ f,\dots,q_{s}\circ f)
\]

\end_inset

is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propxy}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Lift 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\colon\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}|_{X}=f$
\end_inset

 (choosing a lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to choosing a polynomial representation 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

).
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaamy})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Therefore its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}|_{X}=f$
\end_inset

 must be continuous also.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}:\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be the projection to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate map (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(y_{1},\dots,y_{i},\dots,y_{n})=y_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}|_{X}$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 Let us show this directly: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_{1},\dots,z_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

 are distinct points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 (every closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is just a finite set of points).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{i}|_{X}^{-1}(\{z_{1},\dots,z_{n}\})=X\cap\left(\bigcap_{j=1}^{n}V(\pi_{i}-z_{j})\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus the inverse image a closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maps which are continuous with respect to the Zariski topology are not necessari
ly morphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A continuous map with respect to the Zariski topology does not have to be
 a morphism.
 Indeed, consider the complex conjugation map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}:\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 This map is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 To see why, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 is the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\overline{p}_{1},\dots,\overline{p}_{r})$
\end_inset

, where if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}a_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

 , then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{p}_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}\overline{a}_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 does not have a polynomial representation: the only root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\cdot}\neq T^{m}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 galois extension with galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{Gal}(L/K)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot:\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto g\cdot x$
\end_inset

, is Zariski continuous because the inverse image of a closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(p_{1},\dots,p_{r})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(L)$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 is the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(g\cdot p_{1},\dots,g\cdot p_{r})$
\end_inset

, where if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}a_{n_{j}}z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

 , then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot p_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{i}}(g\cdot a_{n_{j}})z^{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 does not have a polynomial representation: the only root of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot\neq T^{m}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(g\cdot):L[T]\to L[T]$
\end_inset

 (and not an 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

One may wonder why we restrict our morphisms between affine algebraic sets
 in the first place.
 Why do we not consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Hom}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all Zariski-continuous maps? The point is that the category
 of affine algebraic sets are naturally thought of as being objects in the
 category of locally ringed spaces (we will define what these are later
 on) rather than just in the category of topological spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Affine Algebraic Sets as Reduced Finitely-Generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-Algebras
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We make the following definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
affine coordinate ring 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, is the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X):=K[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\mathrm{I}(X).
\]

\end_inset

Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(K))$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra in the natural way, where addition and multiplication are defined
 pointwise, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)\cong\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(K))$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(K))$
\end_inset

 is an equivalent description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 which we shall often use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 to be the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{m}_{X,\boldsymbol{x}}=\{f\in\Gamma(X)\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Often we simplify our notation (when context is clear) and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{X,\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{X}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 to be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}_{X}(\mathfrak{a})=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in X\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }f\in\mathfrak{a}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{\widetilde{a}}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[\boldsymbol{T}]$
\end_inset

 which lifts the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the surjective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon K[\boldsymbol{T}]\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{X}(\mathfrak{a})=X\cap\mathrm{V}(\widetilde{\mathfrak{a}})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{X}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 ranges) are the closed sets in the subspace topology 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 We again call this subspace topology the 
\series bold
Zariski topology 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Often it is clear from context that we are working in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, so we will often simplify our notation and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{X}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{X}(f)$
\end_inset

 to be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}_{X}(f)=\{\boldsymbol{x}\in X\mid f(\boldsymbol{x})\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

These are principal open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, which we call the 
\series bold
principal open subsets 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Again we often simplify our notation by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{X}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set.
 The open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, form a basis of the topology (i.e.
 finite intersections of principal open subsets are again principal open
 subsets and for every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{i}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)\cap D(g)=D(fg)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show that every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a union of principal open subsets.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=X\backslash V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 For generators 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 of this ideal we find 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=\bigcap_{i=1}^{n}V(f_{i})$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}D(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is a basic open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(D(g))=D(f^{*}g)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set.
 The affine coordinate ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is a reduced finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-alebra.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/I(X)$
\end_inset

, it is a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)=\sqrt{I(X)}$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism between affine algebraic sets.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\subset Y$
\end_inset

 is a closed subvariety and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to f(X)$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}h=f^{*}g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f(x))=g(f(x)).$
\end_inset

 Or in other words, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(h-g)(y)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h-g$
\end_inset

 is continuous, we must therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $(h-g)(y)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=g$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is not dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $Z:=\overline{f(X)}$
\end_inset

 and pick 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset Y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)\supset I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I(Z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is injective, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}g=f^{*}0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
dominant 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalence of Categories Between Affine Algebraic Sets and Reduced Finitely
 Generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Algebras
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(f):\text{Hom}(Y,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))\to\text{Hom}(X,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)),
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto f^{*}g:=g\circ f$
\end_inset

, defines a homomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras.
 We obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma:\text{(affine algebraic sets)}^{\text{opp}}\to\text{(reduced finitely generated }k\text{-algebras)}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.33}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 induces an equivalence of categories.
 By restriction one obtains an equivalence of categories 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma:\text{(irreducible affine algebraic sets)}^{\text{opp}}\to\text{(integral finitely generated }k\text{-algebras)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A functor induces an equivalence of categories if and only if it is fully
 faithful and essentially surjective.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is fully faithful, i.e.
 that for affine algebraic sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma:\text{Hom}(X,Y)\to\text{Hom}(\Gamma(Y),\Gamma(X))$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 We define an inverse map.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is given, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 that makes the following diagram commutative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} k[T_1 '
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
dots 
\backslash
text{,} T_m '] 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
varphi } "] 
\backslash
arrow[d] & k[T_1 
\backslash
text{,} 
\backslash
dots 
\backslash
text{,} T_n ] 
\backslash
arrow[d] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
Gamma (Y) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
varphi "] & 
\backslash
Gamma (X)  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

We define 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x):=(\widetilde{\varphi}(T_{1}')(x),\dots,\widetilde{\varphi}(T_{n}')(x))
\]

\end_inset

and obtain the desired inverse homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that the functor is essentially surjective, i.e.
 that for every reduced finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 there exists an affine algebraic set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cong\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(\mathfrak{a})\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/I(V(\mathfrak{a}))=k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]/\mathfrak{a}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{m}(K)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 whose components are 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Write the affine coordinate rings of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)=K[T_{1},\dots,T_{m}]/I(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)=K[T_{1}',\dots,T_{n}']/I(Y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)(T_{i}):=T_{i}\circ f=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Gamma(f)(T_{i})(x) & =T_{i}(f(x))\\
 & =T_{i}(f_{1}(x),\dots,f_{i}(x),\dots,f_{n}(x))\\
 & =f_{i}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the bijective correspondence between points of affine algebraic sets
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, we also have the following description of morphisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine algebraic sets and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f):\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding homomorphism of the affine coordinate rings.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(f)^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}_{x})=\mathfrak{m}_{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $g(f(x))=\Gamma(f)(g)(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)=\text{Hom}(Y,\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Affine Algebraic Sets as Spaces with Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now define the notion of a 
\series bold
space with functions
\series default
.
 For us this will be the prototype of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

geometric object
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is a special case of a so-called ringed space on which the notion of
 a scheme will be based on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
space with functions over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a family 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-subalgebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\text{Map}(U,K)$
\end_inset

 for every open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are open and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

, then the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U'}\in\text{Map}(U',K)$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=f_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})\to(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of spaces with functions is a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 such that for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{*}f:=f\circ g|_{g^{-1}(V)}:g^{-1}(V)\to K$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(g^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly spaces with functions over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 form a category.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a space with functions and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 with functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Space with Functions of an Irreducible Affine Algebraic Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 It is endowed with the Zariski topology and we want to define for every
 open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is a domain, and by definition all the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subalgebras of its field of fractions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field of fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X):=\text{Frac}(\Gamma(X))$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
function field 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 as the set of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

, elements of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

, usually do not define functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 because the denominator may have zeros on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, but certainly 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 defines a function 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It might be even defined on a bigger open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as there exist representations of the fraction with different denominators.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will use functions of this kind to make 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into a space with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.38}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 be elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists a non-empty open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq D(g_{1}g_{2})$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}(x)}{g_{1}(x)}=\frac{f_{2}(x)}{g_{2}(x)}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Then the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 lies in the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})=X$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 lies in the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1})=X$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 the maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 the localization of the affine coordinate ring with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\bigcap_{x\in U}\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}\subset K(X).
\]

\end_inset

The localization 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 can be described in this situation as the union 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}=\bigcup_{f\in\Gamma(X)\backslash\mathfrak{m}_{x}}\Gamma(X)_{f}\subset K(X).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in\Gamma(X)\text{ and }g(x)\neq0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It may be tempting to think that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in\Gamma(X)\text{ and }g(x)\neq0\text{ for all }x\in U\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

but this is not necessarily the case.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{4}$
\end_inset

 be the variety defined by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}T_{4}=T_{2}T_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}/T_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(T_{2}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}/T_{4}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(T_{4}))$
\end_inset

 and by the equation of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, these two functions coincide where they are both defined; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{T_{1}}{T_{2}}\Big|_{\mathrm{D}(T_{2}T_{4})}=\frac{T_{3}}{T_{4}}\Big|_{\mathrm{D}(T_{2}T_{4})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So this gives rise to a regular function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(T_{2})\cup\mathrm{D}(T_{4})$
\end_inset

, but there is no representation of this function as a quotient of two polynomia
ls in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T_{1},T_{2},T_{3},T_{4}]$
\end_inset

 that works on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(T_{2})\cup\mathrm{D}(T_{4})$
\end_inset

; we have to use different representations at different points.
 On the other hand, it is true that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in K[\boldsymbol{T}]\text{ and }g(\boldsymbol{x})\neq0\text{ for all }\boldsymbol{x}\in U\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{D(g_{1})}=\frac{f_{1}}{g_{1}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 share no common factors.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not a constant, then there exists another point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(y)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X,y}$
\end_inset

, we must be able to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{D(g_{2})}=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(y)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}|{}_{D(g_{1}g_{2})}=f=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}}|{}_{D(g_{1}g_{2})}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 But the only way we can have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 is if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=hf_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}=hf_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in k[T_{1},T_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is related to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle g_{1},g_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 has depth 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(y)=h(y)f_{2}(y)=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To consider 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 as a space with functions, we first have to explain how to identify elements
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to k$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, the element 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is by definition in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}$
\end_inset

 and we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g/h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and we may set 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x):=g(x)/h(x)\in k$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is well defined and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.38})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies that this construction defines an injective map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\to\text{Map}(U,k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are open subsets we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

 by definition and this inclusion corresponds via the identification with
 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $U\to k$
\end_inset

 resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to k$
\end_inset

 to the restriction of functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions, we still have to show that we may glue functions
 together.
 But this follows immediately from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 as subsets of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
space of functions associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Functions on principal open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 can be explicitely described as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.40}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be the space with functions associated to the irreducible affine algebraic
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is an equality 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}
\]

\end_inset

(as subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

).
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)=\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 (taking 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}\subset\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

.
 If we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}g=h$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h/f^{n}$
\end_inset

 would show that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we will work with ideals, because our argument will use Nullstellen
satz which is a theorem about ideals.
 So set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{a}=\{q\in\Gamma(X)\mid qg\in\Gamma(X)\}.
\]

\end_inset

Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 and we have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\text{rad}\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 By Hilbert's Nullstellensatz we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{rad}\mathfrak{a}=I(V(\mathfrak{a}))$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it suffices to show 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(f)$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}\notin\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g_{1}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and as 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin V(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Note that we needed to use Nullstellensatz here.
 In fact, the statement is false if the ground field is not algebraically
 closed, as you can see from the example of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{x^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 that is regular on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, but not polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The proposition shows that we could have defined 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 also in another way, namely by setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}\text{ for }f\in\Gamma(X).
\]

\end_inset

As the 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology, the axiom of gluing implies that at most
 one such space with functions can exist.
 It would remain to show the existence of such a space (i.e.
 that for 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)=D(g)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}=\Gamma(X)_{g}$
\end_inset

 and that gluing of functions is possible).
 This is more or less the same as the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.40})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The way we chose is more comfortable in our situation.
 For affine schemes we will use the other approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an integral finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra we may construct the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponding irreducible affine algebraic set directly without choosing
 generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as the set of maximal ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\mathfrak{a})=\{\mathfrak{m}\subset A\text{ maximal}\mid\mathfrak{m}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 For an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 we finally define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{m}\in U}A_{\mathfrak{m}}\subset\text{Frac}(A).
\]

\end_inset

This defines a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 which coincides the space with functions of the irreducible affine algebraic
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 corresponding in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This approach is the point of departure for the definition of schemes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Functor from the Category of Irreducible Affine Algebraic Sets to the
 Category of Spaces with Functions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 be irreducible affine algebraic sets and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 a map.
 The following assertions are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of spaces with functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous and if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{O}_{Y}(U)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The equivalence of (1) and (2) has already been proved in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.33})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, it is clear that (2) is implied by (3) by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $U=Y$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that (2) implies (3).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 be the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h\mapsto h\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(D(g)) & =\{x\in X\mid f(x)\in D(g)\}\\
 & =\{x\in X\mid g(f(x))\neq0\}\\
 & =D(f^{*}(g)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As the principal open subsets form a basis of the topology, this shows that
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 The homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism of the localizations 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)_{g}\to\Gamma(X)_{f^{*}(g)}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 this is the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}(D(g))\to\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(f^{*}(g))),$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\mapsto h\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 This shows the claim if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is principal open.
 As we can obtain functions on arbitrary open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by gluing functions on principal open subsets, this proves (3).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Altogether we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The above construction 
\begin_inset Formula $X\mapsto(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 defines a fully faithful functor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{(Irreducible affine algebraic sets)}\mapsto\text{(Spaces with functions over }k\text{)}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that we can embed the category of irreducible affine algebraic
 sets into the category of spaces with functions.
 Of course we do not obtain all spaces with functions in this way.
 We will now define prevarieties as those connected spaces with functions
 that can be glued together from finitely many spaces with functions attached
 to irreducible affine algebraic sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
connected
\series default
, if the underlying topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An 
\series bold
affine variety 
\series default
is a space with functions that is isomorphic to a space with functions associate
d to an irreducible affine algebraic set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
prevariety 
\series default
is a connected space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 with the property that there exists a finite covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{X\mid U_{i}})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
morphism
\series default
 of prevarieties is a morphism of spaces with functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following categories are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The opposed category of finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras without zero divisors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The category of irreducible affine algebraic sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The category of affine varieties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define an 
\series bold
open affine covering of a prevariety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be a family of open subspaces with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 that are affine varieties such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i}U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety.
 The topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian (in particular quasi-compact) and irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first assertion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a finite covering of Noetherian spaces, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 The second assertion follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected and has a finite covering of irreducible spaces, which implies
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Open Subprevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now able to endow open subsets of affine varieties, and more general
 of prevarieties with the structure of a prevariety.
 Note that in general open subprevarieties of affine varieties are not affine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

.
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding principal open subset.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

 be the localization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 be the affine variety corresponding to this integral finitely generated
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),\mathcal{O}_{X\mid D(f)})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic spaces with functions.
 In particular,  
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),\mathcal{O}_{X\mid D(f)})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.40})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))=\Gamma(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 As two affine varieties are isomorphic if and only if their coordinate
 rings are isomorphic, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{D}(f),\mathcal{O}_{X}|_{\mathrm{D}(f)})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=I(X)\subseteq k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding radical ideal.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 as a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 and denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}'\subseteq k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $fT_{n+1}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the affine coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)=\Gamma(X)_{f}\cong k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n},T_{n+1}]/\mathfrak{a}'$
\end_inset

, and we can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a}')\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 to the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 coordinates induces a bijective map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j:Y=\{(x,x_{n+1})\in X\times\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\mid x_{n+1}f(x)=1\}\to D(f)=\{x\in X\mid f(x)\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of spaces with functions.
 As a restriction of a continuous map, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 It is also open, because for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{g}{f^{N}}\in\Gamma(Y)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j\left(D\left(\frac{g}{f^{N}}\right)\right)=j(D(gf))=D(gf).
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(fg))\to\Gamma(Y)_{g}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $s\mapsto s\circ j$
\end_inset

, is an isomorphism.
 But we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(fg))=\Gamma(X)_{fg}=\Gamma(Y)_{g}
\]

\end_inset

and this identification corresponds to the composition with 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\mathcal{O}_{X\mid U})$
\end_inset

 is prevariety and the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $U\hookrightarrow X$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is connected.
 The previous lemma shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be covered by open affine subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Thus a finite covering suffices.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Function Field of a Prevariety
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are non-empty open affine subvarieties, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and non-empty.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V)\subseteq K(U)
\]

\end_inset

by the definition of functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Frac}(\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V))=K(U)$
\end_inset

.
 The same argument for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U)=K(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the function field of a non-empty open affine subvariety 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and we denote it by 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
function field 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine varieties.
 As the corresponding homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(Y)\to\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

 between the affine coordinate rings is not injective in general, it does
 not induce a homomorphism of function fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K(Y)\to K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 is not functorial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties whose image contains a non-empty open (and
 hence dense) subset, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(Y)\to K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Such morphisms will be called 
\series bold
dominant
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.54}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 a non-empty open subset.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subalgebra of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 is another open subset, the restriction map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)\to\mathcal{O}(U')$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion of subalgebras of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary open subsets, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cup V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\cap\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Then its vanishing set 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(0)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 is closed because 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Therefore if the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 is zero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is zero because 
\begin_inset Formula $U'$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that restriction maps are injective.
 The axiom of gluing implies therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cup V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\cap\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

 for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Closed Subprevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 We want to define on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 the structure of a prevariety.
 For this we have to define functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 We define: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{Z}'(U)=\{f\in\text{Map}(U,k)\mid\text{for all }x\in U\text{, there exists }V\subseteq U\text{ open and }g\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)\text{ such that }f\mid_{U\cap V}=g\mid_{U\cap V}\}.
\]

\end_inset

The definition shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}'=\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Once we have shown the following lemma, we will always write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 (instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'$
\end_inset

 is the sheafification of the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X\mid Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.55}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible affine algebraic set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 Then the space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})$
\end_inset

 associated to the affine algebraic set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and the above defined space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z}')$
\end_inset

 coincide.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In both case 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is endowed with the topology induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to X$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of affine algebraic sets it induces a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})\to(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}'(U)\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{Z}(U)$
\end_inset

 for all open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{Z}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\Gamma(Z)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in D(h)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 .
 The restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{D(h)}\in\mathcal{O}_{Z}(D(h))=\Gamma(Z)_{h}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g/h^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\Gamma(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 We lift 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in\Gamma(X)$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $V:=D(\widetilde{h})\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}^{n}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(D(\widetilde{h}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{U\cap V}=\frac{\widetilde{g}}{\widetilde{h}^{n}}\mid_{U\cap V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a corollary of the lemme we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.56}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a prevariety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible closed subset.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 be the system of functions defined above.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})$
\end_inset

 is a prevariety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The most general way to construct prevarieties is to take some affine varieties
 and patch them together: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be prevarieties, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(U_{1},\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}\mid_{U_{1}})\to(U_{2},\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}\mid_{U_{2}})$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism.
 Then we can define a prevariety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 via the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a set, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\cup X_{2}$
\end_inset

 modulo the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim f(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a topological space, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the so-called 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 induced by the above equivalence relation, i.e.
 we say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{1}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap X_{2}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a ringed space, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{(s_{1},s_{2})\mid s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }s_{1}=s_{2}\text{ on the overlap (i.e. }f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U\cap U_{2}})=s_{1}\mid_{U\cap U_{1}})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $t\mapsto\frac{1}{t}:=t'$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)\cong k$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(X\cap X_{1})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(X\cap X_{2})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}=b_{m}T'^{m}+b_{m-1}T'^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U_{2}})=b_{m}T{}^{-m}+b_{m-1}T{}^{1-m}+\cdots+b_{0}\mid_{U_{1}}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}\mid_{U_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

The only way this happens is if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=b_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})=(a_{0},a_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)\cong k[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2})\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{1}}(X\cap X_{1})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}\in\mathcal{O}_{X_{2}}(X\cap X_{2})=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)}(\mathbb{A}^{1}(k))$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}=b_{m}T'^{m}+b_{m-1}T'^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}(s_{2}\mid_{U_{2}})=b_{m}T{}^{m}+b_{m-1}T{}^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}\mid_{U_{1}}=a_{n}T^{n}+a_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}\mid_{U_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

The only way this happens is if 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=b_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{4}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{4}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Projective Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By far the most important example of prevarieties are projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 and subvarieties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

, called (quasi-)projective varieties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homogeneous Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To describe the functions on projective space we start with some remarks
 on homogeneous polynomials.
 Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 To clean our notation in what follows, we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 to denote 
\begin_inset Formula $R[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 A monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=X_{0}^{\alpha_{0}}\cdots X_{n}^{\alpha_{n}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We also denote 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\cdots,1)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\cdots X_{n}=\boldsymbol{X}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 A point in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 We will frequently use this notation whenever context is clear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
homogeneous 
\series default
of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the sum of monomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain with infinitely many elements and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(\lambda\boldsymbol{x})=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})\label{eq:homogeneous}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One direction is obvious, so we will only prove the other direction.
 We will prove the other direction by induction on the number of terms of
 a polynomial.
 For the base case, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a monomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f=c\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homogeneous})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous, but we still need to show that it has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many elements and since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathrm{D}(\boldsymbol{X}^{1})\cap\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 By clearing the denominators of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{a})=f(\lambda\boldsymbol{a})=\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\neq0$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{d}=\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $r=d-|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{r}-1$
\end_inset

 has infinitely many solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (in fact every nonzero element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a solution).
 This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{r}-1$
\end_inset

 can have at most 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=d$
\end_inset

; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For the induction step, assume that we have proven the statement for all
 polynomials with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 terms, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial with 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 terms such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:homogeneous})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=c\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}+g,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\nmid g$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in K^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be a point such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{a})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that such a point exists since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(g)\cap\mathrm{V}(\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, otherwise we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(g)\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\mid g$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 By clearing the denominators if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{a})=f(\lambda\boldsymbol{a})=\lambda^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\boldsymbol{a}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset

Arguing as before, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|=d$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(\lambda\boldsymbol{x}) & =f(\lambda\boldsymbol{x})-c(\lambda\boldsymbol{X})^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\lambda^{|\boldsymbol{\alpha}|}\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\lambda^{d}\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\\
 & =\lambda^{d}(f(\boldsymbol{x})-c\boldsymbol{x}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}})\\
 & =\lambda^{d}g(\boldsymbol{x}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus by induction, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must be homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dehomogenization and Homgenization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify notation in what follows, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}=X_{0},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}_{i}=X_{i,0},\dots,\widehat{X}_{i,i},\dots,X_{i,n}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, we think of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j,i}$
\end_inset

 as being the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}/X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq0$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}\colon R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}\to R[\boldsymbol{X}_{i}]_{\leq d}$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
dehomogenization
\series default
, by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}(f)(\boldsymbol{X}_{i})=\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}(f(\boldsymbol{X}))=f(X_{i,0},\dots,X_{i,i-1},1,X_{i,i+1},\dots,X_{i,n})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Esentially 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 takes a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

, divides it by 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

, and then makes the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j,i}=X_{i}/X_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}^{3}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2} & \mapsto\frac{X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}^{3}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2}}{X_{1}^{3}}\\
 & \mapsto\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{1}}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{X_{2}}{X_{1}}\right)+1+\left(\frac{X_{2}}{X_{1}}\right)^{2}\\
 & \mapsto X_{0,1}^{2}X_{2,1}+1+X_{2,1}^{2}\\
 & =\mathrm{D}_{1}^{3}(X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}^{3}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}\colon R[\boldsymbol{X}_{i}]_{\leq d}\to R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

, called 
\series bold
homogenization
\series default
, by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}(g)(\boldsymbol{X})=\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}(g(\boldsymbol{X}_{i}))=\sum_{k=0}^{d}X_{i}^{d-k}g_{k}(X_{0},\dots,\widehat{X}_{i},\dots,X_{n})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in R[\boldsymbol{X}_{i}]_{\leq d}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the homogoneous component of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Esentially 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 takes a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{X}_{i})$
\end_inset

, multiplies it homogeneous component in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{d-k}$
\end_inset

, and then makes the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j,i}=X_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X_{0,1}^{2}X_{2,1}+X_{2,1}^{2}+1 & \mapsto X_{0,1}^{2}X_{2,1}+X_{1}X_{2,1}^{2}+X_{1}^{3}\\
 & \mapsto X_{0}^{2}X_{2}+X_{1}X_{2}^{2}+X_{1}^{3}\\
 & =\mathrm{H}_{1}^{3}(X_{0,1}^{2}X_{2,1}+X_{2,1}^{2}+1)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear isomorphism with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 being its inverse.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear (it is just an evaluation map).
 Furthermore we have, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}(\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}(f))(\boldsymbol{X}) & =\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}(\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}(f)(\boldsymbol{X}_{i}))\\
 & =\mathrm{H}_{i}^{d}(f(X_{i,0},\dots,X_{i,i-1},1,X_{i,i+1},\dots,X_{i,n}))\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{d}X_{i}^{d-k}f_{k}(X_{0},\dots,\widehat{X}_{i},\dots,X_{n})\\
 & =f(\boldsymbol{X}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in R[\boldsymbol{X}]_{e}$
\end_inset

, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $fg$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d+e$
\end_inset

 and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d}(f)\mathrm{D}_{i}^{e}(g)=\mathrm{D}_{i}^{d+e}(fg).\label{eq:dehomoggraded}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K$
\end_inset

 is a field, we will extend homogenization and dehomogenization to fields
 of fractions as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

 that consists of those elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous polynomials of the same degree.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomoggraded})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have a well defined isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-extensions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{D}_{i}:\mathcal{F}\to K(\boldsymbol{X}_{i}),\label{eq:dehomogiso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\mapsto\mathrm{D}_{i}(f)/\mathrm{D}_{i}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{D}_{1}\left(\frac{X_{1}^{3}}{X_{2}^{3}+X_{1}X_{0}^{2}}\right) & =\frac{\mathrm{D}_{1}(X_{1}^{3})}{\mathrm{D}_{1}(X_{2}^{3}+X_{1}X_{0}^{2})}\\
 & =\frac{1}{X_{2,1}^{3}+X_{0,1}^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Often, we will identify 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X}_{i})$
\end_inset

 with the subring 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X}/X_{i})=K\left(X_{0}/X_{i},\dots,X_{n}/X_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\boldsymbol{X})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of the Projective Space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 is an extremely important prevariety within algebraic geometry.
 Many prevarieties of interest are subprevarieties of the projective space.
 Moreover, the projective space is the correct environment for projective
 geometry which remedies the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

defect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of affine geometry of missing points at infinity.
 As a set, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}^{n}(K):=\{\text{lines through the origin in }K^{n+1}\}=(K^{n+1}\backslash\{0\})\slash K^{\times}.
\]

\end_inset

Here a line through the origin is per definition a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-subspace and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(K^{n+1}\backslash\{0\})\slash K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 the set of equivalence classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n+1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the equivalence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})\sim(x_{0}',\dots,x_{n}')\text{ if and only if there exists }\lambda\in K^{\times}\text{ such that }x_{i}=\lambda x_{i}'\text{ for all }0\leq i\leq n.
\]

\end_inset

The equivalence class of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{0},\dots,x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]=[x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 We call the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
homogeneous coordinates 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i}:=\{[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)\mid x_{i}\neq0\}
\]

\end_inset

This subset is well-defined and the union of the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 we have a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}\colon U_{i}\to\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 which is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{i}([\boldsymbol{x}])=\varphi_{i}([x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n}])=\left(\frac{x_{0}}{x_{i}},\cdots\frac{\widehat{x}_{i}}{x_{i}},\cdots,\frac{x_{n}}{x_{i}}\right)=\widehat{\boldsymbol{x}}_{i}/x_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]\in U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 F Using this bijection, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a space with functions, isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{A}^{n}(K),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{A}^{n}(K)}),$
\end_inset

 which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}})$
\end_inset

.
 We want to define on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the structure of a space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 becomes an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}}=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}U_{i}=\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, there's at most one way to do this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We define the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 by calling a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 open if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This defines a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 as for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cap U_{j}=\mathrm{D}(T_{j})\subseteq U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open (we use here on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 With this definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in\{0,\dots,n\}}$
\end_inset

 becomes an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We still have to define functions on open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 For this, we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)=\{f\in\text{Map}(U,k)\mid f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})\text{ for all }i=0,\dots,n\}.
\]

\end_inset

It is clear that this defines the structure of a space with functions on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

, although we still have to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}}=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the following description of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-algebras 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)$
\end_inset

 using the inverse isomorphism of the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $k(T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k(X_{0},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.59}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(K)$
\end_inset

 be open.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)=\{f:U\to k & \mid\forall x\in U,\text{ }\exists x\in V\subseteq U\text{ open and }g,h\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]\\
 & \text{ homogeneous of same degree such that }h(v)\neq0\text{ and }f(v)=g(v)/h(v)\text{ }\text{for all }v\in V\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has locally the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in k[T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the inverse of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields the desired form of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be an element of the right hand side.
 We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus locally on 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g/h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]_{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Once more applying the isomorphism 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has locally the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g}/\widetilde{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{g},\widetilde{h}\in k[T_{0},\dots,\widehat{T}_{i},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 This shows 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U\cap U_{i}}\in\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(U\cap U_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f|_{U\cap U_{1}}=\frac{T_{2}^{2}+1}{T_{0}+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Then the inverse of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dehomogiso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{X_{2}^{2}+X_{1}^{2}}{X_{0}^{2}+X_{1}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 The bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}|_{U_{i}})\cong\mathbb{A}^{n}(k).
\]

\end_inset

of spaces with functions.
 The space with functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)})$
\end_inset

 is a prevariety.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first assertion follows from the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.59})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a space with functions that has a finite open covering by affine varieties.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible since it is connected and is covered by finitely many irreducibl
e open subsets.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is by its very definition the function field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U_{i})=k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, we usually describe 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

 as the field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=\{f/g\mid f,g\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]\text{ homogeneous of the same degree}\}.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i,j\leq n$
\end_inset

 the identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(U_{i})\cong K(U_{j})$
\end_inset

 is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{j}\circ\Phi_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be described explicitely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(U_{i})=k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right)\mapsto k\left(\frac{X_{0}}{X_{j}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{j}}\right)=K(U_{j}),\qquad\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{i}}\mapsto\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{i}}\frac{X_{i}}{X_{j}}=\frac{X_{\ell}}{X_{j}}.
\]

\end_inset

We use these explicit descriptions to prove the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop1.61}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The only global functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 are the constant functions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=k$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is not an affine variety for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop1.54})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))=\bigcap_{0\leq i\leq n}\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(U_{i})=\bigcap_{0\leq i\leq n}k\left[\frac{X_{0}}{X_{i}},\dots,\frac{X_{n}}{X_{i}}\right]=k,
\]

\end_inset

where the intersection is taken in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 The last assertion follows because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 were affine, its set of points would be in bijection to the set of maximal
 ideals in the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)}(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k))$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 consists of only one point, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gluing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 to Make 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now want to describe how we can glue 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 to make 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 in explicit detail.
 First we start with the rings 
\begin_inset Formula $k[S]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the homogeneous coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $T:=\frac{X_{1}}{X_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S:=\frac{X_{0}}{X_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Projective Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A prevariety is called a 
\series bold
projective variety 
\series default
if it is isomorphic to a closed subprevariety of a projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

As in the affine case, we speak of projective varieties rather than prevarieties.
 Similarly, we will talk about subvarieties of projective space, instead
 of subprevarieties.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in k[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $f([\boldsymbol{x}])$
\end_inset

 obviously depends on the choice of the representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\boldsymbol{x}]$
\end_inset

 and we cannot consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous, at least the question whether the value is zero or nonzero
 is independent of the choice of a representative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}=f_{1},\dots,f_{m}$
\end_inset

 be a finite collection of homogeneous polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[\boldsymbol{X}]$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}_{+}(\boldsymbol{f})=\{[\boldsymbol{x}]\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\mid f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\text{ for all }i=1,\dots,m\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})=\{(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n})\in\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\mid f_{i}(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n})=0\text{ for all }i=1,\dots,m\}.
\]

\end_inset

Subsets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

 are closed.
 More precisely we have 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})\cap U_{i}=V(\Phi_{i}(f_{1}),\dots,\Phi_{i}(f_{m})),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes as usual dehomogenization with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We will see that all closed subsets of the projective space are of this
 form.
 To do this we consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\backslash\{0\}\to\mathbb{P}^{n}(k),\qquad(x_{0},\cdots,x_{n})\mapsto(x_{0}:\cdots:x_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

As for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 its restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{f^{-1}(U_{i})}:f^{-1}(U_{i})\to U_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism of prevarieties, this holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(Z)$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $C(Z)$
\end_inset

 its closure in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 Affine algebraic sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
affine cones 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda x\in X$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in k^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C(Z)$
\end_inset

 is an affine cone in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 It is called the 
\series bold
affine cone of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n+1}(k)$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\neq\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following assertions are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an affine cone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is generated by homogeneous polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists a closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=C(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $I(X)$
\end_inset

 is generated by homogeneous polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\in k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n}]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=V_{+}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Segre Embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{0},\dots,Y_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to find an easy description of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)=\mathbb{P}^{(n+1)(m+1)-1}$
\end_inset

 be projective space with homogeneous coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 There is an obviously well-defined set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}=x_{i}y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmasegreembedding}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 be the set-theoretic map as above.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The image 
\begin_inset Formula $X=f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 is a projective variety in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

, with ideal generated by the homogeneous polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}Z_{i',j'}-Z_{i,j'}Z_{i',j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i,i'\leq n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j,j'\leq m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)\to X$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 is a projective variety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 are exactly those subsets that can be written as the zero locus of polynomials
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[X_{0},\dots,X_{n},Y_{0},\dots,Y_{m}]$
\end_inset

 that are bihomogeneous in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is obvious that the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 satisfy the given equations.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the given equations.
 At least one of these coordinates must be non-zero; we can assume without
 loss of generality that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us pass to affine coordinates by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}=z_{i,0}z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

; so by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

 we obtain a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 that is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuing the above notation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 be a point with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=z$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 are only determined up to a common scalar.
 But then it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bijective.
 The same calculation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are given (locally in affine coordinates) by polynomial maps; so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It follows by the isomorphism of (2) that any closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the zero locus of homogeneous polynomials in the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 of bihomogeneous polynomials in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 (of the same degree).
 Conversely, a zero locus of bihomogeneous polynomials can always be reweritten
 as a zero locus of bihomogeneous polynomials of the same degree in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 But such a polynomial is obviously a polynomial in the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, so it determines an algebraic set in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cong\mathbb{P}^{n}\times\mathbb{P}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

.
 Then Segre embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{2}(k)\to\mathbb{P}^{5}(k)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left([x_{0}:x_{1}],[y_{0}:y_{1}:y_{2}]\right)\mapsto[x_{0}y_{0}:x_{0}y_{1}:x_{0}y_{2}:x_{1}y_{0}:x_{1}y_{1}:x_{1}y_{2}]:=[z_{00}:z_{01}:z_{02}:z_{10}:z_{11}:z_{12}].
\]

\end_inset

By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmasegreembedding})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the vanishing ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbb{P}^{1}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{2}(k))$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle Z_{00}Z_{11}-Z_{01}Z_{10},Z_{00}Z_{12}-Z_{02}Z_{10},Z_{01}Z_{12}-Z_{02}Z_{11}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

We can view this as the ideal generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 minors of the matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}Z_{00} & Z_{01} & Z_{02}\\
Z_{10} & Z_{11} & Z_{12}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

This is an example of a 
\series bold
determinantal variety
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A Quartic Curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we go over an example of a quartic curve which will
 demonstrate many of the concepts introduced above.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Z}[x,y]\slash\langle f(x,y)\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=(y-x^{2}+5x-5)(y+x^{2}-5x+5)-1\label{eq:antilocal1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that from the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=y-x^{2}+5x-5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=y+x^{2}-5x+5$
\end_inset

 are units in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are describing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a quotient of a polynomial ring, but we can also describe it as a finite
 module extension over a polynomial ring.
 Namely, we can write it as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Z}[y][\sqrt{g(x)}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=y^{2}-(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)=y^{2}-g(x).\label{eq:antilocal2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is nice because we can read off information like the discriminant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[y]$
\end_inset

.
 Basically from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we can read off useful information of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 viewed as a finite module extension, whereas from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we can read off useful information of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 viewed as a quotient.
 Both expressions give rise to the same ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at the end of the day.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 To get an idea of what 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 looks like, we first look at its 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued points: 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})=\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{R}\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A=\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{R}[x,y]\slash f$
\end_inset

.
 We can visualize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in the picture below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = none, xmin=-1,xmax=5,ymin=-10,ymax=10,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick=
\backslash
empty ,ytick=
\backslash
empty ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

legend style={draw=none}]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=-1:1,samples=500,color=black,thick] {((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^(
1/2)}; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=2:3,samples=500,color=black,thick] {((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^(1
/2)};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=4:6,samples=500,color=black,thick] {((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^(1
/2)};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=-1:1,samples=500,color=black,thick] {-((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^
(1/2)}; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=2:3,samples=500,color=black,thick] {-((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^(
1/2)};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=4:6,samples=500,color=black,thick] {-((x-1)*(x-2)*(x-3)*(x-4))^(
1/2)}; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [domain=-1:6,samples=1000,color=red,thick] {x^2 - 5*x + 5};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The thick black curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)$
\end_inset

 whereas the thick red curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 do not intersect: this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and hence a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A$
\end_inset

).
 The point is that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\mathfrak{p}):=u\text{ mod }\mathfrak{p}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{a,b}=\langle x-a,y-b\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 There's also the generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=x^{2}-5x+5$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $u=y-p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=y+p$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not antilocal (if you look at the curves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, you'll see that they just barely miss each other), however we can still
 ask: how far away is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from being antilocal? If we add 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 together, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $u+v=2y$
\end_inset

, which is not a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 since the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(y)$
\end_inset

 intersects the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)$
\end_inset

 at four points (you could also see this by plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 above).
 More generally, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}-p^{2}-1
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
mu+nv=(m+n)y+(n-m)(x^{2}-5x+5).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K[u,v,y]\slash\langle uv-1\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K[u,v,y]\slash\langle uv-1,mu+nv\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n(v-u)=2n(x^{2}-5x+5)=2np$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}u=\mathbb{Z}(y-p)\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbb{Z}v
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}(u+v)=2\mathbb{Z}y\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbb{Z}(v-u)=2\mathbb{Z}p.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If particular, all combinations of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(u+v)+n(v-u)=2my+2np
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\neq0$
\end_inset

 gives us a new unit.
 Indeed, in this case if both 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 vanish, then both 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 vanishes too, and the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 takes value 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 here (as can be seen in the expression 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 For instance, the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2(u+v)+(v-u)=4y+2p=4y+2x^{2}-10x+10
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f & =(y-p)(y+p)-1\\
f & =uv-1\\
p & =x^{2}-5x+5\\
u+v & =2y\\
v-u & =2p\\
y & =\frac{u+v}{2}\\
p & =\frac{v-u}{2}\\
u & =y-p\\
v & =y+p
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}=p^{2}+1
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2u+v=3y-p=3y-x^{2}+5x-5
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
5u+v=6y-4p=6y-4x^{2}+20x-20
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2(y-p)+(y+p)=3y-p
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2(y-p)+y+p=3y
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\frac{m-n}{m+n}(x^{2}-5x+5)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{24}\approx4.89$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2n(x^{2}-5x+5)
\]

\end_inset

is another unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If you graph the zero set of this function, you'll see that it gets closer
 to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

, but it still doesn't quite intersect it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
