\begin_layout Section
Irreducible Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connected Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
connected 
\series default
if it is impossible to write 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a union of two non-empty disjoint open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $X=U\cup V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then one of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is empty.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is not connected, then we say it is 
\series bold
disconnected
\series default
.
 A subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is said to be connected if it is connected in the subspace topology.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=(\mathcal{C},\subseteq)$
\end_inset

 to be the poset whose underlying set is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}=\{C\subseteq X\mid C\text{ is connected}\},
\]

\end_inset

and whose partial order is the inclusion map.
 The maximal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
connected components 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the emptyset 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and singletons 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},C_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two distinct maximal elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, then they are necessarily closed (since if 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is connected, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{C}$
\end_inset

 is connected), and they must be disjoint (since if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\cap C_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\cup C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is connected).
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(C_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, then their union 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}C_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of this chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus Zorn's lemma implies that every connected subset is contained in a
 connected component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is contained in a connected component.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the union of its connected components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 being connected is equivalent to saying that it is impossible to write
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a union of two proper disjoint closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X=U\cup V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are two proper open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which are disjoint from one another, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U=V^{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=U^{c}$
\end_inset

 are also two proper closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which are disjoint from one another.
 If we relax this condition a bit, then we get the concept of irreducible
 spaces: we say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
irreducible 
\series default
if cannot be expressed as the union of two proper closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $X=E\cup F$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the either 
\begin_inset Formula $E=X$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $F=X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
reducible
\series default
.
 A subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is said to be irreducible if it is irreducible in the subspace topology.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}=(\mathcal{D},\subseteq)$
\end_inset

 to be the poset whose underlying set is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}=\{D\subseteq X\mid D\text{ is irreducible}\},
\]

\end_inset

and whose partial order is the inclusion map.
 The maximal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
irreducible components 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the emptyset 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and singletons 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1},D_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two distinct maximal elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, then they are necessarily closed (since if 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{D}$
\end_inset

 is irreducible), and they must be disjoint (since if 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}\cap D_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}\cup D_{2}$
\end_inset

 is irreducible).
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(D_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, then their union 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of this chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus Zorn's lemma implies that every irreducible subset is contained in
 a irreducible component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is contained in an irreducible component.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the union of its irreducible components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\subseteq\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 (every irreducible subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected), however for many spaces this is a strict inclusion.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Hausdorff and contains at least two distinct points, then it is 
\emph on
always 
\emph default
reducible.
 Indeed, pick two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 together with two neighborhoods 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x},U_{y}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\cap U_{y}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X=U_{x}^{c}\cup U_{y}^{c}$
\end_inset

 expresses 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a union of two proper closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Irreducible spaces show up a lot in algebraic geometry (for instance, the
 Zariski topology of an affine algebraic variety is irreducible).
 The open subsets of irreducible property are 
\emph on
very 
\emph default
large in the sense of the following proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is not empty.
 The following assertions are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Any two non-empty open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have a non-empty intersection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty open subset is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty open subset is connected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty open subset is irreducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X=U^{c}\cup V^{c}$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{c}=X$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{c}=X$
\end_inset

 which implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 ro 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}^{c}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is non-empty, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}^{c}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}=X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

4): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is not connected: write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(U_{1}\cap U)\cup(U_{2}\cap U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are open subsets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U$
\end_inset

 are non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which have non-empty intersection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

5): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We show that every non-empty open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (this shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is irreducible).
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is also open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and therefore dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is certainly dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(5
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): Obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map of topological spaces.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible subspace, its image 
\begin_inset Formula $f(Z)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are non-empty open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(Z)$
\end_inset

, their preimages in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 have a non-empty intersection.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.17}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 A subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if its closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if for any two open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap V\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap(U\cap V)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This implies the lemma because an open subset meets 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 if and only if it meets 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, one direction is trivial.
 For the other direction, we prove the contrapositive: 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap Y=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap\overline{Y}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap Y=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash U$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash U$
\end_inset

 must contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap\overline{Y}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is and open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap U$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and hence an irreducible closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 whose closure in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Together with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.17})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, this shows that there are mutually inverse bijective maps
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\{Y\subseteq U\mid Y\text{ is irreducible and closed}\} & \leftrightarrow & \{Z\subseteq X\mid Z\text{ is irreducible and closed with }Z\cap U\neq\emptyset\}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\mapsto\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\mapsto Z\cap U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A maximal irreducible subset of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
irreducible component 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.17})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows that every irreducible component is closed.
 The set of irreducible subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is ordered inductively, as for every chain of irreducible subsets their
 union is again irreducible.
 Thus Zorn's lemma implies that every irreducible subset is contained in
 an irreducible component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is contained in an irreducible component.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the union of its irreducible components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Irreducible Affine Algebraic Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be a closed subset.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=Z_{1}\cup Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1},Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 are closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)=I(Z_{1})\cap I(Z_{2})$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)$
\end_inset

 is prime, we must either have 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)\supset I(Z_{1})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)\supset I(Z_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)\supset I(Z_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Now we apply 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to both sides to get 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subset Z_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $fg\in I(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle fg\rangle\subset I(Z)$
\end_inset

, and after applying 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to both sides, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\langle fg\rangle=V(f)\cup V(g)\supset Z.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, either 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)\supset Z$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $V(g)\supset Z$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, say 
\begin_inset Formula $V(f)\supset Z$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to both sides, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\in I(V(f))\subset I(Z),
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Z)$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that the Nullstellensatz was not used in this proof.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quasi-Compact and Noetherian Topological Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
quasi-compact 
\series default
if every open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcovering.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
Noetherian 
\series default
if every descending chain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 becomes stationary, i.e.
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\lambda}=Z_{\lambda+1}=Z_{\lambda+2}=\cdots$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty set of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a minimal element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty set of open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The equivalence of (2) and (3) is trivial.
 Let us show that (1) is equivalent to (2).
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty family closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Again since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}\supset Z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this way, we obtain a descending chain of closed subsets
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}\supset Z_{2}\supset\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

which does not become stationary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that every non-empty set of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a minimal element.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots\label{eq:chainofdescending}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be a descending chain of closed subsets.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Z_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty family of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and hence must have a minimal element.
 This implies that the chain 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainofdescending})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 becomes stationary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.24}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space that has a finite covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 by Noetherian subspaces.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is itself Noetherian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

be a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we obtain a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{i}\supseteq Z_{1}\cap X_{i}\supseteq Z_{2}\cap X_{i}\supseteq\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, this chain must terminate, say at 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\lambda_{i}}\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\max_{i}(\lambda_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z_{\mu} & =X\cap Z_{\mu}\\
 & =\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}\right)\cap Z_{\mu}\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}\left(X_{i}\cap Z_{\mu}\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}\left(X_{i}\cap Z_{\mu+1}\right)\\
 & =\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}\right)\cap Z_{\mu+1}\\
 & =Z_{\mu+1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.25}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian topological space.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact (in particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 has only finitely many irreducible components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z\supseteq Z\cap Z_{1}\supseteq Z\cap Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

is a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

is a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\mu}=Z_{\mu+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap Z_{\mu}=Z\cap Z_{\mu+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
By (1), it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 be the set of those open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are finite unions of the subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $V=X$
\end_inset

, otherwise there existed an 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is properly contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup U_{i}\in\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcovering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It suffices to show that every Noetherian space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be written as a finite union of irreducible subsets.
 If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that cannot be written as a finite union of irreducible subsets were non-empty,
 there existed a minimal element 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible and thus is the union of two proper closed subsets which
 do not lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This leads to a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be any subspace.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.25})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 But descending chains of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 correspond to ascending chains of radical ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian by Hilbert's basis theorem, this proves the proposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a (non-empty) irreducible topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Chain}(X)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all 
\series bold
chains of irreducible closed subsets 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Chain}(X):=\{\wp=(\emptyset\neq X_{0}\subset X_{1}\subset\cdots\subset X_{n}\subset X)\mid X_{i}\mbox{ is irreducible closed subset of }X\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\wp=(\emptyset\neq X_{0}\subset X_{1}\subset\cdots\subset X_{n}\subset X)\in\text{Chain}(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\series bold
length
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $(\wp):=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
dimension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}(X)=\sup\{\mbox{length}(\wp)\mid\wp\in\text{Chain}(X)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is any Noetherian topological space, then the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the supremum of the dimensions of its irreducible components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
curve 
\series default
and a space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
surface
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(T_{1}T_{3},T_{2}T_{3})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathrm{V}(T_{3})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}=\mathrm{V}(T_{1},T_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the irreducible components of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 One can show that a maximal chain of irreducible closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\wp_{1}=(V(T_{1},T_{2},T_{3})\subset V(T_{1},T_{3})\subset V(T_{3})),
\]

\end_inset

and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X_{1})=2$
\end_inset

.
 Similary one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X_{2})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X)=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 as a topological space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the following basic definition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 The 
\series bold
prime spectrum 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Spec}\,A:=\left\{ \mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\text{ is a prime ideal of }A\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

We will now endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a topological space.
 For every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which contain 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)$
\end_inset

 to be the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)$
\end_inset

 consists of the set of all prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which do not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\mathrm{V}(\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, every set of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)$
\end_inset

) can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 is a radical ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(a)$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(a)$
\end_inset

) instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\{a\})=\mathrm{V}(\langle a\rangle)$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\{a\})=\mathrm{D}(\langle a\rangle)$
\end_inset

) in order to simplify notation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following statements hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(0)=\mathrm{Spec}\,A\text{ and }\mathrm{V}(1)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(0)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(1)=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For two ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})\cap\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every family 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{a}_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 of ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\mathrm{D}\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first statement is trivial.
 For the second statement, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\mathfrak{b}) & \iff\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{ab}\\
 & \iff\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\text{ or }\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{b} & \text{since }\mathfrak{p}\text{ is prime}\\
 & \iff\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab})=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 is inclusion-reversing, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab}) & \supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})\\
 & \supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})\cup\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\\
 & =\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{ab}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For the last statement, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}\left(\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}\right)=\bigcap_{i\in I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{i})
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\sum_{i\in I}\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It follows from the proposition above that the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})\mid\mathfrak{a}\text{ is an ideal of }A\}$
\end_inset

 forms a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, which we call the 
\series bold
Zariski topology
\series default
.
 We view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 as a topological space equipped with this topology (and not just as a mere
 set).
 Later on we will endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 with even more structure by equipping it with a sheaf of rings (defined
 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) and this will give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 the structure of a locally ringed space, but for now let us focus on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 viewed as a topological space.
 The closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and the open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to be a radical ideal).
 Open sets of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(a)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 are given a special name: they are called 
\series bold
principal opens
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following statements hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The principal open sets are quasi-compact.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact if and only if it can be expressed in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(1)=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 be two open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})\cap\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, so there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}$
\end_inset

 is inclusion-preserving, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}(a)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(x)\subseteq\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{D}(y_{i})$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, such that
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x)\supseteq\mathrm{V}\left(\langle y_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}$
\end_inset

 to both sides gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{\langle x\rangle}\subseteq\sqrt{\langle y_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in\langle y_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle$
\end_inset

 which implies there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i_{1}},\dots,y_{i_{k}}\in\{y_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i_{1}},\dots,a_{i_{k}}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{n}=a_{i_{1}}y_{i_{1}}+\cdots+a_{i_{k}}y_{i_{k}}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x)\supseteq\mathrm{V}(y_{i_{1}},\dots,y_{i_{k}})$
\end_inset

 or equivalently that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(x)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(y_{i_{1}})\cup\cdots\cup\mathrm{D}(y_{i_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(x)$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is a finitely generated ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\mathrm{D}(x_{1})\cup\cdots\mathrm{D}(x_{n})$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 ios a finite union of quasi-compact spaces.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}=\langle b_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(b_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{b})=\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{D}(b_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, there exists a finite subcovering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(b_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 which covers 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(b_{i_{1}}),\dots,\mathrm{D}(b_{i_{n}})\}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle b_{i_{1}},\dots,b_{i_{n}}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(b_{i_{1}})\cup\cdots\cup\mathrm{D}(b_{i_{n}})=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is finitely generated.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 be the category whose objects are radical ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms are containment and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 be the category whose objects are closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms are inclusions.
 Then we can interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}\colon\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 as covariant functors.
 It turns out that there is a covariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}\colon\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 which is left adjoint to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

, which we defines as follows: for every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Z):=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Z}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}(Z)=\mathrm{I}(\overline{Z})$
\end_inset

, so it is natural to view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}$
\end_inset

 as a functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}$
\end_inset

 being left adjoint to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}$
\end_inset

 means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}(Z)\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\iff Z\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}\mathrm{I}(Z)=\overline{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a} & =\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,A}\mathfrak{p}\right):\mathfrak{a}\\
 & =\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,A}(\mathfrak{p}:\mathfrak{a})\\
 & =\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})}\mathfrak{p} & \text{since }\mathfrak{p}:\mathfrak{a}=\begin{cases}
\mathfrak{p} & \text{if }\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\\
A & \text{if }\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}
\end{cases}\\
 & =\mathrm{I}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}_{1}=\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}_{1} & =\sqrt{0}:
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{D}\mathrm{I}(Z)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Z}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{p}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2.3}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathrm{I}(Y)}=\mathrm{I}(Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{IV}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Y)=\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})=\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{DI}(Y)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The maps 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{ideals } 
\backslash
mathfrak{a} 
\backslash
text{ of } A 
\backslash
text{ with } 
\backslash
mathfrak{a}=
\backslash
text{rad}(
\backslash
mathfrak{a}) 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[r, " V ", shift left = 1] & 
\backslash
{ 
\backslash
text{closed subsets } Y 
\backslash
text{ of } 
\backslash
text{Spec }A 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[l, " I", shift left=1] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are mutually inverse bijections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

.
 This certainly holds for prime ideals and therefore for arbitrary intersections
 of prime ideals as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 This follows from the fact that the radical of an ideal equals the intersection
 of all prime ideals containing it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\supseteq Y & \iff\mathrm{I}\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}\subseteq\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\mathrm{V}(\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}})\supseteq\mathrm{V}\mathrm{I}(Y)\\
 & \iff\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\supseteq\mathrm{V}\mathrm{I}(Y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VI}(Y)$
\end_inset

 is the smallest closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and assume (to obtain a contradiction) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

, there exists a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\sqrt{0}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}.$
\end_inset

 In particular, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\subseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\supseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belongs to every prime ideal which does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

) and assume (to obtain a contradiction) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\notin\sqrt{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ (ax)^{n}\right\} _{n\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 forms a multiplicative set, and so we can localize at 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ax}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=\iota_{ax}^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{ax}\colon A\to A_{ax}$
\end_inset

 is the canonical ring homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (if it did, then it'd certainly contain 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

).
 This is a contradiction.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}:\mathfrak{a}\supseteq\mathrm{ID}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{DI}(Y) & =\mathrm{D}\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathfrak{p}\right)\\
 & =\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Y}\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{p})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 This follows from part 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle x^{2},y^{2}\rangle,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}=\langle x^{2},xy,y^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subset\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 (where the inclusion is strict), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathfrak{a})=V(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 is irreducible if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=I(Y)$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $fg\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\subseteq V(fg)=V(f)\cup V(g).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is irreducbile, either 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq V(f)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq V(g)$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 Then by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{Y}=V(\mathfrak{p})=V(I(\{\mathfrak{p}\})=\overline{\{\mathfrak{p}\}}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 is the closure of the irreducible set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

 and therefore irreducible.
 This implies that the dense subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is also irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that for arbitrary irreducible subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 the prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I(Y)$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 But this is clearly true if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is closed, or more generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is locally closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\mapsto V(\mathfrak{p})=\overline{\{\mathfrak{p}\}}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection from 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 onto the set of closed irreducible subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 Via this bijection, the minimal prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 correspond to the irreducible components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn2.8}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
closed 
\series default
if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

 is closed,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say that a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
generic point 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\{\eta\}}=X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 be two points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
generization 
\series default
or that 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
specialization 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in\overline{\{x\}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
maximal point 
\series default
if its closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\{x\}}$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible component of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is generic if and only if it is a generization of every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 As the closure of an irreducible set is again irreducible, the existence
 of a generic point implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 is the spectrum of a ring, the notions introduced in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defn2.8})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 have the following algebraic meaning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is closed if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 is a generic point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimal prime ideal.
 This exists if and only if the nilradical of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a generization of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is a specialization of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{x'}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is a maximal point if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a minimal prime ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 defines a contravariant functor from the category of rings to the category
 of topological spaces.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism of rings.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of.
 Therefore we obtain a map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi=\mathrm{Spec}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathfrak{q})=\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

.
 The following proposition will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a continuous map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{V}(S))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi(S))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{D}(S))=\mathrm{D}(\varphi(S))$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))}=\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:We-have-"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a closed map in this case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathfrak{q}\in(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{V}(S)) & \iff(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)(\mathfrak{q})\in\mathrm{V}(S)\\
 & \iff\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})\in\mathrm{V}(S)\\
 & \iff\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})\supseteq S\\
 & \iff\mathfrak{q}\supseteq\varphi(S)\\
 & \iff\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\varphi(S)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{V}(S))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi(S))$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{D}(S)) & =(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}((\mathrm{V}(S))^{c})\\
 & =((^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi)^{-1}(\mathrm{V}(S)))^{c}\\
 & =(\mathrm{V}(\varphi(S))^{c}\\
 & =\mathrm{D}(\varphi(S)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))} & =\mathrm{VI}(^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})))\\
 & =\mathrm{VI}(\{^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathfrak{q})\mid\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\})\\
 & =\mathrm{VI}(\{\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})\mid\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})\})\\
 & =\mathrm{V}\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})}\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})\right)\\
 & =\mathrm{V}\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\bigcap_{\mathfrak{q}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b})}\mathfrak{q}\right)\right)\\
 & =\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\sqrt{\mathfrak{b}}))\\
 & =\mathrm{V}\left(\sqrt{\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b})}\right)\\
 & =\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The proposition shows in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}(\psi\circ\varphi)=^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi\circ^{\mathrm{a}}\psi$
\end_inset

 for any ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon B\to C$
\end_inset

, we obtain a contravariant functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 from the category of rings to the category of topological spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{a}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is dominant (i.e.
 its image is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

) if and only if every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We apply 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:dom})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{enu:We-have-})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop2.12}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 be a surjective homomorphism of rings with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,B\to\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

 onto the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a multiplicative subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to S^{-1}A=:B$
\end_inset

 be the canonical homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{S}\to\{\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,A\mid\mathfrak{p}\cap S=\emptyset\}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{S}$
\end_inset

 onto the subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 consisting of prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\cap S=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 We first check that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}'$
\end_inset

 be two distinct prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q}')\neq\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(\mathfrak{p}))$
\end_inset

 which will establish 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 being surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

First, to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a),\varphi(a')\in B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)\varphi(a')\in\mathfrak{\varphi}(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a')\notin\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in A$
\end_inset

 (every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a'\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)\varphi(a')=\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

, or in other words, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $aa'-x\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $aa'\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $a'\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)\in\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 Next we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(\mathfrak{p}))=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(\mathfrak{p}))\supseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(\mathfrak{p}))$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)\in\varphi(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)=\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a-x\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have the reverse inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(\mathfrak{p}))\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a continuous bijection.
 To see that it is a homeomorphism, we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 maps closed sets to closed sets.
 To see this, note that a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 contains an ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if and only if the prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 contains the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi(\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{b}))=\mathrm{V}(\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{b}))\cap\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism onto its image.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Left as an exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathrm{red}}$
\end_inset

 be the reduced ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 obtained by quotienting out all nilpotent elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon A\to A_{\mathrm{red}}$
\end_inset

 be the quotient homomorphism.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\pi$
\end_inset

 induces a homeomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A\cong\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{\mathrm{red}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that the set of all nilpotent elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\sqrt{0})=\mathrm{V(}0)=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, the corrollary follows immediately from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows that the passage from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 cuts out all prime ideals except those contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The passage from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 cuts out all prime ideals except those containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then by localizing with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and then taking the quotient modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 (in either order as these operations commute) we obtain a ring whose prime
 ideals are those prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that lie between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa(\mathfrak{p}):=A_{\mathfrak{p}}\slash\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}=\mathrm{Frac}(A\slash\mathfrak{p}),
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\series bold
residue field 
\series default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectrum of a Ring as a Locally Ringed Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 We will now endow the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a locally ringed space and obtain a functor 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mapsto\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 from the category of rings to the category of locally ringed spaces which
 we will show to be fully faithful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Structure Sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that the principal open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We will define a presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on this basis and then prove that the sheaf axioms are satisfied.
 The basic idea is this: looking back at the analogy with prevarieties,
 we certainly want to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X)=A$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A$
\end_inset

, we consider the localization 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{f}\colon A\to A_{f}$
\end_inset

 the canonical ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto a/1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{prop2.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\iota_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a homeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{f}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 So it seems reasonable to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))=A_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us check that this is a sensible definition: we must check that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}=A_{g}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

, define restriction maps, and check that the sheaf axioms are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\in\langle g\rangle$
\end_inset

 or, equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $g/1\in(A_{f})^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we obtain a unique ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\colon A_{g}\to A_{f}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\circ\iota_{g}=\iota_{f}$
\end_inset

 by the universal mapping property of localization.
 Whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(g)\subseteq\mathrm{D}(h)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}\circ\rho_{g,h}=\rho_{f,h}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=\mathrm{D}(g)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, which we use to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we can define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f)):=A_{f}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and obtain a presheaf of rings on the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathrm{D}(f)\mid f\in A\}$
\end_inset

 for the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 The restriction maps are the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{f,g}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the sheaf of rings on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 again by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 For all points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X=\text{Spec }A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X,x}=\mathrm{colim}_{\mathrm{D}(f)\ni x}\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))=\mathrm{colim}_{f\notin\mathfrak{p}_{x}}A_{f}=A_{\mathfrak{p}_{x}}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 is a locally ringed space.
 We will often simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 instaed of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{Spec}\,A,\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,A})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 be a principal open set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have to show the following two properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f_{i}))$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i}f_{j})}=s_{j}|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i}f_{j})}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(f))$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{\mathrm{D}(f_{i})}=s_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Restricting the presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)$
\end_inset

 and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

 if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=X$
\end_inset

 to ease the notation.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i\in I}\mathrm{D}(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f_{i}\mid i\in I\rangle=A$
\end_inset

 (indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=A$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=A$
\end_inset

).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f_{i})=\mathrm{D}(f_{i}^{n})$
\end_inset

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 there exists elements 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

 (depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\in I}b_{i}f_{i}^{n}=1.\label{eq:2.10.3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of 1: let 
\begin_inset Formula $s=a\in A$
\end_inset

 be such that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is zero for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite, there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

, independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{n}a=0$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:2.10.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\left(\sum_{i\in I}b_{i}f_{i}^{n}\right)a=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of 2: as 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finite, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}=a_{i}/f_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, the images of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}/f_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}/f_{j}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}f_{j}}$
\end_inset

 are equal for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ge1$
\end_inset

 (which again we can choose independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{i}f_{j})^{m}(f_{j}^{n}a_{i}-f_{i}^{n}a_{j})=0.
\]

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{m}a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $n+m$
\end_inset

 (which does not change 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

), we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}^{n}a_{i}=f_{i}^{n}a_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s:=\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}a_{j}\in A,
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the elements in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:2.10.3})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{i}^{n}s & =f_{i}^{n}\left(\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}a_{j}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}(f_{i}^{n}a_{j})\\
 & =\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}(f_{j}^{n}a_{i})\\
 & =\left(\sum_{j\in I}b_{j}f_{j}^{n}\right)a_{i}\\
 & =a_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have just proved that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\longrightarrow A\longrightarrow\bigoplus_{i\in I}A_{f_{i}}\longrightarrow\bigoplus_{i,j\in I}A_{f_{i}f_{j}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Viewing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 as Functors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A locally ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
affine scheme
\series default
, if there exists a commutative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 as locally ringed spaces.
 A 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
of affine schemes is a morphism of locally ringed spaces.
 We obtain the category of affine schemes which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Aff}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Ring}$
\end_inset

 denotes the category of commutative rings and ring homomorphisms.
 We view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}$
\end_inset

 as a contravariant functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Ring}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Aff}$
\end_inset

 which takes a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to the affine scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A=X$
\end_inset

 and which takes a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 to the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 of locally ringed spaces where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, where the underlying continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathfrak{q})=\varphi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and where the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: given a principal open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(s)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A$
\end_inset

), we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\mathrm{D}(s)}^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}(\mathrm{D}(s))\to\mathcal{O}_{Y}(\mathrm{D}(\phi(s)))
\]

\end_inset

to be the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{s}\colon A_{s}\to B_{\phi(s)}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the localization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with respect to the multiplicative set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{s^{n}\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\mathrm{D}(s)}^{\flat}(\alpha)=f_{\mathrm{D}(s)}^{\flat}(a/s^{n})=\phi(a)/\phi(s)^{n}:=\phi(\alpha)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=a/s^{n}\in A_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 As the principal open subsets form a basis of the topology, this defines
 a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves of rings.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(s_{1},s_{2})=\mathrm{D}(s_{1})\cup\mathrm{D}(s_{2})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U)=\mathrm{D}(\phi(s_{1}),\phi(s_{2}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U):=A_{s_{1}}\times_{A_{s_{1}s_{2}}}A_{s_{2}}\xrightarrow{f_{U}^{\flat}}B_{\phi(s_{1})}\times_{B_{\phi(s_{1}s_{2})}}B_{\phi(s_{2})}:=\mathcal{O}_{Y}(f^{-1}(U))
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\mapsto(\phi(\alpha_{1}),\phi(\alpha_{2}))$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathfrak{p}=f(\mathfrak{q})=\phi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{y}^{\#}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the local ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathfrak{q}}\colon A_{\mathfrak{p}}\to B_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 is local, we get an embedding of residue fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\mathfrak{q}}\colon\kappa(\mathfrak{p})\to\kappa(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, we view 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 as a contravariant functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Aff}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Ring}$
\end_inset

 which takes the affine scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to the commutative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(X):=A$
\end_inset

 and which takes a morphism of affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,f^{\flat})\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 to the homomorphism of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon B\to A$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=\mathcal{O}_{Y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=f_{Y}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremantiequivspecgamma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 define an anti-equivalence between the category of rings and the category
 of affine schemes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}$
\end_inset

 is by definition essentially surjective.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\circ\mathrm{Spec}$
\end_inset

 is clearly isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\mathbf{Ring}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it suffices to show that for any two rings 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}_{
\backslash
mathbf{Ring}}(A,B) 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
mathrm{Spec} ", shift left = 1] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom}_{
\backslash
mathbf{Aff}}(
\backslash
mathrm{Spec}
\backslash
 B,
\backslash
mathrm{Spec}
\backslash
 A ) 
\backslash
arrow[l, " 
\backslash
Gamma ", shift left=1] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are mutually inverse bijections.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,B\to\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of affine schemes and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\Gamma(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi=f$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}_{y}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 corresponding to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{y}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 is the unique ring homomorphism which makes the diagram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center} 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} A 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
phi 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[d] & B 
\backslash
arrow[d] 
\backslash

\backslash
 A_{
\backslash
mathfrak{p}_{f(y) }} 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

f^{
\backslash
# } _{y}
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, swap] & B_{
\backslash
mathfrak{q}_y } 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
commutative.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}(\mathfrak{q}_{y})\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{f(y)}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{y}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 is local, we have equality.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi=f$
\end_inset

 as continuous maps.
 Now the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi^{\#}$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi_{y}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 makes the diagram above commutative as well and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi_{y}^{\#}=f_{y}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\phi^{\#}=f^{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
scheme 
\series default
is a locally ringed spaced 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 which admits an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that all locally ringed spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=(U_{i},\mathcal{O}_{X|U_{i}})$
\end_inset

 are affine schemes.
 A 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
of schemes is
\series bold
 
\series default
a morphism of locally ringed spaces.
 We obtain a category of schemes which we will denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sch}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To simplify notation in what follows, we denote a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{O}_{X})$
\end_inset

 simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then it is understood that the corresponding structure sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Fix a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The category of of 
\series bold
schemes over 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\series default
(or 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\series bold
-schemes
\series default
), denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sch}_{S}$
\end_inset

 is the category whose objects are morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to S$
\end_inset

 of schemes, and whose morphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to S$
\end_inset

 are the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 of schemes with the property that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} X 
\backslash
arrow[rr] 
\backslash
arrow[dr] && Y 
\backslash
arrow[dl] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & S 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to S$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
structural morphism 
\series default
of the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (and often is silently omitted from the notation).
 The scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is also sometimes called the 
\series bold
base scheme
\series default
.
 In the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 is an affine scheme, one also speaks about 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-schemes 
\series default
or 
\series bold
schemes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\series default
instead.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 we denote the set of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to Y$
\end_inset

 in the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-schemes by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 (or by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 is affine).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Open subschemes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that there is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\diamond}\colon\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})$
\end_inset

 which is defined as follows: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open, set 
\begin_inset Formula $U=f^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 and define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{V}^{\diamond}(t)=[V,t]_{f(U)}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{G}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that this map makes sense because 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq f(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore it is easy to check that the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{V}^{\diamond}$
\end_inset

 ranging over all 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open constitute a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\diamond}\colon\mathcal{G}\to f_{*}(f^{-1}\mathcal{G})$
\end_inset

 of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Let us see what this morphism looks like in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a scheme and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon U\to X$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map from an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 First of all, recall that we define a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}:=\iota^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is the sheafification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{+}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 is an open map, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota^{+}\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U'\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 open.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{+}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is already a sheaf.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}=\iota^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X}=\iota^{+}\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

, and it is very easy to describe what the sections in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(U')$
\end_inset

 look like (namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(U')=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U')$
\end_inset

).
 Also note that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(V)=\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(U\cap V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V).
\]

\end_inset

Taking this altogether, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{*}(\iota^{-1}\mathcal{O}_{X})(V)=\iota_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X|U}(V)=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U\cap V)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open, and the corresponding morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{\diamond}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\iota_{*}\mathcal{O}_{X|U}$
\end_inset

 has a simple description: it is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{V}^{\diamond}(t)=t|_{U\cap V}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The locally ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a scheme.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 an 
\series bold
open subscheme 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an affine scheme, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
affine open subscheme
\series default
.
 The affine open subschemes of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 form a basis of the topology.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is an affine scheme, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(f)=(\mathrm{D}(f),\mathcal{O}_{X|\mathrm{D}(f)})$
\end_inset

 is an affine scheme with coordinate ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Subschemes of this form are called 
\series bold
principally open
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first work locally: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is an affine scheme and that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an open subset, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 .
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a scheme.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})=\bigcup_{t\in\mathfrak{a}}\mathrm{D}(t)=\bigcup_{t\in\mathfrak{a}}\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be covered by affine schemes and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we work globally: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary scheme and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is an open subset.
 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(U,\mathcal{O}_{X|U})$
\end_inset

 is a scheme.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}U_{i}=X$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i}U\cap U_{i}=U$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 itself is a scheme.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{j}V_{i,j}=U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap U_{i}$
\end_inset

 by affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i,j}V_{i,j}=U$
\end_inset

 is an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by affine schemes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open, then we think of it as an open subscheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Whenever we speak about a morphism of schemes from 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we are just talking about the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(\iota,\iota^{\diamond})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota^{\diamond}$
\end_inset

 was defined above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Morphisms into Affine Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Morphisms of an arbitrary scheme (or even an arbitrary locally ringed space)
 into an affine scheme are easy to understand, as the following proposition
 shows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a locally ringed space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 be an affine scheme, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\Gamma(Y,\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

.
 Then the natural map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sch}}(Y,X)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Ring}}(A,B)
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f_{Y}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will only prove this in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a scheme.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\bigcup_{i}V_{i}$
\end_inset

 be an affine open covering and set 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}=\Gamma(V_{i},\mathcal{O}_{Y})$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 the natural map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Sch}}(V_{i},X)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathbf{Ring}}(A,B_{i})
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{i}}\mapsto f_{U_{i}}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremantiequivspecgamma})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For an affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,j}\subseteq V_{i}\cap V_{j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,j}=\mathrm{Spec}\,B_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, the diagram 
\begin_inset Branch tikzcd
inverted 0
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom} (V_i , X) 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom} (A , B_i ) 
\backslash
arrow[d] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
mathrm{Hom} (V_{i,j} , X) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Hom} (A , B_{i,j} )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 is commutative, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(-)$
\end_inset

 is functorial.
 The assertion now follows from the following general proposition about
 gluing of morphisms.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Gluing of morphisms) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be locally ringed spaces.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 open, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}(V,X)$
\end_inset

 be the set of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to X$
\end_inset

 of locally ringed spaces.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $V\mapsto\mathrm{Hom}(V,X)$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of sets on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basic properties of Schemes and Morphism of Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Topological Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
connected
\series default
, if the underlying topological space is connected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
quasi-compact
\series default
, if the underlying topological space is quasi-compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
irreducible
\series default
, if the underlying topological space is irreducible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
injective
\series default
, 
\series bold
surjective
\series default
, or 
\series bold
bijective
\series default
, if the continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 of the underlying topological spaces has this property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
open
\series default
, 
\series bold
closed
\series default
, or a 
\series bold
homeomorphism
\series default
, if the continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 of the underlying topological spaces has this property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
 Recall that the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 of sheaves on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is injective, surjective, or bijective, if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{y}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X,x}\to\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}$
\end_inset

 is a surjective homomorphism of local rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=f(y)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjective, then it need not be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 For a simple example of this, consider the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,L\to\mathrm{Spec}\,K$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a finite extension of fields with 
\begin_inset Formula $K\neq L$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Surjective morphisms of schemes need not be 
\emph on
epimorphisms.
 
\emph default
Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk[\varepsilon]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\varepsilon]=\Bbbk[t]\slash\langle t^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be the closed immersion of the simple point to the double point corresponding
 to the homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras sending 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\mapsto0$
\end_inset

.
 Also let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 be the morphisms corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1},\varphi_{2}\colon\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\to\Bbbk[\varepsilon]$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(\varepsilon)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(\varepsilon)=\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\circ f=f_{2}\circ f$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\neq f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Similarly, epimorphisms of schemes need not be surjetive morphisms.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is an algebraically closed field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be the discrete scheme obtained form the disjoint union (=coproduct) of
 all the closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The natural morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 has image 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 minus the generic point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and is thus not surjective.
 However one can show that this is an epimorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Noetherian Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally noetherian
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 admits an affine open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup U_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, such that all of the affine coordinate rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U_{i})=A_{i}$
\end_inset

 are noetherian.
 If in addition 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
noetherian
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that since any localization of a noetherian ring is noetherian again,
 we see that eveyr locally noetherian scheme has a basis of its topology
 consisting of noetherian affine open subschemes.
 We also see that the local rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 of a locally noetherian scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 are all noetherian local rings.
 However the converse need not be true: even for affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

, it need not be the case that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is noetherian for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is noetherian.
 Equivalently, there exists a commutative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is noetherian for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 itself is not noetherian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Separation Axioms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-scheme.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\Delta_{X\slash S}$
\end_inset

 to be the diagonal morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

.
 This is the unique morphism of schemes such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}\circ\Delta=1_{X}=\pi_{2}\circ\Delta,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{X}\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 is the identity map on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1},\pi_{2}\colon X\times_{S}X\to X$
\end_inset

 are the canonical projections of the fiber product.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

 is covered by affine opens of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V\times_{U}V'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V,V'$
\end_inset

 are affine opens of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an affine open of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V')\subseteq U$
\end_inset

.
 One can show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\times_{U}V'=\pi_{1}^{-1}(V)\cap\pi_{2}^{-1}(V')=V\times_{S}V',
\]

\end_inset

by showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}^{-1}(V)\cap\pi_{2}^{-1}(V')$
\end_inset

 satisfies the universal mapping property of the fiber product.
 In particular, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta^{-1}(V\times_{U}V') & =\Delta^{-1}((\pi_{1}^{-1}(V)\cap\pi_{2}^{-1}(V'))\\
 & =(\Delta^{-1}\circ\pi_{1}^{-1})(V)\cap(\Delta^{-1}\circ\pi_{2}^{-1})(V')\\
 & =(\pi_{1}\circ\Delta)^{-1}(V)\cap(\pi_{2}\circ\Delta)^{-1}(V')\\
 & =V\cap V'.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The diagonal morphism of a morphism between affines is a closed immersion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra, let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 The diagonal morphism of the the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\colon Y\to Y\times_{X}Y$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the multiplication map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\colon B\otimes_{A}B\to B$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(b_{1}\otimes b_{2})=b_{1}b_{2}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},b_{2}\in B$
\end_inset

.
 This map is surjective since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is unital, so 
\begin_inset Formula $B\cong(B\otimes_{A}B)\slash I$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B\otimes_{A}B$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is a closed immersion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-scheme.
 Then the diagonal morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash S}$
\end_inset

 is an immersion.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is affine open and maps into 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 affine open, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V\times_{U}V$
\end_inset

 is affine open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be the open subscheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

 which is the union of these affine opens 
\begin_inset Formula $V\times_{U}V$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash S}$
\end_inset

 factors as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\to W\hookrightarrow X\times_{S}X,
\]

\end_inset

where clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $W\hookrightarrow X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

 is an open immersion.
 Thus it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to W$
\end_inset

 is a closed immersion.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is covered by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V\times_{U}V\}$
\end_inset

, it is enough to show that each morphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\Delta_{X\slash S}^{-1}(V\times_{U}V)\to V\times_{U}V
\]

\end_inset

is a closed immersion.
 However this is the affine case which we've already shown.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to S$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separated 
\series default
if the diagonal morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash S}$
\end_inset

 is a closed immersion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
quasi-separated 
\series default
if the diagonal morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash S}$
\end_inset

 is a quasi-compact morphism.
 In other words, for every affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

, the inverse image 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash S}^{-1}(W)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 In particular, for every affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $V\times_{U}V'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V,V'$
\end_inset

 are affine opens of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an affine open of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V')\subseteq U$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\cap V'=\Delta_{X\slash S}^{-1}(V\times_{U}V')\subseteq X
\]

\end_inset

is quasi-compact.
 Note that not every affine open of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times_{S}X$
\end_inset

 is of this form though.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is (
\series bold
quasi
\series default
)-
\series bold
separated 
\series default
if the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is (quasi)-separated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a closed map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is local on the target.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=f^{-1}(f(E))$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 be an open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}=f^{-1}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=f|_{V_{i}}$
\end_inset

 viewed as a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\text{ is closed} & \iff f(E)\text{ is closed for all such }E\\
 & \iff X\backslash f(E)\text{ is open}\\
 & \iff U_{i}\backslash f(E)\text{ is open for all }i\\
 & \iff U_{i}\backslash f_{i}(V_{i}\cap E)\text{ is open for all }i\\
 & \iff f_{i}\text{ is closed for all }i.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finiteness Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is of 
\series bold
finite type 
\series default
(
\series bold
presentation
\series default
) at 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 if there exists an affine open neighbourhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,B=V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and an affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A=U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 such that the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the morphism of affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}\colon V\to U$
\end_inset

 is of finite type (presentation), meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 the structure of a finitely generated (presented) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra, that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\simeq A[t_{1},\dots,t_{n}]\slash I=A[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash I
\]

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebras for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A[\boldsymbol{t}]$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is finitely finitely generated).
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\rho_{f^{-1}(U),V}\circ f_{U}^{\flat}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{U}^{\flat}\colon A=\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)\to\mathcal{O}_{Y}(f^{-1}(U))\quad\text{and}\quad\rho_{f^{-1}(U),V}\colon\mathcal{O}_{Y}(f^{-1}(U))\to\mathcal{O}_{Y}(V)=B.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
locally of finite type 
\series default
(
\series bold
presentation)
\series default
 if it is of finite type (presentation) at every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is of 
\series bold
finite type 
\series default
if it is locally of finite type and quasi-compact.
 Equivalenty, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 there is an open affine neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{Spec}\,A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a finite covering
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(U)=\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}V_{i}
\]

\end_inset

of its inverse image by affine open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}=\mathrm{Spec}\,B_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}\colon A\to B_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the morphism of affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V_{i}}\colon V_{i}\to U$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

 the structure of a finitely generated (presented) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is of 
\series bold
finite presentation 
\series default
if it is locally of finite presentation, quasi-compact, 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 quasi-separated.
 Later we will characterize morphisms which are locally of fintie presentation
 as those morphisms such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{colim}\,\mathrm{Mor}_{X}(Z_{i},Y)=\mathrm{Mor}_{X}(\mathrm{lim}\,Z_{i},Y),
\]

\end_inset

for any directed system of affine 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
finite 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 there is an open affine neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{Spec}\,A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that the inverse image 
\begin_inset Formula $V:=f^{-1}(U)=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

 is itself affine and the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the morphism of affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}\colon V\to U$
\end_inset

, gives 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 the structure of a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=A[t]\slash\pi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in A[t]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be the morphism of affine schemes which corresponds to the morphism of
 rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if the leading coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a finite morphism of schemes.
 Then we have the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The fibers of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The underlying continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and choose an affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U):=V=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

 is affine where the corresponding map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 the structure of a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Properness and Separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced Schemes, Integral Schemes, and Function Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
reduced 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is reduced (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 has no nonzero nilpotents) for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
integral 
\series default
if it is reduced and irreducible (meaning the underlying topological space
 is irreducible).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is reduced if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 is reduced for each open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is integral if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain for each nonempty open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is integral, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 is reduced for each open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be open and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 implies there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{x\in U}U_{x}=U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{U_{x}}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

.
 But then this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

 by the sheaf property.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 is reduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is integral.
 Because all open subschemes of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are integral too, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathcal{O}(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(f)\cup\mathrm{V}(g)$
\end_inset

, so by irreducibility, we either have 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this can be checked locally on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, so we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is affine.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(f)=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 says that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathrm{N}(A)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(A)$
\end_inset

 is the nilradical of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is reduced, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(A)=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Convsersely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(U)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 If there existed nonempty affine opens 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1},U_{2}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 with empty intersection, then the sheaf axioms imply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}(U_{1}\cup U_{2})=\mathcal{O}(U_{1})\times\mathcal{O}(U_{2}),
\]

\end_inset

but the product on the righthand side obviously contains zerodivisors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 This follows from part 2 since the localization of an integral domain is
 an integral domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An affine scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is integral if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 The generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then corresponds to the zero ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is the localization 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\langle0\rangle}$
\end_inset

, which is just the field of fractions of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be an integral scheme and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in X$
\end_inset

 be its generic point.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is a field, which is called the 
\series bold
function field 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be an integral scheme with generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 be its function field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty open affine subscheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)=\mathrm{Frac}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)=\mathrm{Frac}\,\mathcal{O}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be nonempty opens.
 Then the maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(V)\to\mathcal{O}(U)\to K(X)$
\end_inset

 are injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every nonempty open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and for every open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\bigcup_{i}U_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}(U)=\bigcap_{i}\mathcal{O}(U_{i})=\bigcap_{x\in U}\mathcal{O}_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of integral schemes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{Y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{X}$
\end_inset

 be the generic points of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 respectively and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{X}=f(y)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then we obtain an induced inclusion map of function fields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(X):=\mathcal{O}_{X,\eta_{X}}\xrightarrow{f_{y}^{\#}}\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}\hookrightarrow K(Y),
\]

\end_inset

where the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y,y}\hookrightarrow K(Y)$
\end_inset

 is the canonical inclusion map.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Schemes of Finite Type over a Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-scheme locally of finite type, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following assertions are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}\slash\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}\slash\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is algebraic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Subschemes and Immersions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A closed subscheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 (let 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon Z\to X$
\end_inset

 be the inclusion) and a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\mathcal{O}_{Z})$
\end_inset

 is a scheme and such that the sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}\slash\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

-ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon Z\to X$
\end_inset

 of schemes is called a 
\series bold
closed immersion 
\series default
if the underlying continuous map is a homeomorphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and a closed subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and the sheaf homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}_{X}\to i_{*}\mathcal{O}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gluing of Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A gluing datum of schemes consists of the following data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
an index set 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 and open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i,j}\subseteq U_{i}$
\end_inset

 (viewed as an open subscheme) where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i,i}=U_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ij}\colon U_{j,i}\to U_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 of schemes such that the following cocycle condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{ij}\varphi_{jk}=\varphi_{ik}
\]

\end_inset

 holds on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i,j}\cap U_{i,k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote such a gluing datum by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}=(I,\{U_{i}\},\{U_{i,j}\},\{\varphi_{i,j}\})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the cocycle condition we implicitly assume that in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{jk}(U_{k,i}\cap U_{k,j})\subseteq U_{j,i}$
\end_inset

 (otherwise the composition is meaningless).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j=k$
\end_inset

, the cocycle condition implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i,i}=1_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $i=k$
\end_inset

, the cocycle condition implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i,j}^{-1}=\varphi_{j,i}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ij}$
\end_inset

 restricts to an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{j,i}\cap U_{j,k}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i,j}\cap U_{i,k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}=(I,\{U_{i}\},\{U_{i,j}\},\{\varphi_{i,j}\})$
\end_inset

 be a gluing datum of schemes.
 Then there exists a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbf{G}}$
\end_inset

 together with morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\colon U_{i}\to X$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 yields an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 onto an open subscheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbf{G}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}\varphi_{ij}=\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbf{G}}=\bigcup_{i\in I}\psi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(U_{i})\cap\psi_{j}(U_{j})=\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})=\psi_{j}(U_{j,i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbf{G}}$
\end_inset

 together with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined up to unique isomorphism.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, then we often simplify our ntoation and simply
 write 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbf{G}}$
\end_inset

, and call 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (together with the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

) the scheme obtained from the gluing datum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first step is to define the underlying topological space of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We start with the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $\coprod_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the (underlying topological spaces of the) 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and define an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on it as follows: points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\in U_{j}$
\end_inset

 are said to be equivalent, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\sim x_{j}$
\end_inset

, if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\varphi_{ji}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\sim x_{j}$
\end_inset

, then it is necessary that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in U_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\in U_{j,i}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{i}]$
\end_inset

.
 As a set, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to be the set of equivalence classes,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\coprod_{i\in I}U_{i}\slash\sim.
\]

\end_inset

The natural maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\colon U_{i}\to X$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(x_{i})=[x_{i}]$
\end_inset

, are injective and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})=\psi_{i}(U_{i})\cap\psi_{j}(U_{j})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We equip 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the quotient topology, that is, with the coarsest topology such that
 all 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are continuous.
 That means that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 the preimage 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}^{-1}(V)$
\end_inset

 is open in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})=\psi_{i}(U_{i})\cap\psi_{j}(U_{j})$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To clean our notation in what follows, set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}=\psi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ij}=V_{i}\cap V_{j}=\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain a locally ringed space, we have to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

glue
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the structure sheaves on the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 so as to define a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of rings on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Also for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, we have a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}:=(\psi_{i})_{*}\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

, defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{i}(V)=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(\psi_{i}^{-1}(V))$
\end_inset

 for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 We also have isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{ij}\colon\mathcal{O}_{i}|_{V_{ij}}\to\mathcal{O}_{j}|_{V_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{ij}:=(\psi_{i})_{*}(\varphi_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{ij})_{V}=(\varphi_{ij})_{\psi_{i}^{-1}(V)}$
\end_inset

 for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\psi_{ij}\}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the cocycle condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{jk}\psi_{ij}=\psi_{ik}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propgluingsheaves})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that there exists a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 together with isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}\colon\mathcal{O}_{i}\to\mathcal{O}_{X|U_{i}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}\psi_{ij}=\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely detetrmined up to unique isomorphism by these conditions.
 An explicit description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(V)=\left\{ (s_{i})_{i\in I}\in\prod_{i\in I}\mathcal{O}_{i}(V_{i}\cap V)\mid s_{j}|_{V_{ij}\cap V}=\phi_{ij}(s_{i})|_{V_{ij}\cap V}\text{ for all }i,j\in I.\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{ij}\colon\mathcal{O}_{i}|_{\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})}\to\mathcal{O}_{j}|_{\psi_{i}(U_{i,j})}$
\end_inset

 is defined by from = 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{i})_{*}(\varphi_{ij})\colon\mathcal{O}_{i}\to\mathcal{O}_{j}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined by its sections (and corresponding restriction maps)
 on a basis of the topology.
 It is thus sufficient to define it on these open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 which are contained in one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, and to check that this is well-defined and satisfies the sheaf axioms.
 For each such 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we fix once and for all an 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\psi_{i}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

, and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(\psi^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U_{i}\cap U_{j}$
\end_inset

, then we identify the rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{U_{i}}(\psi_{i}^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{U_{j}}(\psi_{j}^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{U_{i,j}}(U)$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to define restriction maps.
 We obtain a sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X}$
\end_inset

 of rings on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which is independent of our choices.
 Since all the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 are locally ringed spaces, the same is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Furthermore, with this definition the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are morphisms of locally ringed spaces; they identify 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{i}(U_{i}),\mathcal{O}_{X|\psi_{i}(U_{i})})$
\end_inset

.
 Finally all the 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 are schemes by assumption, that is, they are covered, as locally ringed
 spaces, by affine schemes, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a scheme as well.
 By construction, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i\in I}U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
