\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Open immersions are etale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compositions of elale morphisms are etale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Base change of etale is etale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 are etale, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is etale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proj
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a graded ring.
 Recall that the 
\series bold
irrelevant ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the ideal of elements of positive degree
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{+}=\bigoplus_{n\geq1}A_{n}
\]

\end_inset

We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all homogeneous prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which do not contain the irrelevant ideal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Proj}\,A:=\{\mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\text{ is a homogeneous prime ideal of }A\text{ such that }\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq A_{+}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now endow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 with the structure of a topological space.
 For every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{+}(S)$
\end_inset

 (or more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)$
\end_inset

 if context is clear) to be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq S$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{+}(S)$
\end_inset

 (or more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)$
\end_inset

 if context is clear) to be the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V(S)}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is a homogeneous ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest homogeneous ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(S)=\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(S)=\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{A}=\{\mathrm{D}(\mathfrak{a})\mid\mathfrak{a}\text{ is a homogeneous ideal of }A\}.
\]

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{A}$
\end_inset

 is a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 We call this topology the 
\series bold
Zariski topology
\series default
.
 Note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a}_{i})=\mathrm{V}(\sum\mathfrak{a}_{i})$
\end_inset

, we see that every closed set in the Zariski topology has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 for some homogeneous ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which doesn't contain the irrelevant ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A_{+}$
\end_inset

 and express it in terms of its homogeneous components as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=a_{i_{1}}+\cdots+a_{i_{k}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i_{j}}\in A_{i_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq k$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}<\cdots<i_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i_{j}}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently this says
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{V}_{+}(a)=\mathrm{V}_{+}(a_{i_{1}})\cap\cdots\cap\mathrm{V}_{+}(a_{i_{k}})=\mathrm{V}_{+}(a_{i_{1}},\dots,a_{i_{k}}),
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently still
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)=\mathrm{D}_{+}(a_{i_{1}})\cup\cdots\cup\mathrm{D}_{+}(a_{i_{k}})=\mathrm{D}_{+}(a_{i_{1}},\dots,a_{i_{k}}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)\mid a\in A_{+}\text{ is homogeneous}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)\}$
\end_inset

 covers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{a})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

 be two nonempty open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 are nonzero homogeneous ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 strictly contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{+}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{a})\cap\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{b})=\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

, so there exists a homogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{a}\cap\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\notin\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{+}$
\end_inset

 is inclusion-preserving, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)\subseteq\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{a})\cap\mathrm{D}_{+}(\mathfrak{b})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 need not be quasi-compact (whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is always quasi-compact).
 Indeed, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\Bbbk[\{x_{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N}\}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg x_{n}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}_{+}(x_{n})\}$
\end_inset

 is an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 which admits no finite subcover (note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathrm{D}(x_{n})\}$
\end_inset

 is not an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\{x_{n}\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is not the unit ideal).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{I}_{+}(Z):=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\in Z}\mathfrak{p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

 is empty if and only if all elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{+}$
\end_inset

 are nilpotent.
 More generally, for positive-degree homogeneous elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}_{+}(a)\subseteq\bigcup\mathrm{D}_{+}(a_{i})$
\end_inset

 if and only if some power of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 lies in the homogeneous ideal generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We construct a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
which gives it the structure of a scheme.
 For any open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}\,A$
\end_inset

, we define the ring
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{O}_{X}(U)=\{f
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Functor of Points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}=f_{1},\dots,f_{m}$
\end_inset

 be polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{t}]=R[t_{1},\dots,t_{n}]$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 We have a bijection which is natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\boldsymbol{x}\in A^{n}\mid\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}\simeq\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f},A),
\]

\end_inset

where the righthand side is understood to be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and the lefthand side can be thought of as the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\series bold
-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset


\series default
 (over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in A^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 (meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

) , then we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\boldsymbol{x}}\colon R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f}\to A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\boldsymbol{x}}(t_{j})=x_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f}\to A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism, then we get a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{\varphi}\in A^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}^{\varphi}=\varphi(t_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,R[\boldsymbol{t}]\slash\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, then we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\boldsymbol{x}\in A^{n}\mid\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\}\simeq\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(T,X),
\]

\end_inset

where the righthand side is understood to be the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-scheme homomorphisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Again, this bijection is natural in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and hence in 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

).
 Thus it is natural to attach to a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the functor 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}\colon\mathbf{Sch}^{\mathrm{opp}}\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

 which takes a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and and sends it to the set of all scheme homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}(T):=\mathrm{Hom}(T,X)$
\end_inset

, and which takes a morphism of schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon T'\to T$
\end_inset

 and sends it to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}(f)\colon h_{X}(T)\to h_{X}(T')$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}(f)(g)=gf$
\end_inset

.
 We often denote 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}(f)=f^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{X}(T)=X(T)$
\end_inset

 and we 
\begin_inset Formula $X(T)$
\end_inset

 call this set the 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset


\series bold
-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is affine, then we often set 
\begin_inset Formula $X(A):=X(\mathrm{Spec}\,A)$
\end_inset

 and call this set the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\series bold
-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 More generally, we might consider an arbitrary functor 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon\mathbf{Sch}^{\mathrm{opp}}\to\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

geometric object
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and we call 
\begin_inset Formula $F(T)$
\end_inset

 the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset


\series bold
-valued points of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

More generally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a fixed scheme.
 Indead fo the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sch}$
\end_inset

, we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sch}\slash S$
\end_inset

: the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-schemes.
 Again, every 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 provides a functor from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Sch}\slash S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Set}$
\end_inset

, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mapsto\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(T,X):=X_{S}(T)$
\end_inset

 on objects.
 If it is understood that all schemes are considered 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-schemes, then we simplify our notation further by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{S}(T)=X(T)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 is affine, we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{R}(T)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{S}(A)$
\end_inset

 (or even 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{R}(A)$
\end_inset

 if both 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 are affine).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-valued Points of a Scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-rational points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consists of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\iota_{x})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\colon\kappa(x)\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is an extension of fields.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 Recall that this consists of two pieces of data: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First we have the continuous map of underlying topological spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk\to X$
\end_inset

.
 This is simple to describe since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 consists of just one point, thus the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 sends the unique point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 to some point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Next we have the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 as well as the induced local ring homorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 The data of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}\to\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the data of a compatible sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{U}^{\flat})_{x\in U}$
\end_inset

 of ring homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{U}^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}(U)\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 (compatible with restriction) where the sequence ranges over all open neighborh
oods 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and this is equivalent to the data of the induced local ring homomorphism
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we only need to specify what the local ring homomorphism
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 looks like.
 Note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 is local, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(\mathfrak{m}_{x})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

 factors as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}=\iota_{x}\circ\rho_{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\kappa(x)$
\end_inset

 is the canonical quotient map and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\colon\kappa(x)\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is an extension of fields.
 In summary, the local ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\colon\mathcal{O}_{x}\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 as well as the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk}$
\end_inset

 are completely determined once we specify what the extension of fields
 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{x}\colon\kappa(x)\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 looks like.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(\Bbbk)\simeq\{(x,\iota_{x})\mid x\in X\text{ and }\iota_{x}\colon\kappa(x)\to\Bbbk\text{ is a field extension}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-scheme.
 In particular, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 comes equipped with a canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebras and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have a canonical extension of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x)\slash\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-rational points 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are given by the 
\emph on
closed 
\emph default
points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 whose residue field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x)=\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 has no nontrivial open coverings, a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a map into some affine open subscheme 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and such a morphism is determined by a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A\twoheadrightarrow\Bbbk$
\end_inset

, that is, by a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with residue class field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, we may reverse the construction and see that any 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-rational closed point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk\to X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\slash\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 be an elliptic curve viewed as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-scheme.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is defined by the Weierstrass equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}=x^{3}+ax+b,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-scheme.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

-points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 consists of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,v_{x})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-rational point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (hence is closed and has residue class field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk_{x}=\Bbbk$
\end_inset

) and where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}\in\mathrm{T}_{x}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-schemes.
 Then the underlying continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 sends the unique point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 to some point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathfrak{m}_{x}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}(\langle\varepsilon\rangle)=\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}_{x}\simeq\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a closed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Next note that the morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\flat}\colon\mathcal{O}\to\mathcal{O}_{\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle}$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by the local ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}\colon A_{\mathfrak{m}_{x}}\to\Bbbk[\varepsilon]\slash\langle\varepsilon^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}(\mathfrak{m}_{x})\subseteq\langle\varepsilon\rangle$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{x}$
\end_inset

 induces a unique map 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}\colon\mathfrak{m}_{x}\slash\mathfrak{m}_{x}^{2}\to\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Surjectivity Criterion for Morphism of Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A morphism of schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if for every field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X(K)$
\end_inset

 there exists a field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y(L)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(L)(y)=x_{L}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{L}$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 under the map 
\begin_inset Formula $X(K)\to X(L)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a point of the underlying topological space of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\colon\mathrm{Spec}(\kappa(x_{0}))\to X$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding canonical morphism.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,L\to Y$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-valued point of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(L)(y)=x_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in Y$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{0})=x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjective, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X(K)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 be the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 There exists a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in Y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y_{0})=x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the corresponding extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x_{0})\to\kappa(y_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 such that there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x_{0})$
\end_inset

-embeddings of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(y_{0})$
\end_inset

 and of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $L=(\kappa(y_{0})\otimes_{\kappa(x_{0})}K)\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(y_{0})\otimes_{\kappa(x_{0})}K$
\end_inset

 works).
 Then the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $y\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,L\to\mathrm{Spec}(\kappa(y_{0}))\to Y$
\end_inset

 has the desired properties.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjective on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued points for every field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjetive, however the convserse need not hold.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{G}_{m}\to\mathbb{G}_{m}$
\end_inset

 be given on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-valued points
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(S)\colon\mathbb{G}_{m}(S)=\Gamma(S,\mathcal{O}_{S})^{\times}\to\Gamma(S,\mathcal{O}_{S})^{\times}=\mathbb{G}_{m}(S)\qquad x\mapsto x^{k}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(K)$
\end_inset

 is surjective if and only if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th root.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(K)$
\end_inset

 is surjective and the proposition proved above shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 But of course there are fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(K)$
\end_inset

 is not surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fibre Products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 We would like to gain some intuition as to what 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is.
 To this end, let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-valued points 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $X(k)$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the set of all scheme homomoprhisms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,k$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}[\boldsymbol{T}]\slash\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\rangle$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(k)=\{x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in k^{n}\mid f_{1}(x)=\cdots=f_{m}(x)=0\}=\mathrm{V}_{k}(f_{1},\dots,f_{m})
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
One-Dimensional Schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(X,\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty noetherian scheme and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the irreducible components of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The following assertions are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every closed point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim\mathcal{O}_{x}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The closed irreducible subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is of pure dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim X_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call a scheme satisfying these equivalent conditions an 
\series bold
absolute curve
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact, every closed irreducible set contains a closed point
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This shows the equivalence of all assertions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 A 
\series bold
variety 
\series default
is a scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is integral and the stucture morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is spearated and of finite type.
 In particular, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i}\mathrm{Spec}\,A_{i}$
\end_inset

 where each 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is integral and a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 The diagonal morphism of the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{X\slash\Bbbk}\colon X\to X\times_{\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk}X$
\end_inset

.
 Locally this corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\otimes_{\Bbbk}A_{i}\to A_{i}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\otimes a_{i}'\mapsto a_{i}a_{i}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 A 
\series bold
curve 
\series default
is a variety of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and the projective line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 are curves.
 The scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}(\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle f\rangle)$
\end_inset

 is a curve if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Vector Bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 For an 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open we simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{|U}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 be an integer and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 A (geometric) 
\series bold
vector bundle of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\series default
 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that there exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i}U_{i}$
\end_inset

 and isomorphisms of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

-schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\colon V_{|U_{i}}\simeq\mathbb{A}_{U_{i}}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that for any affine open 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathrm{Spec}\,A\subseteq U_{i}\cap U_{j}$
\end_inset

 the automorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\circ c_{j}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{U}^{n}=\mathrm{Spec}\,A[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is a linear automorphism, that is, it is given by an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra automorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A[\boldsymbol{T}]=A[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(T_{i})=\sum_{j}a_{ji}T_{j}$
\end_inset

 for suitable 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Torsors and non-abelian cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a sheaf of groups on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf (of sets) on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 
\series default
or that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\series bold
-sheaf 
\series default
if there is given a morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $G\times T\to T$
\end_inset

 such that for every open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $G(U)\times T(U)\to T(U)$
\end_inset

 is a left action of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G(U)$
\end_inset

 on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-sheaves is a morphism of sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon T\to T'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{U}\colon T(U)\to T'(U)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $G(U)$
\end_inset

-equivariant for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain the category of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-sheaves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\series bold
-torsor 
\series default
(for the Zariski topology) if it satisfies the following two properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The group 
\begin_inset Formula $G(U)$
\end_inset

 acts simply transitively on 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 open.
 Thus for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t,t'\in T(U)$
\end_inset

 distinct, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gt=t'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}=(U_{i})_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $T(U_{i})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One example for a 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsor is the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 itself on which 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts by left multiplication.
 This torsor is called the 
\series bold
trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\series default
-torsor.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsor if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $T(X)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in this case any 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in T(X)$
\end_inset

 yields an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $G(U)\to T(U)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto gt|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{1}(X,G)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of isomorphism classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsors.
 This is a pointed set, where the distinguished element is the isomorphism
 class of the trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsor.
 One can study 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsors for a finer (Grothendieck) topology than the Zariski topology.
 If we wish to stress that we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-torsors for the Zariski topology, then we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Zar}}^{1}(X,G)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-Abelian Cech Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may also give a more elementary description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{1}(X,G)$
\end_inset

 in terms of cocycles which is often advantageous for concrete calculations.
 To ease notation, for two sections 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in G(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in G(V)$
\end_inset

, we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $st\in G(U\cap V)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U\cap V}t|_{U\cap V}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s=t$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $s|_{U\cap V}=t|_{U\cap V}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Fix an open covering 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}=(U_{i})_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
Cech 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-cocycle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 is a tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=(g_{ij})_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}\in G(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$
\end_inset

 such that the cocycle condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{kj}g_{ji}=g_{ki}
\]

\end_inset

holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ii}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=g_{ji}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 Two Cech 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-cocycles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta'$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
cohomologous 
\series default
if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}\in G(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{i}g_{ij}=g_{ij}'h_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flat Morphisms and Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
flat over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{y}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{X,f(y)}$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
flat over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if it is flat over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
flat 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is flat over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 there exists an open affine neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,B=V\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and an open affine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A=U\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(V)\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 such that the ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the morphism of affine schemes 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{V}\colon V\to U$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 into a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea is that flatness is a local property: if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is flat if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

-module for all prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Chow Ring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 The 
\series bold
group of cycles 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(X)$
\end_inset

, is the free abelian group generated by the set of integral subschemes
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(X)$
\end_inset

 is graded by dimension: we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}_{k}(X)$
\end_inset

 for the group of cycles that are formal linear combinations of subvarieties
 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (these are called 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\series bold
-cycles
\series default
), so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Z}(X)=\bigoplus_{k}\mathrm{Z}_{k}(X).
\]

\end_inset

A cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\sum n_{i}Y_{i}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are integral subschemes, is 
\series bold
effective 
\series default
if the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all nonnegative.
 A 
\series bold
divisor 
\series default
(sometimes called a 
\series bold
Weil divisor
\series default
) is an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-cycle on a pure 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional scheme.
 It follows from the definition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(X)=\mathrm{Z}(X_{\mathrm{red}})$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(X)$
\end_inset

 is insensitive to whatever non-reduced structure 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 may have.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To any closed subscheme 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 we associate an effective cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle Y\rangle$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is a subscheme, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1},\dots,Y_{s}$
\end_inset

 are the irreducible components of the reduced scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\mathrm{red}}$
\end_inset

, then, because our schemes are noetherian, each local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 has a finite composition series.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}$
\end_inset

 for its length, which is well-defined by the Jordan-Hölder theorem, we
 define the cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle Y\rangle$
\end_inset

 to be the formal combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum l_{i}\langle Y_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 (the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
multiplicity 
\series default
of the scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 along the irreducible component 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

, and written 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{mult}_{Y_{i}}(Y)$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,\Bbbk[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(x^{2}y,x^{2}z)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\mathrm{red}}=Y_{1}\cup Y_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}=\mathrm{V}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}=\mathrm{V}(y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{1}} & =\Bbbk[x,y,z]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}y,x^{2}z\rangle\\
 & =\Bbbk(y,z)[x]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}\rangle\\
 & =K[x]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}\rangle,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\Bbbk(y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{i}})=\dim_{K}(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{1}})=2$
\end_inset

.
 A similar computation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{2}})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=2Y_{1}+Y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}(x^{2}y,x^{2}z)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\mathrm{red}}=Y_{1}\cup Y_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}=\mathrm{V}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}=\mathrm{V}(y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{1}} & =\mathbb{Z}[x,y,z]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}y,x^{2}z\rangle\\
 & =\mathbb{Q}(y,z)[x]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}\rangle\\
 & =K[x]_{\langle x\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2}\rangle,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}(y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{i}})=\dim_{K}(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{1}})=2$
\end_inset

.
 A similar computation shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\mathcal{O}_{Y,Y_{2}})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=2Y_{1}+Y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,R[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\Bbbk[u,v,w]\slash\langle u^{2}v,u^{2}w\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 is a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}_{R}(x^{2}y,x^{2}z)=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(u^{2}v,u^{2}w,x^{2}y,x^{2}z)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle u^{2}v,u^{2}w,x^{2}y,x^{2}z\rangle=\langle u^{2},x^{2}\rangle\cap\langle u^{2},y,z\rangle\cap\langle v,w,x^{2}\rangle\cap\langle v,w,y,z\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\mathrm{red}}=Y_{1}\cup Y_{2}\cup Y_{3}\cup Y_{4}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Y_{1} & =\mathrm{V}(u,x)\\
Y_{2} & =\mathrm{V}(u,y,z)\\
Y_{3} & =\mathrm{V}(v,w,x)\\
Y_{4} & =\mathrm{V}(v,w,y,z).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=4Y_{1}+2Y_{2}+2Y_{3}+Y_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rational Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Chow group 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the group of cycles on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 modulo 
\series bold
rational equivalence
\series default
.
 Informally, two cycles 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}\in\mathrm{Z}(X)$
\end_inset

 are rationally equivalent if there is a rationally parametrized family
 of cycles interpolating between them, that is, a cycle on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}\times X$
\end_inset

 whose restriction to two fibers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{0}\}\times X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{1}\}\times X$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Here is the formal definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Rat}(X)\subseteq\mathrm{Z}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the subgroup generated by differences of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Phi\cap(\{p_{0}\}\times X)\rangle-\langle\Phi\cap(\{p_{1}\}\times X)\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0},p_{1}\in\mathbb{P}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is a subvariety of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}\times X$
\end_inset

 not contained in any fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p\}\times X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that two cycles are 
\series bold
rationally equivalent 
\series default
if their difference is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Rat}(X)$
\end_inset

, and we say two subschemes are rationally equivalent if their associated
 cycles are rationally equivalent.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{P}_{\boldsymbol{x}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi=\mathrm{V}(t_{0}x_{1}^{2}-t_{1}x_{0}^{2}+t_{1}x_{1}x_{2})\subseteq\mathbb{P}_{\boldsymbol{t}}^{1}\times X.
\]

\end_inset

Then on the one hand we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{(0:1)}=\mathrm{V}(-x_{0}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2})$
\end_inset

 and on the other hand we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{(1:0)}=\mathrm{V}(x_{1}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 induces a rational equivalence between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(-x_{0}^{2}+x_{1}x_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}(x_{1}^{2})=2\mathrm{V}(x_{1})$
\end_inset

 (a hyperbola and a double-line in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 affine chart).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{C}}(y^{2}z-x^{3}-xz^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Let's calculate the divisors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}(y/z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}(x/z)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}((x-z)/z)$
\end_inset

.
 First we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}(y/z)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}z-x^{3}-xz^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives us the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-x(x+iz)(x-iz)=0$
\end_inset

, which has solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $(0:0:1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(-i:0:1)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(i:0:1)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}z-x^{3}-xz^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives us the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-x^{3}=0$
\end_inset

, which has one solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(0:1:0)$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{div}(y/z)=(0:0:1)+(-i:0:1)+(i:0:1)-3(0:1:0).
\]

\end_inset

Next we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}(x/z)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}z-x^{3}-xz^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives us the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}z=0$
\end_inset

, which has solutions which has solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $(0:0:1)$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0:1:0)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{div}(x/z)=2(0:0:1)-2(0:1:0).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{div}((x-z)/z)$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=z$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{2}z-x^{3}-xz^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives us the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $z(y-\sqrt{2}z)(y+\sqrt{2}z)=0$
\end_inset

, which has solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $(0:1:0)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1:\sqrt{2}:1)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1:-\sqrt{2}:1)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{div}((x-z)/z)=(1:\sqrt{2}:1)+(1:-\sqrt{2}:1)-2(0:1:0).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say that subvarieties 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 of a variety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 intersect 
\series bold
transversely 
\series default
at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are all smooth at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the tangent spaces to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 together span the tangent space to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{T}_{p}A+\mathrm{T}_{p}B=\mathrm{T}_{p}X,
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{codim}(\mathrm{T}_{p}A\cap\mathrm{T}_{p}B)=\mathrm{codim}(\mathrm{T}_{p}A)+\mathrm{codim}(\mathrm{T}_{p}B).
\]

\end_inset

We will say that subvarieties 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
generically transverse
\series default
, or that they intersect 
\series bold
generically transversely
\series default
, if they meet transversely at a general point of each component 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

.
 The terminology is justified by the fact that the set of points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are transverse is open.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bezout's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 be two subvarieties of a smooth variety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{codim}(A\cap B)=\mathrm{codim}\,A+\mathrm{codim}\,B.
\]

\end_inset

Then to each irreducible component 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

, we can associate a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{C_{i}}(A,B)$
\end_inset

 in such a way that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[A][B]=\sum m_{C_{i}}(A,B)[C_{i}].
\]

\end_inset

The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{C_{i}}(A,B)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
intersection multiplicity 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(x^{2}+y^{2}-z^{2})=\mathrm{V}(f)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{V}_{\Bbbk}(y^{2}z-x^{3}+xz^{2})=\mathrm{V}(g)$
\end_inset

 where we view 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as subvarieties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{\Bbbk}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 inside the affine open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{D}(z)\simeq\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{2}$
\end_inset

 at the points 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(1,0)$
\end_inset

 as pictured below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}
\backslash
begin{axis}[axis lines = middle, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xlabel = $x$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ylabel = $y$, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xmin=-2,xmax=2,ymin=-2,ymax=2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

xtick={-2,2},ytick={-2,2},
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

axis equal,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=red,samples=100] ({cos(deg(x))},{sin(deg(x))}); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=-1:0,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addplot [color=blue,domain=1:2,samples=100] ({x},{-sqrt(x^3 - x)});
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=below left:$ p $] (w) at (axis
 cs:-1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node[circle, fill=black, inner sep=1pt, label=below right:$ q $] (z) at
 (axis cs:1,0) {$$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{axis}
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle f\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle g\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cap Y$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\otimes_{\Bbbk}B=\Bbbk[x,y]\slash\langle f,g\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}=\langle x+1,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

, thus the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}-u(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1-x$
\end_inset

 (this is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{p}$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}+ux(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}
\]

\end_inset

Then a calculation shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{p}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{p}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2}-u(x+1),y^{2}+ux(x+1)\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{m}}\slash\langle y^{2},(x+1)^{2}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim_{\Bbbk}(A_{p}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{p})=4$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 intersect at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 Next, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(1,0)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{n}=\langle x-1,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk[x,y]$
\end_inset

, thus the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}-\widetilde{u}(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{u}=1+x$
\end_inset

 (this is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{q}$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, the local ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}+\widetilde{u}x(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}
\]

\end_inset

Then a calculation shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{q}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{q}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2}-\widetilde{u}(1-x),y^{2}+\widetilde{u}v(1-x)\rangle_{\mathfrak{n}}=\Bbbk[x,y]_{\mathfrak{n}}\slash\langle y^{2},x-1\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim_{\Bbbk}(A_{q}\otimes_{\Bbbk}B_{q})=2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 intersect at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X,L_{1},L_{2}\subseteq\mathbb{P}_{\Bbbk}^{4}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-planes 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{V}(x+z,y+w)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}=\mathrm{V}(x,y)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}=\mathrm{V}(z,w)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=L_{1}\cup L_{2}=\mathrm{V}(xz,xw,yz,yw)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=[0:0:0:0:1]\in\mathbb{P}_{\Bbbk}^{4}$
\end_inset

 be the point which corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\langle x,y,z,w\rangle\in\Bbbk[x,y,z,w,t]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 only at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{P}^{4},p}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathcal{O}_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathcal{O}_{Y,p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A\otimes_{S}B & =\Bbbk[x,y,z,w]_{\langle x,y,z,w\rangle}\slash\langle x+z,y+w,z^{2},zw,w^{2}\rangle\\
 & \cong\Bbbk[x,y]_{\langle x,y\rangle}\slash\langle x^{2},xy,y^{2}\rangle\\
 & =\Bbbk\oplus\Bbbk\overline{x}\oplus\Bbbk\overline{y}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(A\otimes_{S}B)=3$
\end_inset

.
 However Bezout's Theorem requires the multiplicity to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 as one can see by moving 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to a plane 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 which is transverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (for instance let 
\begin_inset Formula $X'=\mathrm{V}(x+z+t,y+w+t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 at the (necessarily) reduced point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=[0:0:-1:-1:1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 meets 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 at the (necessarily) reduce point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=[-1:-1:0:0:1]$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Weil Conjectures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Statement of the Weil conjectures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a nonsingular projective variety over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{q}$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the variety obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 by extension of scalars of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{q}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{F}}_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}})$
\end_inset

 be the set of points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 with coordinates in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the zeta function of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(X_{0},t)=\exp\left(\sum_{n\geq1}\#X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}})\frac{t^{n}}{n}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the logarithmic derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(X_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{t}\log Z(X_{0},t) & =\sum_{n\geq0}\#X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n+1}})t^{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus the logarithmic derivative of the zeta function is the usual generating
 function for 
\begin_inset Formula $\#X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n+1}})$
\end_inset

.
 The slogan to keep in mind is that the locations of zeros/poles of a meromorphi
c function control the growth rate of the coefficients of the Taylor series
 of its log-derivative.
 Thus the location of the zeros/poles of the zeta function control the growth
 rate of the coefficients of its logarithmic derivative, and the coefficients
 of its logarithmic derivative are just the number of rational points (we
 can make this slogan precise for rational functions).
 Let us now state the Weil conjectures:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Rationalily
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(X_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 is a rational funciton of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(X_{0},t)=\frac{P_{1}(X_{0},t)P_{3}(X_{0},t)\cdots P_{2d-1}(X_{0},t)}{P_{0}(X,t)P_{2}(X_{0},t)\cdots P_{2d}(X_{0},t)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}(X_{0},t)=1-t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2d}(X_{0},t)=1-q^{d}t$
\end_inset

, and each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}(X_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 is an integral polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Functional equation
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(X_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the functional equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(X_{0},q^{-d}t^{-1})=\pm q^{d\chi/2}t^{\chi}Z(X_{0},t),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\sum_{i}(-1)^{i}\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}=\deg P_{i}(X_{0},t)$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is called the Euler characteristic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Betti numbers
\series default
: If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 lifts to a variety 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the (real) Betti numbers of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 considered as a variety over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Riemann hypothesis
\series default
: For 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq2d-1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}(X_{0},t)=\prod_{j=1}^{\beta_{i}}(1-\alpha_{i,j}t)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 are algebraic integers of absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{i/2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Observe that the conjectures are partially suggested by topological statements.
 In particular, (1) is suggested by 
\series bold
Lefschetz fixed-point formula 
\series default
and (2) is suggested by 
\series bold
Poincare duality
\series default
.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 in (2) is the 
\series bold
Euler characteristic 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and (3) suggests the existence of a cohomological theory such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the Betti numbers of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in that theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If the Weil Conjectures holds, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\#X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}})=\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{0}}\alpha_{0,j}^{n}+\cdots+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d}}\alpha_{2d,j}^{n}-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\alpha_{1,j}^{n}-\cdots-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\alpha_{2d-1,j}^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from rationality.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n\geq1}\#X_{0}(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}})t^{n} & =t\frac{d}{dt}\log\left(\frac{P_{1}(t)\cdots P_{2d-1}(t)}{P_{0}(t)\cdots P_{2d}(t)}\right)\\
 & =t\frac{d}{dt}\log\left(\frac{\prod_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}(1-\alpha_{1,j}t)\cdots\prod_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}(1-\alpha_{2d-1,j}t)}{\prod_{j=1}^{\beta_{0}}(1-\alpha_{0,j}t)\cdots\prod_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d}}(1-\alpha_{2d,j}t)}\right)\\
 & =t\frac{d}{dt}\left(\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\log(1-\alpha_{1,j}t)+\cdots+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\log(1-\alpha_{2d-1,j}t)-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{0}}\log(1-\alpha_{0,j}t)-\cdots-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\log(1-\alpha_{2d,j}t)\right)\\
 & =t\left(\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\frac{-\alpha_{1,j}}{1-\alpha_{1,j}t}+\cdots+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\frac{-\alpha_{2d-1,j}}{1-\alpha_{2d-1,j}t}-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\frac{-\alpha_{0,j}}{1-\alpha_{0,j}t}-\cdots-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\frac{-\alpha_{2d,j}}{1-\alpha_{2d,j}t}\right)\\
 & =t\left(-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\alpha_{1,j}^{n}t^{n}-\cdots-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\alpha_{2d-1,j}^{n+1}t^{n}+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{0}}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\alpha_{0,j}^{n+1}t^{n}+\cdots+-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d}}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\alpha_{2d,j}^{n+1}t^{n}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n\geq1}\left(-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{1}}\alpha_{1,j}^{n}-\cdots-\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d-1}}\alpha_{2d-1,j}^{n}+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{0}}\alpha_{0,j}^{n}+\cdots+\sum_{j=1}^{\beta_{2d}}\alpha_{2d,j}^{n}\right)t^{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (1) was proved by Dwork using 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic methods however this will also follow from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{i}$
\end_inset

 being finite-dimensional.
 (2) was proved by Grothendieck (will follow from Poincare duality).
 Finally (3) and (4) were proved by Deligne.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $|X|$
\end_inset

 be the set of all closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z_{X}(t) & =\exp\left(\sum_{n\geq1}\#X(\mathbb{F}_{q^{n}})\frac{t^{n}}{n}\right)\\
 & =\prod_{x\in|X|}\exp\left(t^{\deg x}+\frac{t^{2\deg x}}{2}+\cdots\right)\\
 & =\prod_{x\in|X|}\exp\left(-\log(1-t^{\deg x})\right)\\
 & =\prod_{x\in|X|}\frac{1}{1-t^{\deg x}}\\
 & =\prod_{x\in|X|}(1+t^{\deg x}+t^{2\deg x}+\cdots)\\
 & =\sum_{n\geq0}(\#\text{ of Galois stable subsets of }X(\overline{\mathbb{F}_{q}})\text{ of size }n)t^{n}.\\
 & =\sum_{n\geq0}\#(\mathrm{Sym}^{n}(X)(\mathbb{F}_{q}))t^{n}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here we require there are only finitely many closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in order for the product to converge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a smooth proper curve of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{X}(t)$
\end_inset

 is rational.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}^{n}X\to\mathrm{Pic}^{n}X$
\end_inset

 which sends a divisor 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to the line bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(D)$
\end_inset

.
 The fiber of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(D)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\Gamma(X,\mathcal{O}(D))$
\end_inset

.
 The expected dimension of this projective space is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dim\mathbb{P}\Gamma(X,\mathcal{O}(D))=\deg D-g+\dim\mathrm{H}^{1}(X,\mathcal{O}(D)).
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg D\geq2g-2$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{1}(X,\mathcal{O}(D))=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{1}(X,\mathcal{O}(D))=\mathrm{H}^{0}(X,\mathcal{O}(K-D))^{\lor}=0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $K-D$
\end_inset

 has negative degree.
 So we've just shown that the fibers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sym}^{n}X\to\mathrm{Pic}^{n}X$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\simeq\mathbb{P}^{n-g}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2g-2$
\end_inset

.
 Now without loss of generality, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\mathbb{F}_{q})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Pic}^{n}(X)\simeq\mathrm{Pic}^{n+1}(X)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\#\mathrm{Sym}^{n}(X)(\mathbb{F}_{q})=\#\mathbb{P}^{n-g}(\mathbb{F}_{q})=\#\mathrm{Pic}^{0}(X)(\mathbb{F}_{q})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2g-2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{X}(t)=\text{polynomial }+\sum_{n>2g-2}t^{n}\cdot\#\mathrm{Pic}^{0}(X)(\mathbb{F}_{q})(1+q+q^{2}+\cdots+q^{n-g}).
\]

\end_inset

One can show this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{X}(t)$
\end_inset

 is rational.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a smooth proper curve of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{X}(q^{-1}/t)=\pm q^{(2-2g)/2}t^{2-2g}Z_{X}(t).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This will follow from Serre duality.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Serre) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a smooth projective variety over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[H]\in\mathrm{H}^{2}(X,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 be the cohomology class of a a hyperplane section (the intersection of
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with a hyperplane in projective space) and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 be an endomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}[H]=q[H]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{i}(X,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 all have absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $=q^{i/2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall there is a cup product map 
\begin_inset Formula $L\colon\mathrm{H}(X,\mathbb{C})\to\mathrm{H}(X,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

 which is graded of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\alpha)=\alpha\cup[H]$
\end_inset

.
 The hard Lefschetz theorem states that there is a canonical isomorphism
 (once 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is fixed):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{H}(X,\mathbb{C})\simeq\mathrm{im}\,L\oplus\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{k}$
\end_inset

 decomposes further as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{k}=\bigoplus_{p+q=k}\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{p,q}.
\]

\end_inset

The Hodge index theorem states that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathrm{H}^{k}(X)_{\mathrm{prim}}$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha,\beta\rangle=i^{k}\int_{X}\alpha\wedge\overline{\beta}\wedge[H]^{n-k}
\]

\end_inset

is definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{p,q}$
\end_inset

 (here 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\sqrt{-1})$
\end_inset

.
 The idea is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,L$
\end_inset

 comes from lower degree cohomology (so maybe we can control it inductively)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{k}$
\end_inset

 breaks up into two pieces which has a canonical bilinear form on them which
 is definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (proof of Serre's analogue of RH) We want eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}$
\end_inset

 to have absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{k/2}$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to do this for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H}^{k-2}(X,\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

, then by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 we can assume the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 has absolute value 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{(k-2)/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F^{*}(\alpha\cup[H]) & =F^{*}\alpha\cup F^{*}[H]\\
 & =\lambda\alpha\cup q[H]\\
 & =q\lambda(\alpha\cup[H])
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|q\lambda|=q^{k/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's do it for the primitive part (this includes the base case for
 the induction step).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{prim}}^{p,q}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=k$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{*}$
\end_inset

-eigenvector.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|\lambda|^{2}\langle\alpha,\alpha\rangle & =\langle F^{*}\alpha,F^{*}\alpha\rangle\\
 & =i^{k}\int_{X}F^{*}\alpha\wedge F^{*}\overline{\alpha}\wedge[H]^{n-k}\\
 & =\frac{i^{k}}{q^{n-k}}\int_{X}F^{*}(\alpha\wedge\overline{\alpha}\wedge[H]^{n-k})\\
 & =\frac{i^{k}q^{n}}{q^{n-k}}\int_{X}\alpha\wedge\overline{\alpha}\wedge[H]^{n-k}\\
 & =q^{k}\langle\alpha,\alpha\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By Hodge index theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha,\alpha\rangle\neq0$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda|=q^{k/2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The slogan here is that structures on cohomology are used to prove the RH.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Etale Morphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 be a morphism of schemes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
unramified 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{Y\slash X}^{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, all residue field extensions are separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
etale 
\series default
if it is locally of finite presentation, flat, and unramified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
formally etale 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and consider the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is not unramified.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\Bbbk[t]$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the generic point of 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

.
 Then the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}\to\mathbb{A}_{\Bbbk}^{1}$
\end_inset

 induces the residue field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk(t)\xrightarrow{\simeq}\Bbbk(t^{2})\subseteq\Bbbk(t)$
\end_inset

 ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\to R$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(t)=t^{2}$
\end_inset

, and this induces the local ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
Grothendieck topology 
\series default
on a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is the following data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or each object 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 we have collection of sets of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha}\to X\}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 called 
\series bold
covering families 
\series default
such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(intersecting a cover gives a cover).
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha}\to X\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 the pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\alpha}\times_{X}Y$
\end_inset

 exists, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha}\times_{X}Y\to Y\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(composition of covers are covers) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha}\to X\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha\beta}\to X_{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 are covering families, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X_{\alpha\beta}\to X_{\alpha}\to X\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(isos are covers) if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\xrightarrow{\simeq}X$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, then the singleton set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Y\to X\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
site 
\series default
is a category equipped with a Grothendieck topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\mathrm{Open}(X)$
\end_inset

 where the objects are open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and morphisms are inclusion maps.
 Then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{\alpha}\to U\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\alpha}U_{\alpha}=U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{ét}}$
\end_inset

 to be the category whose objects are étale morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to Y'$
\end_inset

 are the ones which make the corresponding triangle commute.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{\alpha}\colon Y_{\alpha}\to Y\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup\mathrm{im}\,f_{\alpha}=Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{Ét}}$
\end_inset

 to be the category whose objects are all 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-schemes and morphisms are maps over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{\alpha}\colon U_{\alpha}\to U\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family if all 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are étale and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup\mathrm{im}\,f_{\alpha}=U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{zar}}=\mathrm{Open}(X^{\mathrm{top}})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{Zar}}$
\end_inset

 to be the category of all 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

-schemes.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{\alpha}\colon U_{\alpha}\to U\}$
\end_inset

 is a covering family if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are open embeddings and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup\mathrm{im}\,f_{\alpha}=U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a complex analytic space.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{an}\mathrm{ét}}$
\end_inset

 to be the category whose objects are complex analytic spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon Y\to X$
\end_inset

 such that locally on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an analytic isomorphism, and whose morphisms are morphisms over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{url}\mathfrak{prqr}\mathfrak{s}\mathfrak{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Sh}(X_{\mathrm{anét}})\simeq\mathrm{Sh}(X^{\mathrm{top}})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (fppf topology) (faithfully flat, finite presentation) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{fppf}}$
\end_inset

 to be the category whose objects are fppf morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\to X$
\end_inset

 and whose morphisms are morphisms over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Nisnevich, Crystalline, infinitesimal site, arc topology, ...) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any representable functor is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{Ét}}$
\end_inset

 (in fact any representable functor is a sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathrm{Fppf}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

